text: In Singapore, Tea &amp; Boba Stores are a dime a dozen. &#34;NAM DAE MUN&#34; is an improvement of Korea&#39;s century old desserts. They use less sugar, no oil, no salt, and completely rely on the freshness of ingredients for their delicious/healthy treats. This particular location had its Grand Opening this past weekend in the 313@Somerset Singapore Shopping Mall. Their menu includes Teas, Mochi, Cakes, and Ice Jelly with flavors that will blow your mind! I ordered their &#34;Exclusive&#34; Super Fruit Tea which consists of Guava, Dragon Fruit, Strawberry, Lemon, and Lime. Great flavors, just make sure you ask for &#34;Less Ice&#34; to get more tea than ice. They are still working out their kinks at this location (took 2x to make my drink, confusing checkout &amp; pick-up for drink purchase) but by the time you get to try Nam Dae Mun, they will fully deliver!

text: Do you know how hard it is to find a simple cupcake for my daughter&#39;s birthday on Chinese New Year weekend?<br><br>Hard. Even reliable chain 12 cupcakes was closed.<br><br>Having been Â desperate for a birthday dessert, we ended up at Nam Dae Mun since ... it was the only dessert place open on a Sunday afternoon. Judging by David C&#39;s review of this place, it seemed like a safe bet. <br><br>We got the Snow Jade Osmanthus cake in honor of Jade&#39;s name :) as well as the Black Sesame Sticky rice cake. The osmanthus cake wasn&#39;t fresh tasting and was in fact, a bit hard when we dug into it. Upon warming up in the microwave though, it was better. It has the texture of Filipino &#34;puto&#34; if you&#39;ve had that before. I preferred the Black Sesame one and really liked the flavor of it.<br><br>I also tried the signature HERME strawberry drink which came with fresh strawberries and brewed with premium high mountain tea leaves from Taiwan. It was refreshing and not too sweet since I asked for 50% sugar.<br><br>Nam Dae Mun is a breath of fresh air since it offers something different in Singapore. It won&#39;t replace the ubiquitous pearl drinks anytime soon, but it&#39;s a welcome sight for sure.

text: Quite quiet on a Thursday evening. Staff are not really attentive but otherwise friendly and warm when you get their attention. <br><br>Let&#39;s talk about the food!<br>Aglio Olio - I like their version with sun-dried tomatoes thrown in. The pasta by itself is not very tasty but if you put some bits of sun-dried tomato and garlic slices into it, each bite can be quite delightful. This came with 6 juicy plump prawns that went great with the pasta. <br><br>Beef Burger - They asked for the level of &#34;done-ness&#34; and added they only do medium and up. So I clarified that medium rare is no no and waitress repeated &#34;medium and up&#34;. So we opted for medium and when the Burger arrived, we were surprised that the patty is very thick and when we cut into it, it was fairly pink. Strange for a &#39;medium&#39;. <br><br>Smoked Salmon Pizza - Fairly generous with the salmon slices. The pizza was toped with a drizzle of avocado mayo. Interesting combo. My girl liked it enough. <br><br>Pepperoni Pizza - This pizza was really covered with pepperoni slices! With such a generous coverage of meat, how not to be nice? <br><br>Tiramisu - Quite a decent bowl of &#34;yummy&#34;! Really quite a good serving of tiramisu, not too dry nor wet, with loads of cheese. <br><br>Can come back again!
Great coffee in an excellent neighborhood, but not the best working hours.

This has got to be one of the most negative reviews I have had to write in a LONG TIME. Let me first say that this review is not a reflection of the entire cafe chain but this is specifically regarding the outlet located at Spottiswoode Park road. I believe that this is a new establishment with new staff and perhaps new chef? <br><br>So the husband and I were around the area and we dropped in for lunch. We were craving for pastas so we ordered: Banana bread, Pollo (Penne pasta with chicken in avocado guacamole cream), Aglio Olio with prawns and 2 x coffee (iced latte and hot mocha). <br><br>For starters they got our orders wrong, hot mocha became iced mocha, that&#39;s fine but when they served the banana bread... man it tasted like cardboard. It was dry and crumbly. We have definitely tasted much better banana bread. <br><br>Next came the pastas...The Pollo. What&#39;s supposed to be a penne pasta dish, turned out to be spaghetti. Out of courtesy, the chef should first inform the customer that they have run out of penne and if it is ok to replace it with spaghetti? The guest should not have to ask the serving staff why is this spaghetti and not penne, only to find out the kitchen ran out of it. This is NOT proper restaurant etiquette. Not to mention, the pasta dish was bland and overly creamy. <br><br>Next came my Aglio Olio... I was hopeful that this would be ok since it&#39;s really the easiest to make. But no, this dish was a complete disaster! The pasta is NOT completely cooked through and the taste was really bland. After 2 spoonfuls of the pasta, and 5 prawns I could not eat any further. It really was awful. Honestly, I am not sure if the chef tasted the pasta before it left the kitchen. <br><br>The bill came to a whopping 60-ish dollars to which in my husband&#39;s own words was, &#34;a complete waste of money&#34;. Needless to say we will never visit this outlet again (the millennia outlet is ok though). Anyway, if you want to visit this outlet you eat at your own risk. <br><br>Ps. I originally did not even want to give this cafe a 1 star rating, but had to do so in order to post this review.

text: After reading the other reviews here I felt compelled to write on since my experience was nothing like either. I stopped in the first time to get a coffee while staying at a friends down the street. Service was fast and friendly and the coffee was delicious. It was a take away order so that was the extent of my experience. A few days later I stopped in to sit for breakfast and work on the computer. The server was immediately attentive, I received water, and my order was taken. Food came in a very short time. I ordered the poached eggs and avocado and a latte. The latter was exceptional and its then that I learned they source their own beans. As a coffee lover it was outstanding. My poached eggs were on a GIANT bed of mashed avocado&#39;s and tomatoes and two really delicious pieces of freshly baked sourdough bread. I was pleased. If I were in America that would have been about $6 worth of delicious avocados! <br>I sat near the kitchen and watched freshly baked goods come out of the oven for an hour. Everything smelled wonderful. <br><br>I will definitely come back again, probably tomorrow. Pleasant vibe, good music, outdoor seating if you want, happy hour in the afternoon...<br><br>Also, when people complain about price I feel its mostly their own fault. You can easily take a look at the menu and see what your in for, If you don&#39;t like it, go elsewhere. There are just too many options. Its expensive to run a business. I had an amazing breakfast and a 4-shot latte for about US$15. I&#39;m totally fine with that.

text: Loved Kith in Sentosa. So was interested to give Spottiswode a try. Outside was promising. Inside, all the charm of a cafeteria. Three orders--pancakes came up reasonably quickly. But eggs benedict took more than 25 minutes longer to arrive. Bread was rock hard. Bacon also overcooked. Eggs were rubbery. Sauce was barely drizzled on top. The final insult was the price. This was not cheap at all. We will not be back.

text: Perhaps people typically think of ABC for breakfast or lunch, but my husband and I went last night for dinner and had a fabulous experience! Â Weekday evenings (after 5pm), there is a supplemental menu of specials, with drinks, small plates and desserts each for $9. We ordered an appetizer of risotto balls, and two main course salads, along with a glass of wine for me and a beer for him.<br>The food was delicious - the salads fresh and crispy, with high quality ingredients and generous dressings. Â They came with a complimentary bread basket which is always appreciated- especially in Singapore where it&#39;s so rare. Â The risotto balls were served hot and chewy with an ample side of dipping sauce - each item we ordered is something I&#39;d certainly order again.<br>Best of all was the service. Â We were pleasantly surprised to find that the servers offered us a complimentary pear and almond tarte for dessert Â - truly delicious, and a coupon to use for a free item off the $9 small plates/drinks menu next time we come back. Â We were truly impressed with the customer service and will absolutely be back!

text: abc evenings =artisanal bites, craft beers and Â in marketing is doing their job well. Question is, can they deliver?<br><br>Ordered their wagyu beef sliders, Serrano ham &amp; arugula focaccia and truffle fries. All were labeled &#39;bites&#39; And they were all pretty good. The one part of this meal I can&#39;t figure out is what type of dining establishment abc wants to be. The decor needs to look like a cafe /bakery during the day and an evening hangout afterwards. Neither is achieved. I get a bakery out front, wine cooler but not fully stocked, craft beers, also not extensive, coffee grinder and espresso at the counter area. Most places that attempt so much fail miserably. Here we get a &#39;high&#39; pass. Their saving grace is their baked goods. The breads are very well done. And a lovely way to build goodwill with end of day complimentary eclairs.Â <br><br>I will come back as the food is decent but price points are a tad higher than I would like. Now they just have to laser focus on what they want to be serving and more patrons will make this a regular place.

text: I was quite impressed with the look of the place. It had that French feel to it. Quite spacious to start with. I ordered an omelette filled with mushrooms, roasted capsicums and mozzarella cheese, a raspberry chocolate lava cake and a latte. My colleague on the other hand ordered a goat cheese quiche. Â <br><br>I confess, I had given in to my sweet tooth and dug into my dessert first. The lava cake was just scrumptious! Wish I had ordered two of them. The raspberry-laced chocolate just oozed out of the cake wonderfully.<br><br>My omelette though... I was confused if it was supposed to taste like that, or was there a self-service counter to get myself a salt or pepper shaker. Because if there was, I didn&#39;t know. The omelette was so tasteless, that I had to make the most out of the capsicums for some flavour. The whole set was complimented with 2 slices of bread, which were hard. SO hard. For a french boulangerie, that was just unaccepted. Was it stale? I mean what kind of bread actually makes one bite and pull, and yet still refuses to let go? I was really unimpressed with my meal. Fortunately for my colleague, her simple quiche was good.<br><br>With regards to the service though, you have to make your order at the counter itself. And if you ordered a meal like me, you have to bring the tray of food to your table by yourself. Hmm. Didn&#39;t expect that when I stepped in. So many waiters around and yet still self-service?

text: Very nice upscale French style boulangerie, excellent choice in all sorts of bakery, sandwiches, quiches, etc. <br>The size of coffees is a bit small, considering the opposite located McCafe and Coffeebean offer coffees at double the cup size and lower prices.<br><br>The overall ambiance however is very nice and has a classy feel to it, and is inviting to sit down and try out.<br>The bread quality is especially warm and fresh, and a delight to eat. The roasted chicken baguette is a recommendation, do try that. The eggs benedict is also an excellent choice from the menu.

When you have the words &#34;artisan&#34; and &#34;boulangerie&#34; together, immediately expectations are raised. Â Couple that with the wonderful food shots on the ad for this place near the elevator in the mall, you think you&#39;re in for a real treat.<br><br>I had their specialty Wagyu Burger, and truth be told, the patty itself was pretty good, not an overcooked medium, as it tends to be here in Singapore. But considering their baked stuff supposed to be artisanal, the bun was forgettable. Â Not as bad as the baguette I had gotten for my kids though. Â That was hard, very hard. Â I&#39;m tempted to say stale. Â But being a Sunday morning, surely they baked it fresh for the day. Â Just saying.

text: Have a coffee here with friends after cinema, was good choice. Place is nice cozy, coffee is good and their patisserie was good also.

Went for brunch one weekend. I had shakshouka skillet, which consists of eggs in spicy tomato sauce. It tasted one-dimensional, lacking in other herbs and spices. My husband had the big breakfast which was just average. Their bread is really really hard and not chewy. You need to have teeth of steel to eat them properly. The desserts are good but nothing spectacular.

text: We enjoyed a nice meal here. I had a good pasta dish, my son had the chicken schnitzel, and my husband had a rice dish. For dessert we had a chocolate and banana croissant. We definitely plan to eat here again. :)

This place is amazing. It&#39;s bomb in NYC and it it bomb in Singapore. The pancakes and French toast are just soooo good! Place is open till 6 and sometimes 9pm. Breakfast till 6pm!!! Insane! That&#39;s right there gets 5 stars!<br><br>Place is small, but they do a great job of placing tables for everyone. They ended up giving us two tables because we ordered for five people (even though there were only two of us).<br><br>Blueberry Pancakes - Fire! My only complaint is they don&#39;t put the blueberries inside of the batter. Tastes so much better when inside.<br><br>Walnut Banana pancakes with a side of Chocolate Chips - so good. It&#39;s like a cookie<br><br>Brioche French toast - bomb. Great flavor. Nicely cooked.<br><br>Egg White omelette with goat cheese, mushroom, spinach. Delicious.<br><br>NYC to Singapore. Place is a staple.

Pancakes: $18.00 SGD', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Pancakes: $18.00 SGD'}]
text: So long as Clinton Street Baking Company continues to dish up the best pancakes I&#39;ve ever had in my life be they in New York City, Tokyo, or Singapore, I&#39;ll continue to give them five stars.<br><br>Star 1: How were the service and atmosphere?<br><br>This Clinton Street is a cute little one comparable to their Tokyo location, and while it lacked the natural light conducive to food photography (I know I know I&#39;m sorry for even pointing that out), the service was fast and friendly. Star. <br><br>Star 2: How were the portions relative to the cost?<br><br>$19.00 for brioche french toast was pricey, but very much on par with other spots catering to tourists and expats like Clinton Street and Common Man. Star. <br><br>Stars 3 and 4: How was the food?<br><br>Clinton Street continues to dish up the best pancakes in the world - seriously. I don&#39;t know how they do it and especially how they maintain consistency internationally, but these fluffy cakes of goodness are so flavorful and go so well with the blueberries and maple butter syrup that it&#39;s just impossible to compete. Two Stars. <br><br>Star 5: Would you be excited to go back?<br><br>Always. Star.

I did not like this place much and Â covid made it worse.<br><br>The staff is pretentious, unfriendly when we show up without a booking and almost laugh at us. Even with a booking, they would let a heavily pregnant woman standing in the heat for 30min - no chair, refreshment or compassion shown.<br><br>I ordered online once (ordered at 3pm for a delivery at 7pm). The food arrived soggy, cold and unappetizing. It was most likely prepared 2h in advance and then delivered en masse.

Definitely on the pricey side, but that is to be expected of most of the restaurants in the downtown area. I went for breakfast and the food was amazing, with a variety of American-style options to choose from. I shared the chocolate chip pancakes and a scrambled eggs dish, and both were fantastic. The pancakes were fluffy and the chocolate chips were a perfect complement. It was such a sweet, rich dish and I wish I had gotten a larger share (I split between 4 people though, so that shouldn&#39;t have been a surprise). The eggs were delicious, and the biscuit that came with it was amazing - so buttery and satisfying. I would definitely recommend getting a few things to split, because then you can try multiple offerings. Next time I am in Singapore I will definitely come back!

Boozy Salted Caramel', 'width': 180, 'height': 180, 'caption': 'Boozy Salted Caramel'}]
text: Located in the middle of Purvis Street, is this cafe called Clinton Street Baking Company. Its main outlet is in New York, United States. It is well known for its pancake and is known as &#34;New York&#39;s # 1 breakfast spot&#34; by Lonely Planet, as well as, &#34;Best Pancakes&#34; by New York Magazine (twice). The place was decorated in a traditional, clean cut look.<br><br>The usual menu was presented in a booklet.<br>Besides the usual menu, there is daily special items on the board,<br>as well as, dinner special items.<br><br>Boozy Salted Caramel ($15++ left)<br>vanilla ice cream, bourbon, salted caramel sauce<br>Without alcohol ($10++ right)<br>Pretty strong in the alcohol. The drink tasted very rich and creamy, but could not taste the salted caramel in it.<br><br>Crab Cakes ($15++)<br>Two crab cakes, served with classic remoulade, and house slaw.<br>The crab cake was moist and creamy inside with chunks of crab meat in it.<br><br>Chicken &amp; Waffles ($21++)<br>with honey-Tabasco sauce, a crispy Belgian vanilla buttermilk waffle, and signature warm maple butter.<br>The chicken was served char burnt, which made one quite disappointed. Some parts of the batter was just too hard and bitter to be eaten. One had to remove the batter coating in order to eat. Although the staff saw that we had left much of the batter untouch when clearing the plates, no one asked us about the food. The waffle was not the usual crispy and fluffy type. Instead it was eggy and soft. More like kueh kueh type. Not bad with the maple butter sauce. But not really my type.<br><br>Pancakes with Warm Maple Butter ($18++)<br>Served with wild blueberries.<br>The first which I notice when the dish was served, was that the pancakes were super thick in size. The pancake was fluffy and soft, with a kind of eggy taste. Some may felt that the blueberries was a bit too sour. Nice but could not take in more a piece of pancake. It was way too much for me.<br><br>Overall felt that the food was overrated. Maybe I was expecting too much but it just did not blow me off. Although the place looked sparkling clean, I was surprised to see a certain small animal running through the dining area. No wonder the place had placed a notice that it would be closed early for maintenance on the coming Monday. I soon lost my appetite after that and trying to vomit everything out.

text: The pancakes are insane!!!! <br><br>Went here for breakfast and we ordered heuvos ranchis and the salmon omelette. Both were ok but nothing special. Next we ordered the chocolate chip pancakes. I believe they are one of the best pancakes I have ever tasted. They are hot, fluffy and the chocolate chip are melted inside them. Plus the pancakes are hot such that the chocolate chip sprinkled above them can easily melt. Other than the perfect pancakes the maple syrup that comes with it is also perfect. It&#39;s not your average maple syrup.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/qQhT6AF-qvhnF4jcuBgZjg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/clinton-street-baking-company-and-restaurant-singapore?reviewid=oDZt3XKYAcyxHJ8MudPr9A&select=qQhT6AF-qvhnF4jcuBgZjg', 'altText': 'Photo of Clinton Street Baking Company & Restaurant - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: I&#39;m not a huge fan of pancakes and that&#39;s not because I don&#39;t enjoy them. I do. I really do. It&#39;s just that not everyone perfects them. My husband and I were in Singapore for a couple of days and we both like our meals to be delicious. So my husband found this place mostly because they have good pancakes (based on the reviews he read) and we decided to give it a try. <br><br>We both ordered our pancakes with chocolate chunks. When the waiter brought the pancakes to our table, they looked like regular pancakes. However, the moment I drizzled the buttered maple syrup on top of the fluffy round edges of my pancake, I immediately knew that this one is going to be one of the best I ever had. And I was right. The buttered maple syrup was so darn good to the point that without it, the pancake would not taste this incredible. My husband loved it and so did I. Glad we gave it a try. Now I think you should.

text: What makes this brunch spot unique is their homemade maple syrup which tastes different than anything I&#39;ve ever tasted (in singapore and in the U.S.). The maple syrup is light and sweet with a tang of caramel(?) and an excellent addition to the crispy pancakes or waffles. <br><br>I will admit it&#39;s not the most balanced or nutritious meal however, and do feel a bit guilty and gluttonous after having had brunch there once. <br><br>The wait can be long but i would still say it was worth it. Would go back once in a while

This is a great place to get breakfast all day long. I ordered the pancakes with bananas and walnuts and was not disappointed. The syrup is rich and flavorful, the nuts are candies and the bananas are lightly dusted with sugar. It doesn&#39;t look like a lot but it was very filling. The restaurant isn&#39;t very big so get here early or plan to wait for a table. The prices are average for the area. I will definitely return the next time I&#39;m in Singapore.

I ordered the blueberry pancakes and the veggie sandwich, the veggie sandwich was good, it was packed with avocados which is a plus but it&#39;s a little bit pricy, the pancakes&#39;s however, tasted incredible along with the warm maple butter and the blueberries on top of it. 10/10 would recommend y&#39;all to come here just to get a taste of the pancakes!!

text: I&#39;m not a huge fan of pancakes and that&#39;s not because I don&#39;t enjoy them. I do. I really do. It&#39;s just that not everyone perfects them. My husband and I were in Singapore for a couple of days and we both like our meals to be delicious. So my husband found this place mostly because they have good pancakes (based on the reviews he read) and we decided to give it a try. <br><br>We both ordered our pancakes with chocolate chunks. When the waiter brought the pancakes to our table, they looked like regular pancakes. However, the moment I drizzled the buttered maple syrup on top of the fluffy round edges of my pancake, I immediately knew that this one is going to be one of the best I ever had. And I was right. The buttered maple syrup was so darn good to the point that without it, the pancake would not taste this incredible. My husband loved it and so did I. Glad we gave it a try. Now I think you should.

text: The pancakes are insane!!!! <br><br>Went here for breakfast and we ordered heuvos ranchis and the salmon omelette. Both were ok but nothing special. Next we ordered the chocolate chip pancakes. I believe they are one of the best pancakes I have ever tasted. They are hot, fluffy and the chocolate chip are melted inside them. Plus the pancakes are hot such that the chocolate chip sprinkled above them can easily melt. Other than the perfect pancakes the maple syrup that comes with it is also perfect. It&#39;s not your average maple syrup.

text: This place was soooooo delicious!!! We came here on our first day in Singapore for breakfast and ended up coming back on our last day because of how good it was. The waffles were amazing and the orange juice really was freshly squeezed. The place is very clean inside and the workers were patient, helpful, and friendly. 10/10 recommend!

Mangled upside down pineapple cake', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Mangled upside down pineapple cake'}]
text: My first time here. Ever. Didn&#39;t know about the New York branch so there is no basis for comparison. I&#39;ve heard lots of excited rumblings of course, and friends who used to live in New York were thrilled about its opening. Fair enough. From all accounts, I hear that this place largely works. The food is comparable and all. I&#39;ll have to take their word for it. <br><br>I only came here for some cake and I got the upside down pineapple cake. I don&#39;t know why but seeing a badly sliced and sloppily presented cake annoyed me. It shows a lack of care in the attentive-level of staff.<br><br>When I went to pay, I noticed that other cakes (of other flavors) were similarly badly sliced. Woah. <br><br>I really did think Clinton St Bakery was better than this. <br><br>Taste-wise, the cake was fine. Not great, not terrible. The staff was sufficiently polite. But I think the devil&#39;s in the details and they need to teach their staff how to slice cakes properly, lift the slices and place them on plates.

Cheese Grits. Yum yum (not really)', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Cheese Grits. Yum yum (not really)'}]
text: I had this a few years ago in New York. Unfortunately it was after a visit to Katz (and if you&#39;ve seen the size of their pastrami sandwiches you&#39;d know how stuffed I was at that time) so all I had was the bacon and it didn&#39;t leave much of an impression then.<br><br>FAST FORWARD TO 5 YEARS LATER! And Clinton Street Baking Co is now in SUNNY (hazy) SINGAPORE!<br><br>They don&#39;t take reservations, and we were here on a sunday morning, and the queue was 1.5 hours. By the time it was our turn to be seated it was 2 hours. Be warned that the queue is deceptively short because everyone just gives their handphone number and goes away while waiting. There are some red benches to sit on outside the shop but it could fit a maximum of 8 people. 2 yummy mummy-types tried to cut the queue (&#34;why don&#39;t we tell them that we have a baby?&#34;). To which I said. &#34;IS THE BABY GOING TO BE EATING THE FOOD HERE???&#34;)<br><br>My question was answered when I made the mistake of ordering the cheese grits. A mush in a plate, it tasted as good as it looked. Which was not at all. I&#39;d rather some mashed potatoes. Even the powdered ones that you get from 7-11.<br><br>Other sides were good but not impressive. We had the southern chicken (skin was yums), the scrambled eggs with salmon (not baaaaad), and some farmer&#39;s platter. Like, good but I wouldn&#39;t wait more than 30 minutes for them.<br><br>BUT THE STANDOUT WERE THE PANCAKES. 3 flavors - blueberry, banana, chocolate - to choose from. You can add 1 more flavour for $2. Same pancakes, different toppings. These were nice and fluffy and thick yet light. I think the only other place in Singapore that comes close so far is Skyve. If you put the pancakes from those 2 places together and made me choose 1, I don&#39;t know which would win. But maybe Clinton Street because of that wonderful maple syrup/butter mix, which married the taste of maple syrup with the smoothness of melted butter.<br><br>Come here! Unless you&#39;re a yummy mummy with a baby trying to cut the queue -_-&#34;

The famed Clinton St Neil&#39;s Blueberry Pancake, I really love the Maple Butter!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': "The famed Clinton St Neil's Blueberry Pancake, I really love the Maple Butter!"}]
text: Heard of the fame pancake quite sometimes, finally managed to taste it yesterday!<br><br>Indeed, it is worthy to try the &#39;Best pancake in the city&#39;, voted by New York Magazine twice. I have ordered the Blueberry Pancake, after a short wait, the lovely pancake was served. Generous portion of 3 slabs warm and pillowy pancake, served with tangy sweet blueberry coulis. The maple butter is the killer, I have completely surrendered after tasting it, it is just beyond words! Conclusion, cloud 9 sensation needs only few well made ingredients, come in as a perfect combination!<br><br>The good vibe is still lingering till now! I will definitely come back again, soon!

text: A great spot for a classic American breakfast. We had blueberry pancakes, French toast and the Farmer&#39;s breakfast. All were excellent and the portions are massive, you certainly won&#39;t go hungry! If you go on the weekend I would get there when it opens if you don&#39;t want to wait. There were 12 of us waiting by the time it opened. I&#39;ll definitely be back to sample some of their non-breakfast items at some point. <br>The service was a bit slow. I think the young staff are a bit overwhelmed. Hopefully that will improve with time.

text: Given that it&#39;s a fairly well known brand from NYC, lines and crowds are expected even in the soft launch phase. Approx 1 hour wait during weekend brunch. <br><br>Order came pretty swiftly, had the classic Pancakes. Generous portions as per the ones in NYC. Chicken and waffles were decent but not mind blowing. Overall decent cool brunch spot, hopefully it survived beyond the hype.

text: Favorite brunch place in town. Always bustling atmosphere whenever we drop by. Expect a waiting list during weekends. Chicken waffle is definitely a must try. We&#39;ve tried the huevos rancheros &amp; sugar bacon burger as well which really aren&#39;t bad at all. Overall, everything in this place are cooked &amp; tastes well.

Similar to the NY original (which I find overpriced and overhyped) except this place didn&#39;t have any queue on Saturday at 2pm. I just walked right in. AMAZING!<br><br>Serves your standard easy-to-make-at-home-but-why-bother-lets-just-pay-lots-of-money American brunch fare: chicken and waffles, their famous blueberry pancakes, milkshakes. You know, all that healthy stuff that keeps Americans so notoriously thin.

text: Finally, a good American diner style breakfast place in Singapore! The food here is pretty good - I&#39;ve tried the pancakes with warm maple butter + banana walnut, as well as chicken and waffles. Both were really good! The pancakes were extremely fluffy, and are in my opinion one of the best you can find in here.... and the warm maple butter they&#39;re served with was also heavenly!!

text: If you&#39;re after a substantial American style breakfast or brunch Clinton Street Baking Co is a decent option. The servings are massive, just like in The States, but the prices reflect the portion size. They have a lot of the classics here; pancakes, eggs on toast, a big breakfast etc. I thought they might have more baked goods on offer in the display cabinet given the business name, but there were just a few scones and muffins. I opted for the smoked salmon scrambled eggs and was not disappointed.

This is my 2nd visit, I love the pancake and also the chicken and waffle. The maple butterscotch syrup is a bomb! Supper yummy but can be too sweet for some people, so advice don&#39;t pour it a one go. <br><br>Portion can be huge if you don&#39;t have a big appetite <br> <br>Can be crowed during weekend and dinner time, so advice to make your reservation in advance if you planing dinner or weekend brunch here.<br><br>Tips : You can make reservation via Chope app.

text: I came here because the hotel breakfast at the Intercontinental was $S30 a pop, and I thought I could do better -- or at least the same for less. <br><br>So I decided to go to Killiney Kopitiam but my Ang Moh instincts took over while passing the lower-rated Clinton Street Baking Co. They had muffins on display and I am partial to Western breakfasts. So I was sucked in. <br><br>The first thing I saw from the menu was it was not going to be much less expensive. So maybe it&#39;ll be great? Same for more?<br><br>I ordered what I thought was their signature omelette because it had their name on it. But it only comes with two add-in ingredients (besides the eggs, of course). And apparently nothing but those two plus the eggs because when the omelette arrived I was asked if I wanted salt, pepper, or catsup. The first sign of cooking mediocrity is the need to season it with any of those things after cooking, especially a $20 omelette. If I&#39;d known I would have chosen bacon to go in there. <br><br>Ugh. It was so bland. And dry. I regretted not asking for catsup. I regretted more not having salsa, which is the best cure for bland eggs.<br><br>The hash browns, though, were remarkable. If it was a two-egg omelette instead of a three-egger I was pushing through I would have savored them more. <br><br>My cappuccino was also well done. Final tally, $S33!<br><br>At the hotel I could have bottomless juice, cappuccinos, an array of Japanese, Chinese, Indian, and Western breakfast items. Smoked salmon with capers. Fresh-made waffles. Croissants and danishes. Fresh fruit. <br><br>I got less for more. I&#39;m kind of amazed they didn&#39;t have oatmeal (or porridge) on the menu. <br><br>My punishment for not going to the kopitiam.

text: Great breakfast food, busy, yet nice atmosphere and mediocre service. <br><br>Went on a Saturday afternoon for a late lunch and they were still very busy. Sat at the counter and ate which gave me a front row seat to the controlled chaos of servers flying around picking up orders and ringing up customers. The service could have been better - no one spoke to me after I ordered to check on the food or pour more coffee and I had to ask for the check. Â <br><br>Had the chicken and waffles which was quite good, especially with their green jalapeÃ±o based hot sauce. Add the maple butter and you&#39;re good to go. I agree with another review that the waffle could have been a little more well done, especially to support the fried chicken but still worth getting. <br><br>Will definitely be back for those pancakes.

text: We had the farmers plate and the butter milk biscuit sandwich. On both dishes the scrambled eggs were done perfectly. The buttermilk biscuit sandwich was tasty--the biscuit crunchy on the outside and buttery inside. Bacon was tasty. The farmers plate was a healthy amount of food. Pork patties were flavorful and had just a slight kick. Sourdough bread was a little skimpy. <br><br>Coffee was good, especially if you are tired of the local. <br><br>The restaurant is pleasant, sunny with great staff. Prices are on the high side-- we spent nearly $50 for breakfast.

text: Having been to their original location in LES multiple times, I was very impressed with the pancakes at their new establishment in Singapore. (Let&#39;s be honest here, most of the restaurants that have opened up branches in Singapore are disappointments compared to their original location overseas. E.g., Lady M, Din Tai Fung, Tim Ho Wan, Lawrys, etc.) We came for lunch on a weekday, around 11:40, so there was no wait. My pancakes were fluffy and moist, and my friend&#39;s country breakfast also looked delicious. My only complaint is with the service, which was rather slow. We had to flag down the server a couple times to order our food, even though the restaurant was only half full. Will def be back again soon!

Highly recommend for a great brunch. Best breakfast biscuit sandwich I&#39;ve ever had. Pancakes are typical I felt.<br><br>I lived in NYC for 5 years and remember my times at Clinton Street Baking Company out there very fondly. I loved everything there, even their pancakes had a very impactful memory that I became jaded to any other pancake. Coming here however, I feel that the pancakes are nowhere near the quality in NYC and even taste pretty typical to any other cafe which is the the only reason for the minus 1 star given how hyped they are.<br><br>The biscuit breakfast sandwich is the best I&#39;ve ever had in my life. I was totally wow&#39;d by this here in Singapore and if my review was based on only this, I would have easily given this a resounding 5+ star.<br><br>Orange juice is fresh as is their coffee. <br><br>I would recommend that you call ahead and get a reservation. If you show up during the breakfast or lunch (or weekend brunch) hours, you will for sure need to wait the usual 2-3 hours that they mention.<br><br>Highly recommend but don&#39;t come in just for the pancakes!

text: Loved the thick, fluffy pancakes and maple butter! Do share the food if you&#39;re a small eater. <br><br>Waitresses were so polite. Loved their service. We waited for a few minutes to be served as it was quite packed on a Sunday morning. <br><br>Poached eggs were a tad disappointing as they didn&#39;t drain the water. So the eggs were sitting in a pool of water. <br><br>If you&#39;re the type who doesn&#39;t like sweet-tasting mocha, then this is the place. text: Get your carbs on!<br><br>Brunch lovers and carb lovers - this is YOUR spot! Â Yes, the wait can be a little crazy, but if you&#39;re patient, you will be rewarded with some fab, soul-hugging, muffin-top making food (just spend an extra 10 minutes on the elliptical!) Â The trick is to go early (before 10 am) and the wait is manageable. Â They are only open until 6 pm now but that may change soon.<br><br>The food<br>We couldn&#39;t help but indulge in a few pastries. Â The bacon, spinach, cheddar muffin was savory, a little sweet, and indulgent. Â Even my baby loved it (well for obvious reasons). The cheddar scone was crumbly and had a wonderful buttery top. Â But the real star is the crab cake eggs benedict. Â It was the best eggs benedict I&#39;ve ever eaten! Â Each component from the just cooked spinach to the creamy hollandaise sauce to the rich crab cake was just plain delicious. Â I also had the chorizo with eggs and it was savory and satisfying. Â We were very happy with the food so far and this is one of my new, favorite brunch spots!

A pretty basic place. <br><br>Came here because I was craving Pancakes &amp; they were pretty good. I enjoyed the blueberries Â and the sauce with the pancakes which I felt were a good combination. I wished they gave more blueberries because towards the end it started to get pretty dry. The sauce also started to get too sweet once the blueberries finished. But the pancakes were fluffy and tasty. <br><br>The chicken and waffles were a disappointment. I admit the waffles were done differently and could be subjectively just not up to my taste. But the chicken was poor. Tasteless, kinda soggy and dry. The sweet sauce didn&#39;t really go well with this and overall I&#39;m really not a fan of this dish. <br><br>Ordered the grits as well which was horrible. Could tell they didn&#39;t know how to cook cheese &amp; grits and it is not like what it&#39;s meant to be like. Very dry and undercooked. Flavourless.. bah horrible. <br><br>The sausage patty was just. Minced meat smashed &amp; fried? Not what you&#39;d expect. Disappointing because on the menu it said Sausage &amp; Maple.

text: Everything should be half the price. Â For the same price you can get three times the quality at P.S. Cafe. Â Dishes with eggs were underseasoned and in lack of flavor. Â The 20 dollar omelet has an egg to stuffing ratio of 5:1. Â Not coming back. Coffee was good.

A pretty basic place. <br><br>Came here because I was craving Pancakes &amp; they were pretty good. I enjoyed the blueberries Â and the sauce with the pancakes which I felt were a good combination. I wished they gave more blueberries because towards the end it started to get pretty dry. The sauce also started to get too sweet once the blueberries finished. But the pancakes were fluffy and tasty. <br><br>The chicken and waffles were a disappointment. I admit the waffles were done differently and could be subjectively just not up to my taste. But the chicken was poor. Tasteless, kinda soggy and dry. The sweet sauce didn&#39;t really go well with this and overall I&#39;m really not a fan of this dish. <br><br>Ordered the grits as well which was horrible. Could tell they didn&#39;t know how to cook cheese &amp; grits and it is not like what it&#39;s meant to be like. Very dry and undercooked. Flavourless.. bah horrible. <br><br>The sausage patty was just. Minced meat smashed &amp; fried? Not what you&#39;d expect. Disappointing because on the menu it said Sausage &amp; Maple.

text: Back again on a Saturday night for dinner and this time, we had the Angus cheeseburger, chicken and waffle, Clinton St omelette and buttermilk biscuit sandwich...oh and of course the blueberry pancakes. <br><br>Friends loved the food, particularly the blueberry pancakes and the buttermilk biscuit sandwich. I had the chicken and waffle; I would prefer if the chicken was more deep fried and crispy, though the waffle was tasty with the maple butter. The Angus cheeseburger looked delightful and we particularly enjoyed the very tasty fries. <br><br>Portions were satisfying and we barely had space for desserts - could only make room for 3 pancakes amongst a party of 6. The bill was about $30 per person. <br><br>I had made reservations by phone which was painless, though I wish they have an online option. It&#39;s interesting that&#39;s not available, considering the reservation confirmation was done via an automated system. <br><br>We&#39;ll be back again to try more of their desserts.

text: Located in the middle of Purvis Street, is this cafe called Clinton Street Baking Company. Its main outlet is in New York, United States. It is well known for its pancake and is known as &#34;New York&#39;s # 1 breakfast spot&#34; by Lonely Planet, as well as, &#34;Best Pancakes&#34; by New York Magazine (twice). The place was decorated in a traditional, clean cut look.<br><br>The usual menu was presented in a booklet.<br>Besides the usual menu, there is daily special items on the board,<br>as well as, dinner special items.<br><br>Boozy Salted Caramel ($15++ left)<br>vanilla ice cream, bourbon, salted caramel sauce<br>Without alcohol ($10++ right)<br>Pretty strong in the alcohol. The drink tasted very rich and creamy, but could not taste the salted caramel in it.<br><br>Crab Cakes ($15++)<br>Two crab cakes, served with classic remoulade, and house slaw.<br>The crab cake was moist and creamy inside with chunks of crab meat in it.<br><br>Chicken &amp; Waffles ($21++)<br>with honey-Tabasco sauce, a crispy Belgian vanilla buttermilk waffle, and signature warm maple butter.<br>The chicken was served char burnt, which made one quite disappointed. Some parts of the batter was just too hard and bitter to be eaten. One had to remove the batter coating in order to eat. Although the staff saw that we had left much of the batter untouch when clearing the plates, no one asked us about the food. The waffle was not the usual crispy and fluffy type. Instead it was eggy and soft. More like kueh kueh type. Not bad with the maple butter sauce. But not really my type.<br><br>Pancakes with Warm Maple Butter ($18++)<br>Served with wild blueberries.<br>The first which I notice when the dish was served, was that the pancakes were super thick in size. The pancake was fluffy and soft, with a kind of eggy taste. Some may felt that the blueberries was a bit too sour. Nice but could not take in more a piece of pancake. It was way too much for me.<br><br>Overall felt that the food was overrated. Maybe I was expecting too much but it just did not blow me off. Although the place looked sparkling clean, I was surprised to see a certain small animal running through the dining area. No wonder the place had placed a notice that it would be closed early for maintenance on the coming Monday. I soon lost my appetite after that and trying to vomit everything out.

text: Loved the thick, fluffy pancakes and maple butter! Do share the food if you&#39;re a small eater. <br><br>Waitresses were so polite. Loved their service. There wasn&#39;t an savory + sweet combo for pancakes so I ordered a wild blueberry pancake and added bacon. The pancakes were sooooo fluffy and when paired with the sour-ish berries and sweet syrup, it was great! The bacon was too hard for my liking. Be ready to spend a bit, the pancake with a side of bacon, coffee and juice came up to $42

text: Having been to their original location in LES multiple times, I was very impressed with the pancakes at their new establishment in Singapore. (Let&#39;s be honest here, most of the restaurants that have opened up branches in Singapore are disappointments compared to their original location overseas. E.g., Lady M, Din Tai Fung, Tim Ho Wan, Lawrys, etc.) We came for lunch on a weekday, around 11:40, so there was no wait. My pancakes were fluffy and moist, and my friend&#39;s country breakfast also looked delicious. My only complaint is with the service, which was rather slow. We had to flag down the server a couple times to order our food, even though the restaurant was only half full. Will def be back again soon!

Mangled upside down pineapple cake', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Mangled upside down pineapple cake'}]
text: My first time here. Ever. Didn&#39;t know about the New York branch so there is no basis for comparison. I&#39;ve heard lots of excited rumblings of course, and friends who used to live in New York were thrilled about its opening. Fair enough. From all accounts, I hear that this place largely works. The food is comparable and all. I&#39;ll have to take their word for it. <br><br>I only came here for some cake and I got the upside down pineapple cake. I don&#39;t know why but seeing a badly sliced and sloppily presented cake annoyed me. It shows a lack of care in the attentive-level of staff.<br><br>When I went to pay, I noticed that other cakes (of other flavors) were similarly badly sliced. Woah. <br><br>I really did think Clinton St Bakery was better than this. <br><br>Taste-wise, the cake was fine. Not great, not terrible. The staff was sufficiently polite. But I think the devil&#39;s in the details and they need to teach their staff how to slice cakes properly, lift the slices and place them on plates.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/8AMAV_cQpbhXWQaPBh4OTw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/clinton-street-baking-company-and-restaurant-singapore?reviewid=HKOuU0GYAScQLb05YbIG9w&select=8AMAV_cQpbhXWQaPBh4OTw', 'altText': 'Photo of Clinton Street Baking Company & Restaurant - Singapore, Singapore. takeout counter', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'takeout counter'}]
text: To summarize it all in a word, pancakes. EAT the pancakes.<br><br>Clinton St Baking Co. of Manhattan&#39;s Lower East Side finally lands in Singapore with a huge splash, with glowing reviews in the island&#39;s English language broadsheet, and features on TV.<br><br>Stepping inside, the dining room successfully recreates that typical American diner feel, similar to the original in NY (but definitely much newer).<br><br>The entrees were decently good, but I&#39;d recommend the pancakes above everything else. Fluffy on the inside, crispy on the outside, paired with a sinful maple-butter sauce that&#39;s just amazing as it is calorific. Blueberry, banana walnut or chocolate chunk, they&#39;re all good. The house brew is drip coffee, and refills are free!<br><br>They had a couple of Southern offerings on the menu, but IMO they were Northern interpretations of Southern food. I liked that the buttermilk fried chicken had cornmeal in the batter, however the batter lost its crunchiness rather quickly and fell off the chicken before you had a chance to bite it. Conclusion, stick to the pancakes.<br><br>They don&#39;t take reservations, and weekend brunch lines are an hour wait or more. To avoid the crowds, I recommend coming in on a weekday, or late in the afternoon on a weekend, or heading for the pastry &amp; coffee takeout counter instead.<br><br>It&#39;s been a while since I was back in Manhattan, and I personally have not been to the original on Clinton St (there, I heard the lines are an hour long too), but comparing this to other brunch type places in Singapore they pretty much come out tops. 3 if this is a place in the US, 4 cos it&#39;s in Singapore.

text: The Good, The Bad, and The Bourbon Salted Caramel Milkshake<br><br>I preface this by saying I absolutely love Clinton Street Baking Co. in New York. The Singapore shop matches the New York venue in some respects (main courses and drinks) and fails in other areas (pies and service).<br><br>I&#39;ll start with the good. For a shop known for its baked goods and pancakes, the drinks were fantastic. Â The bourbon salted caramel milkshake was the best thing we had and the bloody mary, which is so rarely made well, was also delicious. The main courses we tried (pancakes and huevos rancheros) were every bit as good as the NY shop.<br><br>Unfortunately, there were several areas where Clinton Street really struggled. First, the service was horrible. After we were seated, not one staff member came to our table without being asked. We had to ask for drinks, for menus, to order, to get a dessert menu, to get a check, and to have our check taken and processed. When there were quality issues with food (see below), we did not get an apology and the waiter seemed annoyed to have to deal with the issue.<br><br>Second, when we arrived for brunch, two of the three pies of the day were unavailable. No explanation was give nor was any apology forthcoming. We tried the only special available (strawberry rhubarb pie) and the lime meringue pie. Both were disappointing. The crumble on the strawberry rhubarb pie was like a group of small, indestructible rocks. We could not break up the 10cm pieces with a fork -- and we tried! We were not provided a knife with dessert. Â The lime meringue pie tasted good but there was so little lime custard except at the very edge of the pie that it tasted almost exclusively of meringue.<br><br>When I pointed these out to our server he simply asked if we would like something different. I pointed out that there was very little else available as two of the pies of the day were not available and he stood in silence. He did not seem to have any idea how the pies should be made or the quality that is normally associated with Clinton Street.
Breakfast was mediocre. Nothing crazy or wow about. Overpriced as well. Would I recommend? Sure, if there&#39;s nothing else on the block to eat. Otherwise, it&#39;s not worth a visit.

text: Very disappointed in this place. Over priced for such mediocre food. Eggs were over cooked, sausage patties and the piece of ham were not very flavorful. I also personally didn&#39;t like the strong flavor of the cheese. Coffee wasn&#39;t that great either. All in all, not worth the price. Mediocre food for high end price.

Great food, but while eating my breakfast they have decided it&#39;s a great time to fix the door hinge to the entrance which consists of some ass hat pounding and tapping on it during my entire meal. Â Clueless and ruined my experience. Â Would have been awesome other than that.

I had heard about this place from a few people. Â I tasked myself for bringing a pumpkin pie for a Thanksgiving get together, i wanted a back up. Â I called the week before and they mentioned that the seasonal pies (pumpkin and pecan were $55) Â Nope. Â I ended up baking one, but still wanted another desert so I decided to pop by on Sunday because I wanted breakfast and needed a back up dessert. Â I ordered the breakfast sandwich that came with spinach, bacon, egg and cheese on a biscuit. Â Now, this place is supposedly by the same company as the one in NY, so my expectations were high. Â I&#39;m from the South, so you better bring your A game when it comes to biscuits. Â I ordered and my food came out before my latte. Â It looked awful and for $18, I was not happy. Â The cheese looked like it was under a heat lamp for the last hour, the hashbrowns were burnt, and the one side of the biscuit had what looked like a tomato sauce on it. Â WTF? Â The bacon was so sad and undercooked I just couldn&#39;t touch it. Â I ate a tiny piece of the biscuit, and drank my latte. Â The waitress was nice enough to ask me what was wrong in which I told her it looked like my meal came from when Bush was President, and asked if I wanted a replacement. Â The pancakes looked really good but by this time I needed to get outta there. Â I did order a Strawberry Rubarb pie to take with, and they took off my breakfast off my bill. Â They also game me a large take away biscuit for good measure which by itself was really tasty. Â Everyone at Thanksgiving liked the pie, I didn&#39;t taste it. Â I doubt I&#39;d come back here there are just too many good options for brunch in Singapore to strike out again.

text: Went for the chicken and waffles - they were amazing! The batter on the chicken was light and NOT greasy! The jalapeÃ±o cornbread was quite large and yummy. <br><br>We got a blueberry shake. Unfortunately, it was not worth the price, but everything else was yummy! <br><br>This was my second time, and this time the service was awful. (Luckily the food is so yummy!) text: This is a nice cafÃ© with a very inviting dÃ©cor located in Market Street. However, to be honest, it is a little hard to find this place even though it is right in the middle of Raffles Place. It&#39;s behind the M1 shop at Caltex House.<br>Dimbulah prides itself on bringing fine Australian coffee from the plantation straight to the consumer, and it shows: the coffee here is simply mindblowing. <br>They have a breakfast menu as well as a lunch menu. They also have cakes, tarts and muffins on display. However, it seems that most people were there for the coffee.<br>My friend had a triple deck roast chicken sandwich and a chicken pie. The chicken sandwich was nothing special, just three slices of wholemeal sandwich bread with roast chicken and the usual garnishing. The chicken pie was not bad. I had a tuna baguette which was also very normal, so food-wise, it&#39;s really not impressive. As I&#39;ve mentioned though, the Â coffee was really good. It&#39;s not harsh and too acidic, and there is kind of an underlying richness which gives the coffee texture and body. Overall, this is a great place to chill. Recommended!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/Az_GzfFZJ3b4-N8OmSb_dg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/dimbulah-singapore?reviewid=-3eiR_PCVYSVLO1pZ9pGMA&select=Az_GzfFZJ3b4-N8OmSb_dg', 'altText': 'Photo of Dimbulah - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Up there on my list of favourite cafes in the CBD - its so conveniently located, just an escalator and a few steps away from Raffles Place MRT. What better place to meet a friend for coffee and breakfast before starting your day?<br>Its pleasantly quiet in the mornings before 9am, but a line will slowly form as it creeps closer to 9 for takeaway coffees.<br>The food I must admit is very average, but this is a coffee joint more than anything else, and they serve excellent coffee which is why I think it is still deserving of a full 5 stars. <br>The baristas here have certainly been trained well, with the coffee being consistent in its delivery - at the perfect temperature, not lukewarm or burnt. <br><br>What impressed me most though was the service here. Â I came with a colleague one morning but as we were running late we only had about 10 minutes to sit down with our coffees after ordering, which wasn&#39;t enough time for me to drink it (I know I&#39;m quite slow - but I really don&#39;t enjoy gulping my coffee down!), and so I asked if it would be possible for my half drunk coffee to be taken away - and the server was incredibly nice and said of course not a problem and had it put in a takeaway cup for me. Â I was actually quite amazed! Wasn&#39;t sure what I was expecting when I asked honestly, but Â was pleasantly blown away.<br><br>So well deserving of 5 stars I reckon! Love Dimbulah!

text: Dimbulah is an Australian coffee franchise whose motto is &#34;plantation to cup&#34;. It operates several locations across Singapore, including two in Raffles Place (with the other being located in Market Street). I prefer the Chevron House outlet as it&#39;s larger, more inviting and, because it&#39;s not out in the open, has more privacy.<br><br> On the coffee front, Dimbulah is certainly very much Australian in that the staff is friendly and its coffees are brilliant. I&#39;ve only had the flat whites here twice and they&#39;ve been consistently delicious. Prices are reasonable for Singapore at $4.50. The only let-down though is that there&#39;s no latte art. I know it&#39;ll vanish the moment I drink my beverage, or, what&#39;s more likely, get destroyed by the time I get back to my office, but... still! Presentation does count, and for that, I&#39;ll take off half a star, only Qype doesn&#39;t do half stars, so I have to take off one whole star so as to distinguish Dimbulah from the other cafes with great coffee.<br><br> For food, Dimbulah offers sandwiches, wraps and cakes. This particular outlets also sells soups from Saybons.<br><br> Given its location, it can get a little crowded with office workers swinging by to get their morning /post-lunch fix, but the service is very fast, without quality being compromised.

I honestly detest places that only take cash. Â Seriously people, we live in 2016, and I hate using cash. Â The only place I&#39;ll give a pass to is hawker centers. Â I&#39;m guessing that Asia has not discovered the square. (a payment system used by everyone in the US for small businesses) Oh how I wish it would hurry up and get here. Â <br><br>ANYWAY, my work colleague turned me on to Simply Sandwich as there just not enough sandwich places in the CBD. Â Subway doesn&#39;t count. Â The sandwiches are legit, the chicken salad is the best, but my friend swears by the roast beef and the steak one. Â Good sizes for decent prices. Â Chips plus sandwich $11.80. Â Fast counter service with a few tables outside and inside. Â Def. recommended if you work in the area. Â Only open for lunch.

text: Well portioned sandwiches to break the monotony of Japanese, Korean and Asian fusion lunch spots on Robinson road. The sandwiches are hot or toasted. Had the ham and cheese which was better than average. Prices are reasonable and service was good though we went early.

Yuck. Not a fan of the sandwich.<br><br>I got their daily special of roasted chicken with mushroom and spinach, and for a $10.30 sandwich it fell awfully flat. There was just zero excitement in the taste. The chicken was bland, spinach was blah and mushroom was just mushroom. Was there even any sauce in this sandwich? I can&#39;t recall.<br><br>if anything, it was just.... salty. I&#39;m not sure if I just tried the wrong sandwich or what (first visit) but judging from the lack of yelp review and crowd, they&#39;re probably not all that impressive anyway.<br><br>Not coming back.

What could possibly lead people to queue a swimming pool&#39;s length for econ rice?<br><br>Value is probably it. Not many places in the area - at least this side of the highway - allow you to eat for $2-4 and walk away full. Juices for $2 is 50% better than anybody else. $1 tea sure beats any other option in the area, including the Peace Centre food court.<br><br>The food is quite good for an econ rice stand. The CKT had decent wok hei and more importantly bits of Chinese sausage unfortunately missing from many other food courts&#39; versions. Mee goreng and mee rebus seemed to be particularly popular, but econ rice is the star of this tiny food court.<br><br>Despite the massive queue at lunchtime, seating is relatively easy. Unlike, say, Food Republic at PS after its renovation (more space, less chairs, much chope). <br><br>One day this mall is going to get &#34;renovated&#34; and it will be back to overpaying for claypot chicken and BKT, but for now I&#39;m enjoying it weekly.

text: Hidden on the second floor of Park Lane Shopping Mall is Isle Eating House, a simple coffee shop located in the heart of Dhoby Ghaut.<br> <br>Not always common, but self-service curry gravy. For those like me who love a ton of curry gravy on their rice, this is perfect. 50 calories per scoop of curry gravy does deter me from flooding my rice with curry gravy.<br> <br>A great mix of meat and vegetables! Anything you could possibly want. <br><br>For $6.90 you can get two plates of rice for two people! You could probably only afford a plate of Indonesian mixed food rice at the Plaza Sing Food Court just a 5 minute walk away.<br><br> <br>I love my potatos and I usually get some form of potatos from any chai peng (mixed veg rice) stall and this tasted pretty good. The potato slices were pan fried first, before getting cooked, as you can see the charring of each potato slice and some even tasted crispy. The omelette egg was decent, not too salt and they were generous with the serving of the omelette. I enjoyed munching on the omelette that was drowned in curry gravy. The chicken pieces were okay, tasted like the normal fried chicken you get from a chai peng stall. But for $3.50, I felt it was reasonably priced for a meal in the city area.<br> <br>Finding Teh-O, Kopi-O for 90 cents and Teh, Kopi for $1, is very reasonably priced in the city area!<br><br>Specials for just $2<br> <br>For $2, what meal can you get in the Dhoby Ghaut area? At Isle eating house, you can either get 2 crispy roti prata or fried carrot cake! <br><br>Definitely my choice of cheap eats if I&#39;m near Peace Centre, or before I head to Teo Heng at Hotel Rendezvous.

This humble eating house is on the second level of Parklane Shopping Mall, a rather rundown place that reminds you of what malls were like in the 80s and earlier part of the 90s. There&#39;re also dodgy looking shops like massage and spa parlors, KTV lounges, money lenders, a &#34;photon energy waves&#34; &#34;health&#34; supply shop, a suspiciously darkly lit LAN gaming shop and plenty of empty units.<br><br>However as we know, the only thing ambience guarantees you is high prices. Well okay the air conditioning here is quite anemic, but you don&#39;t linger in this kind of place anyway.<br><br>I took a walk around this shopping centre at lunch time and this was the most popular of the eating houses in the building so I decided to try it.<br><br>There&#39;re several stalls in this unit; so far I&#39;ve patronised the economy rice and fried rice stalls.<br><br>Economy rice:<br>I got a plate of rice with 2 meat items and 2 vegetable items for $4.30, which is a price that&#39;s hard to match in town. <br><br>The &#34;rendang&#34; chicken was a generic curry sauce and didn&#39;t look or taste like rendang (which is closer to a dry paste coating the meat). There was a bit too much chicken skin but happily not too much potato - many places put a lot of potato in their curries to cut costs.<br><br>The curry pork was great, having a stronger spice blend and a thicker sauce which went well with pork, which is a somewhat heavier meat than chicken. Again there wasn&#39;t much potato which was good.<br><br>Large fried tofu cubes in a Thai-ish chili sauce was pretty tasty, though the tofu was a bit dry. Despite not being freshly fried it still retained some of its crunch, and the sauce was more complex than the usual &#34;Thai&#34; chili sauces which taste like they come from out of a bottle. The tofu cubes were also crinkly on the outside and firm on the inside (most places use a smoother type of tofu), and the texture was pleasing (most places do it very smooth).<br><br>The Chinese spinach with ikan bilis was alright - not overcooked as some do it though I&#39;ve had better.<br><br>The curry sauce I opted to have spooned over my rice struck a good balance - it didn&#39;t overpower the taste of the other dishes, while adding welcome flavour to the plain rice.<br><br>This is definitely one of the better cai pngs (economy rice) I&#39;ve had.<br><br>Fried rice:<br>It was okay.<br><br>Ingredients wise it was quite generous, with small pieces of meat, crab stick, chinese sausage and even some small prawns generously scattered. There were even a few medium sized pieces of roast pork.<br><br>Sadly there wasn&#39;t enough wok hei (wok flavour) - maybe the fire isn&#39;t big enough.

text: My favorite milk tea place in sg. I have tried Liho (large cup), everyone each cup (no much tea flavor), Koi (very creamy), etc. this is really the best shop with strong tea flavor but not lack of good milk. I have to stop by Ghoby Gaut MRT just to buy this.

1. Small Pearls<br>- Love the small pearls! Not all bubble tea joints serve these mini pearls :) <br><br>2. Jasmine green tea<br>- I had the taiwan jasmine green tea, 30% sugar. Love all taiwan tea and generally TEA of all sorts. Taiwan is famous for its tea which are of three main types: oolong tea, black tea and green tea. The former two are more bitter so I&#39;d recommend going for the green tea (for beginners) if you are planning on drinking it neat (aka no milk, no/less sugar). If you&#39;re going to mix it up with milk then anyone of the 3 is fine. Milk basically musk the taste of distinct flavor of each tea so it ends up Â being almost the same. <br><br>3. Milk tea (original) <br>- The most famous version of it! <br>- My friend had it (no pearls - why why why). He seemed to like it.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/McG06NQCamkYT4m6X-094g/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/a-gan-tea-singapore?reviewid=gTNTwxR3heYwOBqMsQKgeg&select=McG06NQCamkYT4m6X-094g', 'altText': 'Photo of A-Gan Tea - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: A-gan tea offers something different from the usual stuff from gongcha and koi. While they are technically a bubble tea shop, their strengths lie in their variations of jellies. While they do decent pearls, I&#39;m not exactly a fan. <br><br>I like that they have pretty interesting fruit flavours that are light and refreshing. I love their passionfruit tea and their mango green tea for the fresh fruits in them. The mango green tea is a current favourite although it is a little too sweet for me, even at 25% sugar level. It comes with agar-agar jelly, which has a nice crunch to it, as well as bits and pieces of fresh mango. Great for a hot day out on Orchard Road!

At Dhoby Ghaut MRT / technically the &#34;basement&#34; of Plaza Singapura, before you enter, is this bubble tea shop that sprang up last year. Considering it&#39;s been here over a year now, it must be doing pretty well. There&#39;s always a line, especially now that Gong Cha upstairs is gone due to renovation works.<br><br>Their speciality &#34;A-Gan&#34; black tea is quite good. like the pearls (although they always seem to run out of black pearls, and I am kind of freaked out by the white pearls) which are chewy. I&#39;m somewhat of a bubble tea afficionado, so if I had to compare it to a bubble tea shop, I&#39;d liken it to Gong Cha.<br><br>The latest trend is the ability to dictate your sugar level, which A-Gan also offers. The 25% sugar level A Gan black tea tastes strongly of tea and is complemented with the right amount of sweetness to make it a pleasure to drink. This makes it one of my preferred bubble tea shops for black tea. <br><br>The milk tea is quite decent as well, though at 25% , it is still a little too sweet for me.<br><br>One MAJOR drawback though is that the staff are damn slow. Really . Really. Slow . How long does it take for one to make a standard black tea with pearl? I have waited five minutes with just one person (and one order) in front of me. Each time I&#39;m faced with a not inconsiderable wait, so make sure you&#39;re aware of this even when there isn&#39;t a queue.

text: Bodacious serves up simple and unpretentious food. They serve all-day breakfast menu dishes such as all time favourite Eggs Benedict, among many other chef&#39;s specials. It has an outdoor dining area that is sheltered as well as an indoor dining area complete with a bar top counter for beers and more.The interior is very pop culture like with chic and sleek furnishing. The dining area is mainly lit up by natural lighting from the glass windows surrounding the entire bisotro, so you can be sure to get really good photos during the day. The air conditioning was just alright and kept me cool throughout my dining session. The iced water they served was chilled and had a citrusy taste.The menu for the appetizers seems to have something for everyone, including my favourite truffle fries. Their all day menu looked very satisfying but there were interesting items on the main menu like seafood risotto and pan fried sea bass that I was tempted to try. The menu itself is very simple with reasonable prices. Check out the furnishing!<br><br>1. Mela Merillo $4.20+<br>This was an interesting drink or at least seemed like one on the menu. Listed as a mocktail tea that was strawberry flavoured. I was a bit shocked to see such a huge cup placed on my table by the waiter. Taste wise, it was more like strawberry syrup with peach syrup mixed with some sprite. The temperature of the drink was superb for the scorching hot weather outside.<br><br>2. Sea bass $16.80+ *Highly Recommended*<br>Pan-fried sea bass in spicy tomato sauce with mash potatoes. I decided to pick this as my main as I felt that it would lighter but I was wrong. The sea bass was huge, in comparison to what is offered at most eateries. It had a very crispy fish skin and my knife exposed a very soft and tender fish meat that tasted both fresh and with the tomato sauce was mind blowing. But sadly, the tomato sauce does overwhelm the crispy fish skin a bit and so the fish didn&#39;t stay crispy for too long. The mashed potatos were so soft and no clumps were seen. This was a perfect lunch option and I&#39;m definitely getting it again. I cannot get over the crispy goodness of the fish and the sheer portion of the sea bass!<br><br>3. Spaghetti Vongole $15.80+<br>A crowd pleaser! Spaghetti &amp; clams in white win sauce accompanied with a tomato salsa topping. We asked if we could get this without the tomato salsa but we were told it was cooked together with the spaghetti. This dish despite not having a spicy warning label was extremely spicy, like peppery mouth burning hot! They used a lot of garlic as well, so fellow office workers around, do check if you have external meetings after your lunch here before choosing this dish. <br><br>4. Shibuya Toast $13.80+ *Highly Recommended*<br>A cube of toasted, honey-drizzled, thick and uncut, soft milk bread, decorated with berries, topped with salted butter and vanilla ice cream. The thick toast had a slightly crisp exterior but the interior was kind of dry for my liking, but only on the edges. On the inside, the toast was layered with butter clustered all in the middle, evenly spreaded. The toast had a decent amount of sweet fragrance and when the staff placed it on my table. I could immediately sense my sweet tooth going &#34;wow&#34;.Portion is strongly recommended for sharing between 2 or more pax. The toast was still decent. Really really love the texture of their vanilla ice cream, it was so smooth and light, with a melt-in-your-mouth texture. The ice cream was pretty frozen, so after a pro-longed photo taking session, the ice cream finally warmed up to the right temperature for my fork to ease it&#39;s way into the ice cream. <br><br>This shibuya toast is a great option for those with a sweet tooth! My only wish was that this toast should be served with a portion of honey or syrup that we could drizzle over the ice cream! There was some syrup all over the plate, but it just wasn&#39;t enough for my &#34;wannabe-diabetic&#34; tastebud!<br><br>Overall : Loved the ambiance at Bodacious, and their newly revamped menu. Just wished the staff could&#39;ve been more attentive to our needs during a weekday lunch hour.

text: Decided to pop into this hip and cosy bistro for dinner. The decor is dark wood chic but the food here is what you can rave about. A wide selection of beers and the coffee is AMAZEBALLS. I think they are affiliated with the nearby cafe, Long Black, which is well known around this parts for their awesome set lunch deals and gourmet coffee. <br><br>Must order their burgers, eggs bene, cakes and all day brekkie! The owner, Heng is super friendly and warm which makes for hanging out with friends and colleagues are comfortable here. Will definitely come back again as its not too crowded or pretentious and did I mention about the great coffee here again??

text: I ordered pawn paste fried chicken using sugar app. This is the first time I tried this dish and its specialised in Singapore. The taste is quite good and chicken is juicy. But the oil is explosive, I had to use 7 pieces of napkins to suck up all the oil of this dish in order to finish them. They serve very fast and fresh and hot, by think they should get rid of some oil before serving. <br><br>The atmosphere is nice and surrounded by new Highriser in a biotech business building area.

text: Yes, i give the awards based on consistency! over the decades, it has maintained standards and consistency w a small hike in price only<br><br>The meat served is cucculent and sauce that goes with it is good...(some chicken rice stall served ok meat w not-too-blending sauce)<br><br>U will never be bored with just roasted meat (char siew)/duck/chicken etc over here, they served other dishes like a variety of home cooked soups...After eating here, u can visit the bugis area or the famous Liang seah street for some desserts<br><br>but they r closed by evening ....their main group of customers are office workers...having said that, i saw a rich &#34;Tai tai&#34; drove her large mercedes( parking at the side at about 4pm+) just to take-away some char siew<br><br>It s a shame that many do NOT know this shop!

text: I&#39;ve been going to Alex for 5 years.Â Â However the last two visits were terrible.Â Â The wait time was 40 min. I ordered breast meat larger portion of duck and got mainly bones.Â Â If you are in Singapore and want roasted duck I would not recommend this place for the service, for the food or for the value. If you like to pay $8 for duck bones, go to Alex.Â Â If you want to wait on your food, and chase the server for your food, go to Alex.Â Â However I like Kam&#39;s behind Shaw Center much better.Â Â Go to Kam&#39;s if you want actual Duck Meat.

One of the most popular places around town to have a simple and good dish of roasted meats with rice, Alex Eating House is hugely popular during lunch time with the working crowd. Even though the staff there are almost exclusively all from China, the food is still very much Cantonese and good.<br><br>Choose from a combination of roasted meat with char siew or duck meat with your white rice. Prices are fair and service quick. You might have to share a table with others but that&#39;s alright for the delicious dish in front of you!

Stopped in for lunch after being unable to locate the restaurant we desired to go to, I recall walking by at 12:30 AM and seeing this area packed with locals, which is always a good sign. Â Didn&#39;t know what to expect but the peking ducks hanging in the window were promising. Â I don&#39;t speak Chinese, so when I asked for duck on noodles and my buddy asked for BBQ Chicken on rice we weren&#39;t disappointed. Â Add in a few chilled cans of green tea and we were in business. Â The ambiance is relaxed, the chef wields a cleaver and hacks away at the ducks and chicken while servers scope rice or noodles onto trays that get topped with the BBQ sauce or Shoyou. Â The &#39;register&#39; was literally a plastic bucket full of cash and coin. Â Definitely a lucky score on a sunday afternoon!

text: The place was in the park, hidden by the lalang surrounding it. It was located just a stone throw from the bus stop. There was both outdoor alfresco and indoor air-con dine in area, with the carpark just in front. <br><br>Salted Egg Chicken Burger ($14.90)<br>Crispy chicken thigh, topped with salted egg sauce, served with salad &amp; fries <br>The sauce looked quite thin a layer on the chicken patty but the flavour was most distinct. Can&#39;t wondering if the patty had been seasoned in salted Egg.<br><br>Black Pepper Smoked Duck Aglio Olio ($14.90)<br>spaghetti tossed with olive oil, herbs, chilli flakes, garlic, mushroom &amp; black pepper smoked duck <br>It was well flavoured without overdosed by black peppe<br><br>Chilli Crab Pasta (S$16.90)<br>spaghetti tossed with chilli crab paste, shredded crab meat &amp; egg <br>Those who love love crab but didn&#39;t want to dirty fingers would this dish &#39;cos it was packed with chunky real crab meat. No crab stick here.<br><br>Baked Fragrant Rice ($12.90)<br>mixed grain rice in rich cream with carrots, onion, mushrooms, topped with choice of bacon/ chicken &amp; baked with mozzarella cheese <br>Using mixed grain rice, one would think it would difficult to digest. Turned out it was savoury with soft fluffy rice.<br><br>Chicken Chop ($14.90)<br>pan grilled chicken thigh, topped with mushroom slices, served with salad &amp; wedges <br>Tender juicy piece of meat drenched in rich sauce <br><br>Mixed Platter For 4 ($18.90)<br>Chicken winglets &amp; drumlets, chicken strips, sausages wrapped with bacon strips, calamari rings &amp; potato wedges<br><br>Truffle Fries ($8.90) <br><br>Salted Caramel Lava Cake ($7.90)<br>Served with a scoop of ice cream <br>Not sure why but felt that the scoop of vanilla ice cream tasted sweeter than the soft moist cake.<br><br>Organic Peppermint Leaf Tea (S$5.90)<br>Origin : Laos<br>Uses : For indigestion, loss of appetite, stomach discomfort, flatulence, nausea, vomitting, morning sickness, lung infections, liver porblems, gall bladder problems, painful menstrual periods.<br>It was served in such elegant tea pot with the cup below it, and brown sugar in bottle.<br><br>Hibiscus Orange Organic Tea (S$6.90)<br>Origin : Laos<br>Uses : For high blood presure, high cholesterol, heart disease, loss of appetite, colds, coughs, irritated stomach, fluid retention, nervous condition. <br>The tea was kept warm for quite awhile with a slight floral taste.<br><br>Zucchini Refresher ($4.90) <br>The drink was refreshing with a cucumber-like taste.<br><br>Salted Caramel Latte ($4.90 + $1)<br>Served in a double-wall glass, with the salted caramel on top.<br><br>Fizzling Passionfruit ($4.90)<br><br>Raspberry fruit ice ($5.50)<br><br>Rose Dale ($6.50)<br>Milk, soda, ice cream, boba<br>The drink was milky and carbonated with boba pearls bursting out in the mouth when bitten.

text: How can you ignore these pastries. Tai Sar Piah . also known as bean paste biscuits, similar to filfipino hoopia, except thinner. This joint is a one of the best where I tasted these pastry. It was done in very traditional way and they offer sweet and salty flavors. A good snack on the go or for breakfast with coffee. They are also cheap from SGD.60 to SGD.80. Or you can buy it for 3 for SGD 1.00 . Thats a deal. A must try in Singapore food scene and dont forget to take some with you.

We often go to this cafe to enjoy the great desserts after having dinner in the area. In particular, we love the sugar roll, fruit tarts and the coffees here. Haven&#39;t really tried much of the hot food they serve here but I don&#39;t think they&#39;re much to shout about. If you&#39;re in the area, definitely stop by for some of their desserts!
