text: This little Starbucks counter is located right between center point and OG on orchard. It&#39;s nice because there is so much ample seating (2 levels), but it can get crowded with people hanging out for hours at a time and there is no regulation by the workers. HOWEVER, I like frequenting this Starbucks because the Starbucks inside center point doesn&#39;t have free wifi!!!! How lame is that?! <br><br>Another thing, this is an open air Starbucks, so during the summer months it can get especially muggy. <br><br>Did I say free wifi?! Starbucks provides a nice break from all the shopping one can possibly do on orchard rd. you can also do some pretty awesome people watching if you sit on the second (street) level of this Starbucks. <br><br>The only thing I will complain about--Starbucks needs to universalize the rewards system!! I can&#39;t get stars in singapore!!! :(

text: What you see with this Starbucks is not what you get. What you see is a large sign clearly visible on Orchard Road. It makes you think that is where this Starbucks is located. It is not. It is actually located down the stairs next to the sign. Plus, it is open-air. Meaning, you are not going into a Starbucks where you can expect air conditioned comfort. No, you will feel the warm air.<br><br>The staff that work at this Starbucks are all very nice and they do their job very well. The actual design of this Starbucks is nice enough and they have seats and tables on either side of where the baristas are creating your drinks.<br><br>This is certainly a great place to grab a drink or a snack on the go but if you want to step back from the elements this is probably not the best Starbucks to seek out.

This quaint little cafe is on one of the busier roads in Tiong Bahru. Prices are fair game for the area, with drinks around $5-8 and tarts and pastries around $7. I got the cinnamon egg tart which was absolutely delicious along with the drips crushed iced lemon drink - also very tasty. Friends got the lime meringue tart and a piece of peach pie; neither were as good as the egg tart.<br><br>It is not as hipster as some other cafes you will find in the area, and the space was rather cramped and crowded. Atmosphere is light with crisp decorations. A little too busy for my taste but the fare was great!

text: Drips Bakery Cafe isn&#39;t joking when they have this huge decal that screams &#34;We specialize in Tarts&#34; to everyone that walks by. Located in hipster land, near Chapter 55, is Drips, which is a pretty huge shop.<br><br>There&#39;s quite a lot of seating, so fear not and the ambience of the whole place is very classy, with $7,900 paintings decorated on the wall which are for sale, and colourful stools.<br><br>Powersupply sockets are locked with a TSA lock so no one can steal their power lol.Looking at their display of sweet awesome tarts, I wanted to try them all! But at $8.80 each, my bank account didn&#39;t concur with my stomach.They don&#39;t serve alot of cooked food, but they do serve some sandwiches and a waffle item.<br><br>1. Chicken Mushroom Pie $5.50<br>This was more of a snack sized pie, it&#39;s really tiny and for $5.50, I didn&#39;t see or taste any chicken or mushroom. Wasn&#39;t impressed by this.<br><br>2. Seasonal Fruit Tart $8.80<br>I loved the sweet fruits, the strawberries were huge, but to command an $8.80 price tag, it&#39;s a bold move! The tart itself was crumbly and it wasn&#39;t too sweet. They definitely can make good tarts, I did enjoy it! But will I come back here for this again? Probably not.<br><br>3. Chocolate Tart $7<br>Supposedly highly raved about, this was an interesting one, it was chocolate mousse on the inside but it wasn&#39;t too dense/jerlat/heaty/&#34;makes you feel like you&#39;re going to get a sorethroat&#34;. So I actually liked this one, as I normally stray away from chocolate tarts.<br><br>All in all, a good place to chill and if you like tarts and have a deeper wallet than your stomach can hold, go for it and try Drips! I know for a fact, I want to try alot more of their tart offerings but I just can&#39;t bear to fork out $9 for another one!

text: We wanted to check out some cafes in this area and we were enticed by Drips&#39; tart selection. I got the egg tart and lemon tart, as well as a strawberry smoothie. <br>Overall, I wasn&#39;t blown away by the tarts, especially for the price. I was expecting more flavor from the lemon tart, as it seemed more sugary than anything. The egg tart was pretty good, though. Finally, I wasn&#39;t a fan of the smoothie as the berries were sour. <br><br>The place was pretty big with lots of seating, so it&#39;s a good place to hang out. I can&#39;t say how good their coffee is, so maybe I&#39;ll pop in to try it out again.

text: Seen this place numerous times and finally step in here today. Does not help that they only open at 11am... Usually go looking for food before that on a weekend... <br><br>Came here after a heavy breakfast, looking for coffee. Ordered a Long black and it is good. Generally don&#39;t like the sourness in black coffee that some cafes tends to do. <br><br>Pastries, tarts and cakes looks absolutely delicious! Can&#39;t wait to come back next time to try them. They do have savoury and breakfast menu too. <br><br>At this time of the day, things are quiet, two tables (besides myself) occupied. There are sofa seating are and tables and chairs, big enough of a setting. <br><br>Going to come back for the food next time around <br><br>Update : quiche and salad meal is nice :) price tag at $8.30, plus a coffee with that nice light meal for under $14.<br><br>And now the tarts/cake ...

text: A small cafe that serves really good desserts for a reasonable price. We got many of their tarts to share. No complaints at all. What makes the difference (to me) is that the tart shell is perfect in thickness, crispness and butteriness.

text: I almost always come here only for one thing - their tarts (sliced, whole minis), some of the bests I&#39;ve had around.<br><br>First discovered their tarts and pastries from the tiny neighbourhood store at Tanglin Halt - Fredo Galaxy some years ago, so when Drips opened up at Tiong Bahru (near me), I was thrilled. It&#39;s located a little away from the &#34;main attraction&#34; streets where 40 Hands, Books Actually, Tiong Bahru Bakery, Orange Thimble are... so it&#39;s usually less crowded, a good thing if you&#39;re just looking for somewhere to sit down without having to queue or jostle with others.<br><br>Drips dons a modern, white-tiled, high ceiling decor, a nice space to chill but honestly, not one that I dine-in frequently. I do swing by often enough to get their tarts to-go for friends&#39; home parties, picnics, birthdays and such, but that&#39;s about it. Looking pass the pastries display to the menu on the wall, you&#39;ll find there isn&#39;t much else that excites - a tiny selection of sandwiches, coffees and tea-bag teas, mostly somewhat overpriced.<br><br>I will still highly recommend Drips for their tarts and cakes, but for a tea time outing that&#39;s a little less damaging to your pocket, here&#39;s what I usually do: have your pick and splurge on one of their delicate bakes, pack it up in a box... then hop on over to Tiong Bahru Food Centre, order a local soul-warming cup of Teh (milk tea), find a nice big table and dig it. Bliss - economical version ;)

Drips has script on their window that clearly proclaims, &#34;We specialize in tarts.&#34;<br><br>Perhaps it was out of desperation that I came here looking for a savory, as I thought I&#39;d given Tiong Bahru Bakery too much of my money throughout the week. Additionally, I was pressed for time so I was hoping I could grab something quick nearby to hold me over. <br><br>We all make mistakes. Today, mine was buying the ham and cheese pizza.<br><br>From the looks of it, I figured it&#39;s been sitting out for at least a few hours. After ordering, I thought the cashier would make the extra effort to heat it up for me. She didn&#39;t.<br><br>So after paying $7.80 (cringe) I hightailed back to the office and nuked it in the office microwave. The result was a still-tough piece of bread with horrible melted cheese and overcooked pieces of ham. Trying to eat it with a fork and spoon (due to a lack of butter knives and uneven hotspots) proved futile. I took 3 bites and my appetite was ruined.<br><br>Kids, listen to the proclamation and just stick with the tarts.

text: Cute place, a lot bigger than expected. <br><br>Lets get down to it...<br><br>No free wifi boohoo<br><br>Fruit Tarts (had the strawberry blackberry)<br>Fruits are plump, fresh and delicious, custard can be a little smoother, but the pate sucree base is buttery and light.<br><br>Chocolate brownie/cake<br>Quite dry and chalky...<br><br>Skinny Cappuccino (smooth, good)<br><br>The overall space is light and airy...but I am very disturbed by the amount of fruit flies that are hanging around every nook and cranny...whats up with that??<br>One of them is hanging on the wall right beside me...and his friend is just a few inches to the left. They&#39;re just chilling out, buzzing only when disturbed. <br><br>Please get this place cleaned up a little better...You&#39;re lucky the health board isn&#39;t here right now.

Okay so the tarty tarts are still unspectacular and coffee HORRIBLE but DUDES (and DUDETTES) you have to try:<br><br>a) Sticky Cinnamon Bun<br>This should be called their sticky cinnamon caramel BOMB instead. It&#39;s fantastic. Cinnamon is light but detectable, and SO MUCH GOOEY CARAMEL you&#39;ll feel your heart race.<br><br>b) (fancy name) Chocolate Tart<br>HOOOOLY COW that was good. Rich, with a firm, tasty pastry base, I was quite full when I was eating this and it was so rich it was a bit much but it was so good I couldn&#39;t stop myself. It was one of those OMG SO GOOD TOO MUCH BUT SO GOOD I should probably stop BUT I CAN&#39;T.<br><br>Why am I not bumping this up a star? <br><br>After you&#39;ve tried their coffee, you&#39;ll understand.

text: Having quite a fair bit of searches for Drips on my blog, I can tell that this place is still quite a place of interest among Singaporeans. This is one of the last few shops to open up in Tiong Bahru before there was a lull (and now there&#39;s Tiong Bahru Bakery) but Drips specializes in fruit tarts. That is very obvious. The shop space itself is very large, which is rare. It almost felt like there is too much space and not enough furniture!<br><br>The decor is once again vintage and retro inspired. Pretty decent ambiance. However when I visited this place on a Saturday afternoon they have also ran out of almost everything! Can&#39;t nobody get some decent food nowadays at a cafe?<br><br>When we were about to leave however a fresh batch of tarts came out of the oven. They looked absolutely delicious! I might revisit to try them.

text: Wandering the increasingly hip streets around the insides of Tiong Bahru, I chanced upon what appeared to be a rather run-of-the-mill cafe, so I walked in and it turned out to be anything but.<br><br>Maybe I exaggerate a little - there is nothing quite special about its interior - very modest, no real frills, but a typically modern clean look about it. Clearly the spotlight would be on their desserts. <br><br>I must admit to having been taken aback by the prices on display at the shop. Having just come from Tiong Bahru Bakery where I had a croissant for $2.50 (and what a croissant that was!), I was left quite confused when I found the price of a croissant at $4.50 here, and none of the cakes for anything less than $6, a little more than I felt prepared to. Nevertheless, I felt intrigued as to how a little cafe like this had planned to thrive in the Singapore&#39;s increasingly saturated market with such high prices, so decided to give it a go.<br><br>I asked the man by the dessert counter what he would recommend if I was only going to get one thing and one thing only, and he was quick to point out that their signature dish was the mixed fruit tart ($7.80), so I duly asked for one before he could say another word.<br><br>On the walk to the back of the cafe to pick a table, I was captivated for a fair moments by a display of drip coffee by their coffee counter, a technique that I have found to be fairly trendy on my travels, but pretty rare in Singapore. <br><br>Back to the tart, and I guess you could say it was as good as it could get - pretty much perfect in fact, but genuinely nothing that really blew my mind. The tart was topped with such a generous castle of raspberries and blueberries, crowned with the most luscious of cherries, which was true to its deep colour. The berries were surprisingly sweet, especially when raspberries can often get pretty sour. <br><br>The tart was wonderfully made, not at all crumbly, but not rock hard either. This was filled in with a very consistent helping of custardy cream (or is it creamy custard?) that was not at all overly sweet. <br><br>As I said, this was as good as it gets, and if you&#39;re willing to fork out to find your perfect fruit tart, you probably don&#39;t need to look no further. I just didn&#39;t feel, and maybe will never feel, like I would need to pay so much for dessert in a no-frills cafe, and the simple man that I am would have been just as happy with the mixed fruit tart I&#39;d find from the Delifrance around the corner from my house.

Drips makes a good cuppa with their intricate siphon technique. I&#39;m still sticking to my espresso blends though. Not quite the coffee connoisseur yet. Hopefully the coffee workshop that i&#39;m attending next week will increase my understanding of Mr. Joe! Aromatic latte ($4.80) that is not too acidic and lightly sweetened by the milk. Pretty smooth on the palate. I didn&#39;t need sugar with this one. <br><br>So desserts before the mains! Had the Mixed berries tart ($7) which was amazing. I love the crunchy shortbread crust, which has the right amount of butter and salt. I tasted a hint of a nutty almond paste in base. Perhaps that&#39;s their secret. The cream custard was smooth and slightly eggy, goes perfectly with the plump sweet strawberries and blackberries. Perfect summer dessert alert!<br><br>The chocolate tart is made from a high percentage of cocoa. Same pastry base as the Mixed Berries tart but this time with a rich dark solid filling. I like my chocolate dark and slightly bitter and this has the right balance of sweetness.<br><br>Desserts are better than the mains. Gotta have is the Avocado cheesecake which they only make to order. If you&#39;re lucky there may be extra from the batch that they sell.

Come to Tiong Bahru for whatever reason - all the hipster hangouts, the rockstar market, the hawker food, but make sure you step in here for the fruit tarts.<br><br>Yeah, they&#39;ve got other things on the menu, but when you set your eyes on the tarts in that display fridge, you&#39;ll know that there&#39;s not much else you want to look at.<br><br>THEY ARE GORGEOUS. And I&#39;m talking about pastry here. Chef Alfred&#39;s done this for years, first at the Shangri-La in Singapore, and then they sent him to work with and train their chefs in London for six years! He&#39;s been home for a while now, and after opening a smaller first joint in the Tanglin Halt area, he&#39;s come to hipster-ville to show them what dessert should be like.<br><br>I&#39;ve tried a good number of them tarts, and my favourites have to be the brandied cherry, and the pear ones. I could type a good chunk of text telling you about how luscious and full the fruit looks, the mirror-like glaze, the flakiness of the crust, and the vanilla-beany goodness of the custard, but I&#39;ve said too much already.<br><br>They go quick, so make sure you order as soon as you get in the doors!

Best fruit tarts in town, hands down. Pastry chef Alfred Chan once baked in the kitchens of Shangri-La, but prefers baking in the heartlands where he has the opportunity to interact with his customers. His years of expertise has made him a master in desserts, which led to the opening of Drips, a quaint cafe in the charming Tiong Bahru neighbourhood, to the benefit of us mortals who can&#39;t afford to dine at Shangri-La. <br><br>I am a big desserts fans (a girl always has stomach for sweets!), and fruit tarts are easily one of my most favourite form of after meal delights. I&#39;ve always been a ice cream or cake kind of girl, until I discovered the fruit tarts at Drips. Sweet pastry shells are filled with delicious custard, then generously stacked with fresh fruits (the strawberries on their tarts are the biggest I&#39;ve seen in Singapore). I don&#39;t think my words will do the tastiness of these tarts justice. All I can say is, you don&#39;t know fruit tarts until you&#39;ve tried the ones at Drips. These precious tarts tend to run out quickly so I wish you all the best in coming at the right time. <br><br>The reason why I gave Drips four stars is because their mains are rather mediocre. I would suggest that you enjoy a cheap and hearty meal at Tiong Bahru market a few minutes&#39; walk away before coming here for dessert.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/c618kTwJwkPhYJG9VYDUbg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/drips-singapore?reviewid=RzZuiMAM6sNxi5RlW5ldqw&select=c618kTwJwkPhYJG9VYDUbg', 'altText': 'Photo of Drips - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Popped by for lunch one day with a couple of colleagues, and found Drips to be bright and cheery. Cute retro furniture and bright seats, and the seating area at the back even boasts a terrarium. Menu is pretty limited, and I went with a smoked ham sandwich and pear tart. The sandwich was generously filled with ham and vegetables, and slathered with whole grain mustard; my favorite. Strangely, it also came with two cucumber slivers and a small tomato. Not sure if this is a weak attempt towards fulfilling their customers&#39; fibre intake of the day. Pear tart was ok, not bad. My colleagues found it way too sweet though, which I agree. I do like the firm tart shell and creamy filling though. Price wise, rather taxing on the wallet. Definitely not somewhere you could patronize on a weekly basis.

With all these cafes popping up around town, I didn&#39;t really find anything outstanding about Drips. Decor and ambience wise, it is decidedly ordinary.<br><br>Although I heard many good things about the dessert and coffee at Drips before going, i found the coffee decent but not to the standard of other competing cafes in the area like Forty Hands. The tart I tried was well made, but what more can you really say about a fruit tart. It wasn&#39;t anything very special.<br><br>The prices at Drips are also higher than average and I didn&#39;t think my overall experience really matched the price tag.

Having heard and read quite a bit on the fruit tarts at Drips, I finally visited the cafe one Monday afternoon. The cafe is pretty simply decorated, a little hippie and slightly retro with high ceilings that gives the cafe a spacious feel. <br><br>I was looking forward to their special fruit tart, which was unfortunately sold out. I settled for the blackberry almond tart and the cherry brandy tart instead. The blackberry almond tart was the better of the two. With a great balance of tanginess of fresh blackberries and sweet, accompanied with a slightly crisp yet crumbly crust, it was absolutely delightful. The cherry brandy tart was a little less exciting and I found it a little too sweet. <br><br>The coffee there is not fantastic but is good enough to go along with their yummy tart!

An excellent place for tarts and other assorted desserts, Drips is located near Tiong Bahru market and is really more accessible than it actually looks. A five minute walk from Tiong Bahru MRT station is all it takes to enjoy the cosy indie cafe and should you drive, there&#39;s ample parking lots to be had. So far, the service I&#39;ve had is pretty top notch, considering there&#39;s like only 2 or 3 staff (I&#39;ve seen) that handles all the customers. Orders are swiftly taken and processed to keep wait times to a minimal and diners happy. The cafe is spacious and seating is spread out nicely, enabling you to have your own quiet little corner to just sit back and enjoy your desserts and drinks. So far, there are sandwiches for mains should you feel puckish, but they&#39;re relatively cookie cutter and taste wise, nothing much to scream or rave about.

Â Ambience really much better than the bar indeed for after work hours working crowd. Â Was told be the staff that they will start serving breakfast. Â Think that is a good idea as we deliberately went over to Lokal for breakfast before coming here. Â Tried the Trilogy, Tiramisu and the Malt. Â Verdict is we are still kids!!! Looks like the Bars combo suit us better.

text: Oh wow, the prices are high compared with what I&#39;m used to paying in the USA.<br><br>In Miami pay a little less than $5 for a tall coffee and here it was about $7.5<br><br>The place was clean, with nice background music, and wonderful service.<br><br>I got my Singapore Mug in here, as usual when I travel and I love it!!

text: I usually like the matcha latte and the shaved ice at Tsujiri. This is a new outlet across the road from 313@Somerset where it used be at. <br><br>Somehow the shaved ice and matcha latte here are not as good as those I had at 313 and at 100 AM (also closed down now). I am not sure what is the issue but the taste is not there. <br><br>The place is also quite tiny and the walkway just fits the width of a stroller. Â So if you are going to bring your child with stroller, it will be better to sit near the entrance instead of all the way inside.<br><br>I am just glad that there is still an outlet in the Orchard Road area.

text: I have been going here every morning for quite some time, it always has been the same.<br><br> Other than the fact that the food is amazing, the people who work their can be quite rude, it&#39;s rare that you get someone nice taking your order. They are famous for their crossaint but they always run out- do they not think to make more earlier? you can see the frustration in every customers face when they get told their items aren&#39;t available rudely. The service is also incredibly slow.

text: TBB hasn&#39;t really gotten very much love since it opened to much fanfare a few years back, and I&#39;d just like to drop it, and this branch in the Holland Village area, some love. Â I appreciate consistency because it keeps my borderline OCD from a border-crossing. Â Consistency means that all I need to account for are trading hours and I know when I walk into a TBB and order a croissant, I can expect on-the-money flakiness, a bready almost dough-moist corpus, and an enveloping buttery nose. Â I want and need that kind of reassurance in a world where things can turn on a tweet, and TBB has always been dependable in delivering on that promise of consistency and consistent goodness. Â The Holland Village TBB at Chip Bee is no exception. Â  Nice that it&#39;s also located near plenty of parking at the Raffles Clinic building right behind it and within neighborly proximity to the Daily Scoop! Â Hang in there Holland V TBB, it shouldn&#39;t only be banks that are dependable in an increasingly undependable world.
Kind of a nice place to just get a snack, a coffee, and do some work. Nice surprising addition to the area.

text: For me its not just that this place is known for the quality of its cupcakes but its service and genuine customer service. <br><br>A regular customer that goes at least a couple times a month to taste their yummy specials is something I look forward to every visit.<br><br>They are also prompt to answer my queries and orders via email that I am really pleased about.<br><br>I really appreciate and will always remember the time that the service staff going all out to make my party an awesome one by paying attention to my needs. <br><br>A definite recommendation for sweet treat lovers like me who just want a personal touch of service amidst the commercialisation of the cupcake business in Singapore.<br><br>Do check out their facebook page for their awesome promotions and monthly specials. A definite must try!

text: This stall is a cupcake bakery that sells gourmet and heavenly cupcakes in different sizes and even in pop sticks. They have a wide variety of flavours and all taste yummy. The service is also extraordinary as it is a small stall after all and they make customers feel at home. <br><br>My favourite cupcake flavour has got to be the strawberry burst as it has fresh strawberries and it is topped with strawberry cream cheese frosting! Simply divine. Price wise it was quite reasonable as well. A good option for parties or gatherings as it brings people closer when you talk about the flavours and textures of the cake.<br><br>Overall a good place to have your cupcakes and one of the few cupcake stores in Singapore that actually sell nice cupcakes with so many varieties.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/PKhZ9OIsxFq7gXhGjCKhEA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/swirls-bake-shop-singapore?reviewid=nwAvJbudYmKOTz9-rM7vYw&select=PKhZ9OIsxFq7gXhGjCKhEA', 'altText': 'Photo of Swirls Bake Shop - Singapore, Singapore. Small but bright and cheery shop', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Small but bright and cheery shop'}]
text: There are too many cafes and not enough bakeries in Singapore! Luckily for us, Swirls Bake Shop opened up at the very trendy neighbourhood of Rodyk Street which is very near to Kith cafe and Toby&#39;s Estate. Serving up cupcakes in various shapes, flavours, sizes and colors, Swirls Bake Shop was opened up by a charming couple who decided to start a business together. Very brave I must say. The lady boss came from a fashion background so the shop had design influences from that. They then embarked on a cupcake tour of USA to taste all the cupcakes for RESEARCH purposes. Isn&#39;t that fun? They specialized in tasting red velvet cupcakes as well, which is coincidentally my favorite.<br><br>I heard mixed reviews about Swirls. Some say good, some say bad. Timeout magazine said it was &#34;possibly the best-tasting cupcakes we&#39;ve ever had&#34;.<br><br>It is quite a small but cozy space that is divided into the kitchen and the shopfront. There are 4 chairs inside along a small counter, and more chairs outside.<br><br>All the cupcakes sold do not have swirly icing which is ironic since the shop is called Swirls. We found that that is because the icing is &#39;handswirled&#39; with a flat knife instead of piped from a bag. That&#39;s why every cupcake is unique.<br><br>Well. The taste testing around all of the States did not go to waste. I tried the Red Velvet and found that it was really delicious! The cake was soft and fluffy, adequately moist and looked so good with the red coloring. It was not too sweet and all together just very enjoyable.<br><br>For the rest of the cupcakes I found them rather average. The problem I have with cupcakes is that they tend to be very very sweet, so much so I will normally just scrape off most of the icing and eat the cake with a thin layer of it. <br><br>It paled slightly in comparison to Plain Vanila Bakery&#39;s cupcakes, but on its own it does pretty well.

Swirls Bake Shop is a gourmet American cupcake bakery that has been described as the &#34;Best cupcake store Singapore has seen&#34; in a mere 6 months since its opening. Nestled in the Rodyk estate, it has garnered a strong following from the expatriate crowd and locals alike with their luscious cupcakes and wide variety of flavors (they have 101 thus far).<br><br>This did not come easy. Former fashion stylist Alia S Dada and husband Danish road-tripped across the USA and Europe, stopping at every bakery they could find. The cupcake lovers tried and baked countless cupcakes before finally perfecting their recipe to bring us these moist and flavorful desserts. <br><br>Strawberry Burst was a refreshing and tangy depart from the usual chocolate or vanilla cake. Fresh strawberries are blended into this one and topped with a strawberry cream cheese frosting. I like that it isn&#39;t too sweet. <br><br>The Red Velvet is extremely delightful. The interior is a moist and dense crimson chocolate and the light cream cheese frosting complements it well. <br><br>My other favorite is What&#39;s Up Doc?, a carrot-cake cupcake. This is something that i would get in the Colossal size (Giant Cupcake)! I would say it&#39;s the best carrot cake i&#39;ve tasted in Singapore. Shredded carrot is used in this cupcake and crushed pineapples were used to give it that extra zest. The cream cheese frosting is a tad too much for the tiny one though. <br><br>Everyday, Swirls will showcase different flavours from their Specials Range, which changes every month. I simply have to rave about the Tiramisu. The coffee, kahlua and cream mascarpone is a lethal combination that blew me away. It&#39;s my weakness. I would have a dozen of these anytime. <br><br>Swirls Bake Shop is definitely my favorite cupcake bakery in Singapore! Highly recommended.

A colleague brought in a box of mini Swirls Red Velvet cupcakes and I immediately fell in love. <br><br>Swirls Bake Shop is an authentic American bakery that serves a standard of 9 different flavors online (with many more in-store) in 3 sizes, &#39;Gobble Gobbles,&#34; (tiny and bite sized) &#34;Regulars,&#34; &amp; &#34;Colossals&#34; (giant sized). Their minimum order for delivery is 6 Regulars or 12 Minis and they come reasonably priced from $2.50 for Gobble Gobbles to $4.10 for Regulars <br><br>I&#39;ve only had a chance to try the Red Velvet thus far but I am definitely going back for seconds!

my favorite cupcake shop in singapore! (so far) :)<br>the cupcakes are moist and not overwhelmingly sweet.<br><br>my favorite cupcake is &#34;Nuts About You&#34; which is Chocolate cupcake with smooth peanut butter frosting...and m&amp;m peanuts.<br><br>they said their best selling item is the red velvet...but it didn&#39;t impress me.<br><br>i like the fact that they have mini cupcakes, which are good in maintaining my silhouette.

text: Singapore has recently jumped onto the cupcake bandwagon which has been popular in other countries for years. I was excited to try Swirls. But unfortunately, I was disappointed. <br><br>They have many flavors here--traditional ones and also specials like key lime and carrot cake. They also have mini cupcakes if you want to try to different flavors or cant finish a big one. <br><br>Prices here are ridiculous in my opinion. The small cupcakes which can be finished in literally one bite are $3. If I am going to pay this much for a tiny cupcake, I want it to taste amazing. It was just ok. Honestly, the three times I have tried it it was REALLY dry. Not cool for cupcakes at all. <br><br>Also, the staff here was very unfriendly. I went in and out without them saying ONE word to me--how unprofessional.

text: This place is quite large with many entrances. There are 4 main large sections where there are lots of restaurants set up. Even though there seems like hundreds of stalls here, the food doesn&#39;t seem to repeat so you can defiantly eat here everyday of your visit and still have something new to eat. All of the dishes we got seemed to be around the $8 CAD range. <br>Upon arriving to Singapore, I knew I wanted laksa everyday. We came to Maxwell enter around 11:30 am and it was already packed with lots of locals that it made it a bit overwhelming to hunt for laksa. I recommend of you are in a group, have half the group reserve and table while the other fetch for food. Lucky the food is very sharable and you can have it family style. I regret not visiting this center more than once.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/mBTNxplqHiOmTE6A_6N2pg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/maxwell-food-centre-singapore-3?reviewid=_vHycS5A6Tb76cpyS9_JrA&select=mBTNxplqHiOmTE6A_6N2pg', 'altText': 'Photo of Maxwell Food Centre - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Delicious hawker center that I was able to nosh at several time during my stay in Singapore! The center consists of a ton of food vendors situated next to each other in rows, with seating in between. There are SO many options offering a ton of different cuisines from the many different cultures that exist within Singapore. <br><br>A signature dish, hainanese chicken rice, was my absolute favorite, and one of the options that was offered by most vendors. I ended up having that a few times, along with many other dishes, desserts, and drinks. All the food was absolutely fantastic, and was one of the biggest things I miss about my trip!<br><br>The tables are first come first serve, but the turnover is quick and workers clear the tables very efficiently. The people watching is great as well, and the location is fantastic as you are in the middle of everything.

text: Quintessential hawker food center experience. For foodies this place can be overwhelming because you literally don&#39;t know where to look first, especially if your really hungry like we were. Just know wherever you land, you&#39;re going to have some incredibly tasty food for like pennies on the dollar. We had 3 entree sized dishes and 2 huge beers for 25 SD (Around 18 USD.<br><br>Expect to share a table especially during peak times but who cares you&#39;re there for one thing. Highly recommend trying at least once during your visit to Singapore. Enjoy this streetfood experience and do yourself a favor and try EVERYTHING!

text: Singapore most iconic dish- -Hainanese Chicken Rice has attracted tourists from all over for a taste of their famous chicken rice.<br><br>While Maxwell Hawker Center has a myriad of other sweet and savory dishes available, it is most recognized for this particular dish. <br><br>This monochromatic dish may seem deceptively boring, it&#39;s anything but. It has a sweet and savory tenderness to the meat and glistening soft skin that is enhanced by their homemade chili sauce made by blending chilies, lime juice, ginger, oil and other aromatic ingredients together. Served with rice that was cooked to perfection in the chicken broth making way for a fragrantly delicious rice. <br><br>While visiting this food court, we couldn&#39;t go without comparing this famed dish from two different rival stalls- -Tian Tian and Ah Tai (ex-veteran chef from Tian Tian). Therefore, in my true fashion, I did just that! <br><br>Tian Tian, renowned for it&#39;s Hainanese chicken rice has amass praises from the likes of Anthony Bourdain and Gordon Ramsay. The rice is the cornerstone of Tian Tian due to the richness of the broth that it&#39;s cooked in and the gravy they drizzle on top to accentuate the dish. Served only with a side of chili sauce. <br><br>Ah Tai, while lesser known, their chicken rice is equally if not better than its counterpart. You get the same flavor profile and texture from both stalls and the only thing that truly sets them apart is the fact that you get a bowl of chicken soup (perfect accompaniment for washing down your meal with) plus there&#39;s hardly any queue. <br><br>For something sweet post-meal we tried out the kaya toast and kopi from the 1950&#39;s Coffee stall. The name and photos looked promising but, unfortunately it fell short. The toast as well as the coffee lacked flavors that I&#39;ve grown accustomed to. The kaya jam tasted off while the coffee was bitter without the proper balance of the condensed milk to sweetened it up a bit. However, at the very least it fixed my sweets craving. <br><br>Overall you&#39;ll be happy with either stalls and will leave wanting more!

text: We came here the first night we arrived to Singapore and were so happy to try all the food here. There are so many options but my favorite was the soy beancurd at Lao ban! They have original and almond flavor and both are delicious! <br><br>Everything we tried exceeded our expectations! <br>We came back the next day! <br>We only spent $20 for dinner for two and was soooo full! <br>One of the best hawker center we went to!

One of the more popular hawker centers in the city. They serve mainly hainan chicken, bbq chicken and some dessert places, mixed in with a couple of non local food stands. <br><br>Tried two of the hainan chicken stands along with the Chinese bbq. Sugar cane juice, Beancurd pudding all a must. <br><br>Affordable prices and worth eating. <br><br>Some places do close down on various days and hours. If you like bean curd pudding must try lao ban right at the front of the hawker center. Don&#39;t go to anywhere else in the center.

text: Maxwell Hawker Centre is the best in Singapore. The food here has some good choices include the Tian Tian Hainanese Chicken, Maxwell Drink and more. Tian Tian use to be the pass Michelin Star winner. The hawker center has good high roof. The high roof separated the heat of the sun. Many nearby business come here for lunch. <br><br>I got the Tain Tain bottom section quarter chicken. What we call dark meat. I also got the roasted chicken instead broil white chicken. It is great and flavors full. The cost is a little more expensive $8.5 SG. But the taste is great. Worth the money. I also got the mango soya bean milk shake. The use soybean mixed with mango meat and blended with ice. Great drinks indeed. <br><br>I enjoy my time here since it is 3 pm. No line in compare to 12 noon lunch time. So avoid the crowds is important.

text: This is a MUST VISIT in Singapore. You have to try the Hainanese Chicken Rice - this is Maxwell&#39;s specialty and 1 in 4 stalls here sells it. Also try drinking a fresh coconut or sugar cane water. Great quality food for cheap prices. Located just outside Singapore&#39;s Chinatown. <br><br>There are sinks around the perimeter of the dining area for you to wash your hands before/after eating. Bus your own tables at the tray shelves nearby. Some of the staff are super elderly (I swear one of the men I saw sweeping the floors and picking up litter was 90 years old) and appreciate tips from tourists. <br><br>If you&#39;re feeling something sweet and icy, highly recommend the dessert stalls. Their jellies and fruits are fresh and house-made. <br><br>Definitely try to come during a peak dinner hour. Any other time of day and most of the stalls will be closed, limiting what would otherwise be a great variety of options.

text: More than just chicken rice. The Maxwell hawker Centre is a foodies Mecca. <br><br>Stroll all the stands before settling on your choices. <br><br>Be choosy. Go to the places that are crowded. They&#39;re probably doing something right. <br><br>The beauty of this place is the focused simplicity. <br><br>Each stand is usually famous for 1-2 dishes. <br><br>Seek and discover.

text: This Hawker Center was the first one I hit up on my quick 24hr trip to Singapore, and it was well worth it. <br><br>Well, I do wish that I had more time to hit up this center a bit earlier in the night, as more than half the stalls were already closed by the time I got there around 8ish. Also, the popular stalls that were still open, had only one or two dishes left on their menu. <br><br>HOWEVER, it doesn&#39;t mean that the food options that were left weren&#39;t delish!! Laksa was on my list of dishes to try out, and it was honestly a pescatarian dream. How in the world do you eat a steamy hot noodle soup in the middle of steamy hot humid Singapore? Well you chase it down with a chilled beer, of course. <br><br>Everything in this center is about $5 or less! Grab a table or share a table. We shared a table with two Singaporean grandpas who told us what to eat next and where to go. Everyone&#39;s super friendly. It&#39;s also a quick 10min walk from the closest MRT station. <br><br> Happy grubbin! 5 stars

text: I am embarrassed to say that even tough I&#39;ve spent much of my adult life in and around Asia, including the Southeast and Southwest countries and Asian Pacific, I had never tried to Hainanese Chicken Rice. Not because it didn&#39;t look good; I just always found something that struck my fancy instead. Until my 30th or 40th time to the hawkers&#39; Maxwell Food Center. <br><br>The problem is now I can&#39;t find it anywhere else that was any where near as good! And talk about a pain the ass to make. So you&#39;re stuck, knowing where you can get this fantastic dish, but living half a planet away and pricey plane ticket to get there. Such are life&#39;s first-world dilemmas. <br><br>Anyway, there are plenty of options in terms of stalls that serve Hainanese Chicken, but this is the one I preferred... though I&#39;m not sure there is enough of a difference to warrant standing in a long line versus a shorter one. You&#39;ll have to explore it yourself.

text: The food and travel YouTubers that I follow (i.e. Mark Wiens, Mike Chen, Luke Martin, etc.) ... all RAVE and have said pretty positive things about Maxwell Road Hawker Centre. I came here twice actually .... it&#39;s mostly because I wanted to try Tian Tian Chicken &amp; Rice and sadly they were closed for BOTH days when I came here. :&#39;( I visited Singapore after Chinese New Year so many vendors were also closed too. I&#39;m not sure they were on vacation during this time or closed their stalls early.<br><br>Stalls that I tried:<br>2/20/2018 late afternoon (~2pm):<br>-Stall #52 &#34;Hong Xiang Hainanese Chicken Rice&#34;: I don&#39;t recommend coming here when the line is super long. They were extremely slow and they were stingy with the rice that day.<br>-Stall #62 &#34;Rojak, Cockles and Popiah&#34;: Got the popiah. It was made to order and it was delicious.<br>-Stall #91 &#34;Lao Ban Soya Beancurd&#34;: Got the original beancurd. It was a nice refreshing tofu dessert.<br><br>2/21/2018 early dinner (5pm):<br>-Stall #7 &#34;Ah Tai Hainanese Chicken Rice&#34;: Good chicken and rice. There could be a long line here too but the line goes by fairly quick.<br>-Stall #78 &#34;Muar Sugarcane&#34;: Got the ice kachang and it was a nice refreshing shaved ice treat.<br><br>I will be back again one day to try:<br>-Stall #10&amp;11 &#34;Tian Tian Chicken &amp; Rice&#34; (Hopefully, they will be open when I visit!!!)<br>-Stall #54 &#34;Zhen Zhen Porridge&#34;<br><br>Take the MRT to Chinatown stop and it&#39;s on the Downtown (BLUE) line. Then, you have walk about 5+ minutes to get here.

First time in Singapore and first hawker center that my friend and I have ever been to and this place is great! This is essentially a huge cafeteria containing 50+ stalls of food, drinks, snacks and everything you would want if you were starving, though that would be financially dangerous as you could buy a lot and still have another 50+ stalls to try. Although there are a good amount of stalls, there are probably 3-5 versions of the same stall, which one is better? that is dependent on the person although I&#39;m sure most agree some are better than others.<br><br>The more popular stalls stand out easily as people literally stand out in a really long line for that particular stall which makes you low-key want to try it because you&#39;re just wondering &#34;is it 30 people in line good?&#34; and then you make your way into the 20+ minute line instead of a 1 min line that serves the same thing in hopes of 2% better taste but to each their own haha. <br><br>All the stalls here have a great selection and I&#39;m sure wonderfully tasty food (not that I would know since I haven&#39;t tried them all). I had the hainanese chicken rice from two places, Tian Tian and Ah Tai, the two most popular chicken rice stalls. Although Tian Tian had the reputation and the lines, I found the more superior stall to be Ah Tai&#39;s as his had more overall flavor and taste and just had better portions for the price compared to Tian Xian&#39;s. <br><br>There&#39;s a good number of other stalls and hawker centers to try and I certainly will be back to compare which stalls fair the best!

text: A must visit hawker center when visiting Singapore. Â If you have an appreciation for local flavors this place is a foodies paradise and home to the Tian Tian chicken rice! Â There is just something about the atmosphere of being surrounded by locals and visitors, sitting down and eating a meal that I just absolutely love. Â There is a wide variety of food from savory to sweet to choose from. Â Also be forewarned that it&#39;s not in an air conditioned building so feel that south east asia heat and humidity penetrating against your skin. Â <br><br>Located in the heart of Chinatown and walking distance from the Chinatown MRT stop make sure to stop by Maxwell!

text: This has gotta be my favorite hawker center in Singapore! <br><br>There are so many tasty gems that you can find all under one roof! Selling a variety of inexpensive yet delicious food from different ethnic groups. The location was pretty accessible, just a couple minutes walk from Chinatown MRT, or in our case we took Uber. Popular among the local as well as the tourist, you can expect this place to be buzzing. <br><br>Some of the things to look forward here are the famous Tian Tian Chicken Rice (stall #10-11), Fuzhou Oyster Omelette (stall #5) as well as their Marina South&#39;s Char Kway Teow (stall #35). Everything we had was delightful and guaranteed to induce food coma. To wash down the grease, there are also many fruit shake stalls, but my suggestion is you gotta try their sugar cane... So refreshingly sweet! <br><br>Casual quick eats, tons of choices with delicious taste and value for the money... can&#39;t help but to fall in love with this hawker center!!

text: I came here pretty late and was disappointed to see alot of stalls were closed, Not sure if they close at certain times or ran out of food . Anyhow I browsed the stall and noticed a stall with a very long queue, so I decided to eat there because it had to be good right? it was a place serving duck, chicken, rice and noodles and it had a rating of A. I had the roasted duck with Â rice. There&#39;s a nice sauce they add to the duck and the rice and man.. It was amazing. It was about $3 and was delicious, cant best that. Also look for the stalls with fresh juice, I ordered pink guava and it was amazing and no added sugar.

text: If you are visiting Singapore and want to have REAL local food, Maxwell Road Hawker Center is your spot! Here you can find a lot of typical Singaporean and Chinese food that will have you craving for more! Â <br><br>Forget about most of the fancy restaurants around Marina Bay Sands and Orchard Road! Grab the MRT and head to China Town where you&#39;ll find this little gem. I do recommend you to bring cash because some of the places don&#39;t accept cards, plus everything is so cheap is not even worth it to put it on the card. <br><br>When you visit the Hawker Center, I would recommend you to FIRST get your drink and THEN your food...you&#39;ll thank me later! Also, the tables are first come, first serve..so if you see an open spot, go and get it. It can get particularly busy around lunch time, so just keep that in mind.

text: When traveling to Singapore a must stop is trying there hawkers. We decided to stop at the Maxwell hawker and boy was I impressed! I&#39;m a Ruth Chris kind of girl, I love being spoiled and served so a hawker wasn&#39;t my top thing to do. I&#39;m so glad I did because it was an experience I&#39;ll never forget!! <br><br>My favorites are the chicken dumplings and coconut water. Everything we tried there was freshly cooked the people were nice. <br><br>There&#39;s many hawkers and this one was my favorite.

The first Hawker I got to try in Singapore and I am very happy that we got to visit this one due to the great food selection!<br><br>This one is a little tucked away so be sure to refer to a map to be sure where this one is located. Venue itself is small for a hawker but still has a lot to offer! The rows of vendors and stalls was plentiful and had good variety. <br><br>There are vendors that sell Chicken Rice, Pot Stickers, and a bunch of other Singaporean classics! There&#39;s a Chicken Rice vendor here that had a very visible line right as we walked in and we knew we had to try it. Of course, it did not disappoint. Simple, fragrant, light, and savory. Definitely a must try here!<br><br>We came here a little after lunch time so a good amount of vendors were closed, so just be wary of when you visit to ensure that you&#39;re coming at a good time so you&#39;re not limiting your options. Overall, a good spot if you&#39;re in the area!

Even though I had Amoy closer to where I was staying, I would always find myself walking to Maxwell (the People&#39;s Park pathway was a nice connection to here) for my meals whether it be brunch, lunch or dinner!<br>There&#39;s something here for whatever you&#39;re craving!<br><br>I&#39;ve tried so many things!<br><br>-fu zhou oyster pancake: good amount of oysters. Do eat it when it&#39;s fresh. Was not a fan of the cilantro addition though. For some reason I had expected it to be crispier?<br><br>-almond pudding: DELICIOUS! Must get. Who knew almond pudding could taste so divine? Perfect way to cool down on a hot day for sure. If only I knew it would be so good I would&#39;ve tried their tofu puddings too but alas I only found this place on my last day.<br><br>-tian tian hainese chicken rice: no wonder there&#39;s a line at this place during lunch! The chicken was alright but the rice is where it really shines! <br><br>-hainese chicken rice (from another stall): there&#39;s something magical about the rice of chicken rice (more so than the chicken). It&#39;s on the same level as my grandma&#39;s chicken.<br><br>-cheap pancake thing: it&#39;s less than 1 sgd so I got it. The lady was kind of nasty while I was asking about which flavors were available though...so I got red bean. It was passable. I wouldn&#39;t get it again...it&#39;s basically rice cake.<br><br>-soursop juice: one of my best food discoveries during my trip! it tastes like a strawberry and pineapple hybrid! Its flesh was sort of like a tougher version of dragon fruit meets lychee? I wish I could try it again<br><br>The only things I&#39;m sad about missing out on are: the rickshaw noodles and the curry hainese rice. Every time I went they were closed unfortunately...if I visit again I&#39;ll make sure to make more time to try out more of the stalls here!<br><br>I don&#39;t know about the bathrooms though as this center is quite old...<br><br>There&#39;s also a lot of signs around promoting reduction of food waste...so I guess that means if you know you won&#39;t be able to finish all your food it&#39;s okay to ask for less! I do wonder if stall vendors would give you a discount or something for asking for less food (like less rice) though...

text: There are a lot of variety here but really came here for tian tian chicken and rice spot. Came here in November and it was hot and humid here. There are fans by the seating area but still very hot. Definitely grab a sugar cane juice or lime juice at one of the stalls!

text: A must-visit for tourists - so many different types of delicious food for cheap!<br><br>Tian Tian&#39;s Chicken Rice (4/5) - Not sure if this lived up to the hype - the rice was super delicious and had an insane amount of flavor packed into it, but the chicken itself was meh to me. The chili garlic sauce gave the dish a pretty nice kick, which I loved<br> <br>Hainanese Curry Fish (4/5) - The curry was delicate and light, which paired perfectly with the fish and rice. Nice portions for the price.<br><br>Fish Bee Hoon (4/5) - Super light fish broth with tender of pieces of fish.<br><br>Juice Farm (5/5) - Pineapple dragonfruit smoothie was so delicious! Wish I could&#39;ve tried their other smoothies as well.

text: First and only Hawker Centre I visited while in Singapore. Arrived on a weekday after 12 and it wasn&#39;t packed. There was a handful of open tables; I&#39;m guessing people didn&#39;t visit due to construction. <br><br>So the saying goes if you don&#39;t know what to eat, you have to try which ever stall has the longest line. Now here I was standing in line for their chicken and rice (with a side of vegetables because I have to get my veggies in), eagerly waiting and wondering if it&#39;s worth the hype. To be quite frank, this was a good dish. The chicken was moist and had a good texture to it. I&#39;m a little bit confused why they have (S/M/L) listed but the only size dishes offered is medium and large. Now it really depends on your preferences but I had better. For example, the chicken and rice at Siam Paragon Malls food court in Thailand is more flavorful. Their Rice is cooked with garlic and chicken stock soup creating a more flavorful mouthwatering dish. Overall I&#39;m glad I can say I tried one of the most well known dishes while visiting Singapore.

text: If you plan on coming here, don&#39;t come too late on the evening. We went after 7pm and a lot of the popular places were closed (Tian Tian, Ah Tai) because they&#39;re so popular and probably ran out of food. I knew about it prior and google has the places closing at 8 so we took a shot anyways. There were still other stalls open, but I wanna say like only 30-40% of the stalls were still open after 7pm on a Thursday evening. Still pretty packed though as it was hard to find seats. <br><br>It&#39;s under a roof, but open air space so no Air conditioning. The stall operators do understand enough English so don&#39;t be too nervous. Food was pretty good. Only regret is we didn&#39;t go earlier in the day to get the full experience

This Hawker stand has a lot of variety! Â Everything from classic Singaporean dishes to Western fare.<br><br>I got a solid education in Hainanese chicken rice and also got some good coffee in here. Â I wish I had more time to try other things as there&#39;s many different cultures represented in here! Â If you&#39;re in the area drop in and I&#39;m sure you&#39;ll find something that interests you

I&#39;ve only been in Singapore for not even a full day, and have frequented this place three times already! This is so close to my hotel, and when I don&#39;t know what I want for my 3+ meals a day. I&#39;ll stop by here and take a walk around to see what I&#39;m in the mood for. You honestly can&#39;t go wrong with anything here. I haven&#39;t had a bad meal here yet. Not to jInx myself! <br><br>There&#39;s tons of options here from Hainanese chicken rice to congee to Laksa to Indian/halal food and lots of refreshing drinks! My one stop shop for all my Southeast Asian goodies! I love getting the Hainanese chicken rice from Tian Tian&#39;s and my all time favorite sugar cane drink. <br><br>The Centre is also equipped with washing sinks and bathrooms if you need to freshen up. This place is good for people watching, and lots of cute little ol grannies and grandpas pushing their cleaning carts around to collect your plates.

This is a large hawker center in the Chinatown area. Â  Â So many choices.<br><br>I got a nice Lychee Juice. Â  People around me were going crazy for Seafood noodle soup. Â  The Hainanese Chicken Rice is very popular with many stall offering the dish. Â  <br><br>Most food can be had for less than US$5. Â  Some as low as $2.5-3, depending on what you want and how much food you want to it. Â  Usually very busy.

text: This was literally a 3 minute walk from our hotel. <br><br>This place has many options to choose from &amp; they have everything. I didn&#39;t see any Michelin stalls but I ate some really good items some better than others. The sauces used are so fresh and authentic. Some stalls open early and others only at night so go twice to experience everything.<br>Start ordering, then save a table. Try several stalls and plenty to drink as well (fresh juices &amp; beer). WARNING, most do not have or give away napkins, you must bring your own or buy a travel size Kleenex. And, dont be afraid to ask questions, most speak English. <br> <br>I do however prefer Peoples Park Complex Food Centre. The selection &amp; quality/taste were unparalleled.

We went to a lot of different hawker centers in Singapore but this one was our favourite! They had the best selection of local Singaporean fare (stir fried daikon and oyster pancake). We ordered the Hainanese chicken and rice and stir fried daikon - both were amazing and so cheap! Everything was well under $10 SGD.

text: The mix duck rice is insanely good. The flavors really well developed. I would highly recommend mr. black and white stall. Their food is also super cheap. Just for all that it was $3. You also know it&#39;s good when they got a line of people waiting to get food from them. Don&#39;t skip out and try out their food

text: I really dont know how people can eat in a hawker centre outdoors in this type of humidity and heat. Instantly makes me lose appetite and makes me feel dirty and sticky. Came for the famous chicken rice - it was good but i think its overhyped. Also had prata which i saw from a youtuber - it was good but the curry was very gamy which i didnt like. I think the curry had lamb in it

text: Maxwell may well be the best hawker centre in Singapore. It has the majority of typical Singapore dishes - Hainanese as well as Malay (ayam penyet) chicken rice, Nasi lemak, carrot cake, fish soup, peranakan, laksa, porridge, Â etc. Even western salads or ramen for unadventurous tourists. That&#39;s why both ang moh (tipped by tourist guide books or travel websites) come here. Prices are reasonable, not cutthroat as in tourist ghettos like Newton Circus. Of course, Singapore street food being so plentiful, many dishes are not represented, eg. fish head curry, prawn mee, biryani, claypot rice, sup tulang, etc. My favs are Tian Tian chicken rice, China Fritters, and Fuzhou oyster cake (see reviews).

text: If you&#39;re a fan of chicken rice or known as the Hainanese Chicken Rice dish, this hawker center is worth the stop for it. My friends and I came by here early morning to beat the crowd and found that most stalls weren&#39;t opened before 10am (weekday). For an hour, all of us wandered around looking for any open food stalls. My friends and I were looking forward to trying out Tian Tian (the famous chicken rice stall) but it wasn&#39;t opened till 10. <br><br>During the time we all were waiting, I decided to try a white carrot cake. It was similar to the taste of taro cake (dim sum dish) but overall, it was a bit lacking in texture. For the hawker center itself, it&#39;s a very spacious and open place and everything was quite clean and orderly. <br><br>When it got closer to 10am, this is the time to start lining up. Be aware of the many similar chicken rice stalls that have the same blue sign and white font as Tian Tian. I heard that these competing stalls have dishes just as good as Tian Tian but aren&#39;t as well known since Tian Tian was visited by Anthony Bourdain. <br><br>In all, got my chicken rice dish and even by the time we left (closer to 11 ish), half of the food stalls weren&#39;t opened yet, which left me a bit disappointed since I had wanted to try out more food.

Pretty much any food you could ever want for cheap prices. However a number of vendors were closed on a Sunday afternoon which limited choice and atmosphere. It&#39;s gritty for Singapore and it&#39;s hot... but definitely worth the trip!<br><br>There are a number of Michelin star places here for very cheap.

text: A must-visit for tourists - so many different types of delicious food for cheap!<br><br>Tian Tian&#39;s Chicken Rice (4/5) - Not sure if this lived up to the hype - the rice was super delicious and had an insane amount of flavor packed into it, but the chicken itself was meh to me. The chili garlic sauce gave the dish a pretty nice kick, which I loved<br> <br>Hainanese Curry Fish (4/5) - The curry was delicate and light, which paired perfectly with the fish and rice. Nice portions for the price.<br><br>Fish Bee Hoon (4/5) - Super light fish broth with tender of pieces of fish.<br><br>Juice Farm (5/5) - Pineapple dragonfruit smoothie was so delicious! Wish I could&#39;ve tried their other smoothies as well.

text: I got a chance to come here when I was in Singapore for the a couple weeks ago. I know that Singapore are well know for Hawker stand and that everyone get an options when it come to food. This hawker centre is located near Chinatown and offer three aisles of food. I feel like I was in food heaven for sure. Â We opted for the black pepper crabs and mi goreng. As for drink, I got sugar cane and it was so refreshing. The crab was so yummy and filled all black pepper all over and the mi goreng was tasty as well. I added a little lime to the mi goreng for a sour kick to it which made a different to the taste and I like it. The services was top notch where they are friendly and helpful. This place is well maintain and clean. After the meal, we walked over to Chinatown and browse around. I high recommend this place if you are in the Chinatown and want good food. I would go back here if I&#39;m in Singapore again.

This is another place to come to eat where they have multiple kinds of food stands, but this one is located primarily in china town. I thought this hawker stand wasn&#39;t as good as the other one I went the day before which was called Tiong Bahru hawker.

This Hawker stand has a lot of variety! Â Everything from classic Singaporean dishes to Western fare.<br><br>I got a solid education in Hainanese chicken rice and also got some good coffee in here. Â I wish I had more time to try other things as there&#39;s many different cultures represented in here! Â If you&#39;re in the area drop in and I&#39;m sure you&#39;ll find something that interests you
Probably the best of the hawker food centers in Singapore. Perfect balance of cleanliness and authenticity.

text: Boy was this place awesome, I went back a 2nd time and added more photos.<br><br>Place is fantastic in every way, shape, and form. I followed the long lines this time and went for the porridge with chicken and century old egg from Zhen Zhen. Best porridge I have ever had in my entire life. Having tried some top places in Hong Kong and Cambodia, this place was hands down better than all. Waited in line about 50 minutes to order my food.<br><br>Glad we had some regulars eat with us that lived in Singapore. Â We all loved the Hainanese chicken rice. Tian Tian is incredible, you can even see Anthony Bourdain&#39;s picture in the front of the place. :-)<br><br>The only thing I didn&#39;t like about this place was the heat! If it were enclosed they could put in some A/C but it is open on all sides and made it a bit uncomfortable.<br><br>Glad to have found this place on Yelp, would have gone back Kovan Hougang Food Centre which I have frequented many times on my travels to Asia. Kovan isn&#39;t bad, will probably never be as good as Maxwell Food Centre.

text: This was one of my favorite hawker centers I went to when I visited Singapore. It had a good variety of stalls, without being too overwhelming. My first night, I tried hainanese chicken rice from Ah Tai. I really wanted to try Tian Tian&#39;s, but they were closed. And there was a long line at Ah Tai, which is always a good sign. I read the articles about how the cook from Ah Tai used to cook for Tian Tian - chicken rice drama! The chicken rice set (rice, chicken, dipping sauce, soup, and veggies) was delicious! At another stall, I got the almond soya beancurd, which I guess is like a tofu pudding. That was good too! And another day, I came for lunch and had the hainanese curry rice: veggies, fried egg, pork cutlet, and curry over rice. It was also delicious and the old man working there was so nice. <br><br>It&#39;s really fun looking around and getting food from the different stalls. There are always busy, but Saturday at lunch was crazy packed. Don&#39;t be shy about sharing tables!

Plenty of cheap and good food. Â Lots of tables around but you need to get them quick. Â Although they have lots of fans, it still feels pretty hot inside. Â <br><br>We specifically came for the Tian Tian Hainanese Chicken Rice. Â We must have come after the lunch crowd, cause the line wasn&#39;t that long. Â I recommend getting a juice drink from the stall across. Â It was cheap and refreshing, and the lady working there was so helpful. Â My mom had ordered a coconut drink and the lady actually scraped out all the meat for her afterwards since her hand was injured.<br><br>Conveniently located walking distance from the Chinatown station.

text: Some might say hawker food is overrated, others say it&#39;s the best possible kind of food. None of these is absolutely true. Hawker food can be defined by its two main attributes: it&#39;s cheap and it&#39;s tasty. Don&#39;t expect amazing creativity, fancy innovation or exotic ingredients. These uncles and aunties have been cooking the same five or six dishes for a while, so they have perfected them over the years. This degree of specialisation is not usually seen on restaurants. Cooks at hawker stalls won&#39;t feel guilty about taking ingredients from tins, bags or boxes. They also won&#39;t pretend to be cooking high cuisine. Hawker food is all about flavour.<br><br>One of my favourite hawker centres is Maxwell Food Centre. Location is fantastic, right in front of the Buddha Tooth Relic Temple, in that fuzzy border between Chinatown and the CBD. During peak hours it will be bursting with people wearing office attire and name tags hanging on their belts. It&#39;s also a good spot to line your stomach before hitting Club Street, just a block away. There must be over one-hundred stalls, offering a massive variety of food for nearly all tastes. It&#39;s pointless to try and describe the variety of food present. The only thing I miss is more Indian food, there are only like three stalls selling it.<br><br>The dishes everyone should try are the sliced fish soup from stall 77 (their fried fish soup is also scrumptious), ban mian from stall 32, duck noodles from stall 71 ($3.50!), fried dumplings from stall 92 (the steamed dumplings look tempting too), and the almighty, delicious, always mouth-watering Fuzhou fried oyster cakes (at $2.00 each!) from stall 5. Absolute winner. All these stalls deserve individual reviews.<br><br>Maxwell Food Centre also boasts the famous Tian Tian chicken rice. However, I&#39;ve never tried it. Can&#39;t be bothered to queue.

This is another place to come to eat where they have multiple kinds of food stands, but this one is located primarily in china town. I thought this hawker stand wasn&#39;t as good as the other one I went the day before which was called Tiong Bahru hawker.

text: This is one of the most famous and popular hawker centres in Singapore among tourists. <br><br>The location is pretty convinient -close from the Chinatown and Club Street, about 10 mins walking from the Chinatown MRT station. It is kind of hidden so don&#39;t forget to check the map before coming here.<br><br>Most tourists are coming here for the Tian Tian Chicken Rice. When I went there around 1:30PM, there was a long line. I think I waited about 15 to 20 mins. It is very humid so make sure to bring a bottle of water with you. Expect to share a table with strangers because it is realy crowded.<br><br>The foods are reasonably priced and in my opinion and delicious. There are many stalls to pick from so you can eat here several times in a day. I would definately recommend if you want cheap and good food.

Solid hawker center, with plenty of options - more than you can imagine - and big fans cooling you down. Hurry up to get a table, though, as people fight for them. <br><br>I ordered some tasty scrambled eggs with oysters and a prawn cake.

text: If you leave Singapore without gaining weight then something is clearly wrong, unless you have fast metabolism, because the best part about Singapore is the food!! Hawker centers can&#39;t be skipped and is considered a tourist destination and a normal hang out for locals wanting a quick bite or a complete meal. <br>Maxwell Food Centre, in particular, was a place I had to go since there&#39;s a shop here Anthony Bourdain mentioned and I had wanted to visit. If, for some reason, you don&#39;t like this hawker centre, there&#39;s a dozen more like it, so don&#39;t fret haha. <br>This is the only hawker centre I visited, so I can&#39;t compare it to others. This one is quite big, with three massive rows of endless goodies and majority, if not all, were super duper cheap; I&#39;m talking like under $7 for a meal, some even less than $5! Some stall owners were friendlier than others, but you&#39;re here for the food not the service la!

Tian Tian Hainanese Chicken Rice!!! that&#39;s all we had the stomach to try in this Chinatown center with many food vendors but BOY was it worth the trip!! next time I want to try Zhen Zhen porridge &amp; the Chinese donut shop at the end<br><br>We came around 11am when not many of the stalls were open BUT there was already a line at Tian Tian (don&#39;t worry, the line goes quickly)<br><br>we definitely ordered WAY too much food for the 2 of us <br>--half chicken (steamed)<br>--2 portions of chicken rice<br>--oyster sauce flavored veggies<br><br>VERDICT? the hainanese chicken wasn&#39;t better than the chicken we tried in Melaka, Malaysia HOWEVER the loose chicken-flavored rice here was SO FLAVORFUL MMmm, can&#39;t be beat<br><br>NOTE: next time i&#39;d get the &#34;chicken drumstick rice&#34; since the dark meat is definitely tastier than the white meat &amp; it comes with rice!

Maxwell Food Centre is conveniently located near Chinatown and easily accessible by MRT. If you are a visitor to Singapore like me and with limited time, this maybe the only hawker centre you should visit,<br><br>So many choices here. A lot of tourists and locals all come here to enjoy some good food. It might not have as many stalls as the nearby Smith Street Chinese Complex but I love the design a lot more,.at least I don&#39;t feel too overwhelmed and lost.<br><br>So what are the not to miss food here? Just go and look for the longest lineups with all these locals queue up for their food even during off peak hours! I personally rather not to queue up.. but my sister went and waited over 30 minute for her fish soup and I thought she got lost!<br><br>And even if you don&#39;t want to queue up for that long, there are also other options... sometimes I just want something quick! <br><br>Tip: for a hot day, I would always pick up a cold drink or ice kachang and the wait can be more tolerable!<br><br>I guess I would be back again...and again...

text: On the eve of Singapore&#39;s 50th birthday celebration, my left-handed daughter and I had dinner at the Maxwell Food Center. By local custom, we placed a tissue packet on a vacant table and went perusing the food stalls.<br><br>With about one hundred different places serving a dizzying array of aromatic and appetizing fares, we were mystified by the choices and unable to decide what to eat. Bewildered, we just picked the longest line and waited in it. Before our eyes, the affable and impassioned chef sliced sizzling strips of pork, and heaped it atop a mountain of delicate noodles.<br><br>Returning to our table, we found a group of ill-informed tourists in our &#34;reserved&#34; seats. Overlooking this serious breach of hawker center etiquette, we moved to another table, and dug into our seasoned pork noodles. <br><br>As we savored our meals, an eloquent Singaporean gentleman with a shiny bald head approached us. He smiled broadly and said to my daughter that he had never before seen a woman hold chopsticks in her left hand. Now a 72-year-old retired professor, he went on to generously teach us about his country&#39;s short but proud history and amalgamated culture.<br><br>At the Maxwell Food Center there are a myriad of menu choices that epitomize the country&#39;s world-class food culture. Our meals were immensely enjoyable, but it was our lucky encounter with a brilliant member of Singapore&#39;s pioneer generation that proved to be a most enlightening way to celebrate Singapore&#39;s 50th birthday.

So many different choices you definitely can&#39;t go wrong! But by the time you leave you will feel like a pig! Here you can pretty much find most of Singapore&#39;s recommend cheap eats - all in one place!<br><br>Definitely worth coming back to try to try everything!<br><br>Remember to get a fresh juice! So refreshing!

5-star review for a $5 meal? yes, sir!<br><br>well I think I spent over $10 because I went back for more<br><br>you can&#39;t go wrong here. there are dozens of stalls with so many choices. chicken and rice, noodles, thai, malaysian, halal, and on and on. grab a table with some friends, a couple of large bottles of beer or coconut water and chow down. have to come here at least once every time I&#39;m in SG. and walking distance to Chinatown where you can go for dessert!

text: Nice food center in Chinatown with 3 rows of affordable Hawker stalls. It&#39;s a great way to try different foods without running around town. There are different Hainanese chicken and rice, smoothie, carrot cake ( made of radish), noodle, seafood stalls,etc! Plenty of tables and seats and short lines if any!

text: Ok, so most of the stalls start shutting down around 8:30, despite that yelp says it stays open until 11:00. I was so impressed with the food and disappointed that the stalls were closed, I went twice :)<br><br>Chicken rice. Steamed pork buns. Pho. Young coconut. dim sum for days. <br><br>Would go again in a heart beat.

text: I got a chance to come here when I was in Singapore for the a couple weeks ago. I know that Singapore are well know for Hawker stand and that everyone get an options when it come to food. This hawker centre is located near Chinatown and offer three aisles of food. I feel like I was in food heaven for sure. Â We opted for the black pepper crabs and mi goreng. As for drink, I got sugar cane and it was so refreshing. The crab was so yummy and filled all black pepper all over and the mi goreng was tasty as well. I added a little lime to the mi goreng for a sour kick to it which made a different to the taste and I like it. The services was top notch where they are friendly and helpful. This place is well maintain and clean. After the meal, we walked over to Chinatown and browse around. I high recommend this place if you are in the Chinatown and want good food. I would go back here if I&#39;m in Singapore again.

text: DELICIOUS! Â We came for the tian tian chicken. I didn&#39;t care for it. The chicken was cold and rubbery and the sauce was diluted... BUT, we also ordered char Kway teow... holy moly, was it fabulous. The noodles, sauce, and scallop slices were pure heaven on a plate. Yum! From a third vendor, we ordered beer and fresh juice drink. Ice cold and refreshing. We&#39;ll be back!

I&#39;d never heard of a hawker center until it became a reality that we would travel to Singapore. Â Considering the expense of the flight and the accommodations, any reasonable way to save some money was agreeable to us. The Maxwell Food Centre did just that for us. Â We&#39;d watched some online videos about this location and decided to try it once settled in. Â We enjoyed our beer and milk tea drinks. The chicken/rice dish left something to be desired for my wife and a lot to be desired for me. Â The rice was fine but the chicken itself was so gummy and borderline slimy, I worried I&#39;d be sick later (thankfully I wasn&#39;t). I guess I shouldn&#39;t have been surprised considering 1) how long the line was for the food booth we went to, 2) how quick the line went. &#34;Cooks&#34; were just chopping what looked like chicken at super speed and slapping the result on top of rice in a bowl and shoving it at the waiting patron, NEXT!! With all that said, if you like that kind of chicken, you&#39;ll be thrilled to have a yummy meal on the cheap. Â If we are privileged to have a future return to Singapore, we&#39;ll come to Maxwell again - one substandard experience at one food booth among -dozens- doesn&#39;t not at all mean Maxwell Food Centre is not worthy of note. Â As an example, before we left we wanted food for later so from a different booth we got breakfast sandwiches (because breakfast is delicious 24 hours a day). Â When we did get around to eating them, we both wished we&#39;d bought 4 instead of 2. Â Oh yeah, last note - when at Maxwell Food Centre, if you see an open table, do a suplex off the top rope to grab it NOW. Â Seating can be challenging when they are busy. Â Or.....just plop down at someone else&#39;s table with a little space and go for broke &#34;howdy neighbor.....&#34;

text: This hawker centre was not as big as the Chinatown one but it still had a good array of options. Lots of seating and pretty clean as well. Remember to get some sugar cane juice. There&#39;s so many sugar cane places here and juice places. The most famous stall her would be Tian Tian but unfortunately I came on a day they weren&#39;t here so I went to the other store (which has some relation to Tian Tian, you can look up the story) and it very good. But the other stores I tried, were still pretty good.

text: Great hawker center with lots of options and seating. Â Pretty clean for street food standards with order among the chaos of options. Â Gave it a 4 star because there was a wafting unclean smell in one part of the center but it&#39;s outdoors so what could you really expect. Â Tried the famous TianTian chicken rice and had a dragon fruit soursop drink to get a break from the humidity. Â <br>Have been here many years prior and in a nice way, it hasn&#39;t changed much. Â Famous chef Anthony Bourdain&#39;s visit really increased some tourist visits accompanied by a lot of selfie sticks but you can easily avoid them by walking faster. On a Sunday afternoon about hand the stands were closed, I imagine on a Saturday it&#39;s much busier.
I had the chicken curry rice. Good meal! <br>There was a power failure which made the place unbelievably sweaty. Thanks to the tender coconut water, I survived through lunch :-)

text: It&#39;s a hawker centre, a paradise for food. Albeit this place is relatively small for a hawker centre and the whole thing is under construction (you have to walk the way around the building site), this place offers whatever you feel like. Meeting up with friends who have different taste in food from you? No problem. You can find anything.<br><br>I had noodle soup first time I was here, the second was fried cockles kway teow. They have also the famous chicken rice (blame my not-eating-poultry- policy) but I didn&#39;t taste any. It&#39;s a perfect walking distance to downtown Chinatown, so if you feel like you don&#39;t want to go where tourists go, go here instead.
Ah Singapore, I can&#39;t wait to get back there; the food and people were great!

text: This is the first hawker station I&#39;ve ever visited but needless to say, it&#39;s pretty awesome. It&#39;s enclosed with tons of construction for future expansion but it&#39;s pretty easy to find. It is quite a bit hot and humid if you&#39;ve lived in colder parts, so bring a portable fan if you need one. There are fans inside above the tables as well. This hawker center is home to the infamous, Michelin star restaurant Tian Tian- the hiananese steamed chicken is a must try.
