text: My favorite food court in Singapore--I feel that they do a better job at making better quality food than the other hawker centers!<br><br>Hong Kong Soya Bean--Green tea flavor-- so delicious.<br>Porridge galor. <br>Great Chicken rice selection.<br>Lots of fresh fruit drinks. <br><br>Newly renovated, and fans installed for better air circulation. You can&#39;t go wrong, there are tons to choose from. Love it.

text: This is my favorite hawker center just because my favorite Hainan chicken restaurant TianTian Hainan Chicken is here. Â The place is easy to get to, if taxi driver doesn&#39;t know this one then he probably shouldn&#39;t be driving. The facility offers a large variety of food just like other Hawker centers. This place is clean, table gets bused really quick. Stall owners are friendly, and they all speak English. I love the fact I can order my favorite food in the morning along with a glass of beer and not feel guilty about it!

text: I&#39;m still not used to this ridiculously humid/tropical climate, so I was a bit uncomfortable and hot here and couldn&#39;t try all the foods I wanted since I didn&#39;t want to shower at Maxwell... but this is a foodie&#39;s paradise! Â The prior night, I went to the Old Airport Road FC with colleagues and didn&#39;t find this one to be much different, but there are indeed a good number of foreigners and tourists here. Â Still, the food stalls are heaven for someone who loves food.<br><br>Lao Ban dou hua - 2nd night in a row. Â Such a good cooling dessert.<br><br>Buns - I don&#39;t remember where the buns came from, but the stall basically only sold buns and I had pretty much one of each. Â I didn&#39;t like that the char siu bun had cooked cilantro in it (I love cilantro, but hate it when its been cooked), but it was still yummy as well as the pork-filled bun. Â Shumai was okay... not a big fan of shumai anyways.<br><br>We had some Malay food, which looked like stirfried instant maggi noodles with super extra spicy sauce, lots of green chilies, and anchovies. Â I couldn&#39;t eat much of this as it started to make me really hot.<br><br>To finish off, I had cheng teng at a dessert stall. Â I freaking love this stuff, so perhaps I&#39;m a bit biased. Â It may be weird for people who aren&#39;t familiar with it, but its basically a &#34;health&#34; drink. Â YUM.<br><br>I&#39;d suggest going with a local and trying a bit of everything here - can&#39;t really go wrong. Â Bring your own napkins and/or wet wipes though... seems like Singapore isn&#39;t about wiping your face and your hands unless you pay for it :P

I came on a Sunday evening and many stalls were closed. I had no idea what is good here besides the famous Tian Tian Chicken Rice stall. It was closed on Sunday so the only long line on a Sunday evening was at Ah Tai Chicken Rice stall. I believe that stall is opened by an ex-employee of Tian Tian. I did not bother queuing for that and by 6.30-7pm, the stall has sold all its chickens for the day.<br><br>Wandering around, I realized there are many chicken rice stalls in this place. In any case I tried the dry mee sua at a stall with a certificate stating its culinary achievement or something. It was similar to a fish ball noodle stall except it also included fried ikan bilis (anchovies). It was actually pretty good, and the small bowl of soup was tasty and not some watered down version of something passing off as soup. <br><br>The satay was a bit tough. Rojak was good with crispy taupok (dried bean curd puff) and you tiao (fried dough stick cut into pieces). Fried carrot cake was decent though not with mouth melting soft kueh. The ham chin peng stall saw a steady stream of customers (but no line) and was actually smaller than other places. As it was hot, fresh out of the hot oil, it was very good. <br><br>Unless you have a hankering for Tian Tian chicken rice or ham chin peng, I don&#39;t find it worth a trip just to have something you can probably get at your neighborhood food center.

text: Granted I&#39;ve been to only to Hawker in Singapore, and sadly my first experience was so good it&#39;s hard to live up to my first experience. Sadly I don&#39;t know where I was for the first time because my uber driver took me there without telling me where it was. So I&#39;m on the hunt for the Hawker from &#34;that night&#34;...<br><br>Maxwell is definitely well established and lots of options...unlike the first Hawker I went. Lots of seating area, bathroom (probably the worst condition bathroom in Singapore), and oh so cheap food. <br><br>I ate a street noodle similar to pad see ew from Thai, it was okay but not great. Noodle we&#39;re over cooked and lacking any ingredients that I saw on the photo menu...

text: I have found food stall heaven. Â It&#39;s Maxwell and I wish I lived closer to Singapore for this place alone. Â I tried everything I wanted because everything is ultra inexpensive. Â Like $3 noodles, $3 soup, $3 stir-fry. You get the idea. <br><br>I have to give a special shout out to this bun place called Creative Designs. It is a strange name but their baked goods are ultra-delish. Â I had a banana nutella filled bun and my husband has a pizza bun. I give a more favorable recommendation to the sweet over the savory, but I wish I could eat one every day.

Ok, I can see why all the hype to come here. Â But, I must be missing something if all I can give is three stars! <br><br>Yes there are probably a few stalls that make good, or even very good food. But, to walk around in the heat and humidity, to survey and observe the food, and then to wait in line for 15 minutes.... come on folks, this isn&#39;t nirvana.<br><br>Prices are cheap. ..averaging about $4-5 per bowl/plate. Beer is likely the most expensive item here @ ~$7. <br><br>For my money, I&#39;ll go to ION Food Opera, or Shaw Centre Food Court and suffer through same or slightly lower quality at slightly higher prices and enjoy air conditioning.

text: A pleasant place to visit! We&#39;ve actually visited here twice during our stay in Singapore. It truly worth $5 taxi fare from our hotel (Fullerton). We have tasted Zhen Zhen Porridge; Tian Tian Hainanese Chicken Rice; Popiah @ Rojak Popiah &amp; Cockle; King-Hwa sliced Fish Bee Hoon; Fu Jee Fu-Jo fish ball. All very delicious. Some people had to wait for 15-20 min during even non-busy hours. This place was almost always packed.

text: Youtube Video of Singapore/Maxwell Food Centre: <a href="/redir?url=https%3A%2F%2Fyoutu.be%2FAS-VZa63WLU&amp;s=5a63d2b6d8177aee5b68753dc46a1f5303dc94ec0c685cf7e8246ab2f620e14d" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">youtu.be/AS-VZa63WLU</a><br><br>Context: Came here with my parents, and we had a specific place in mind, I believe called Tien Tien&#39;s Hainan Chicken (A MUST BY THE WAY) <br><br>Environment: It&#39;s like an outdoor (but enclosed roof) night market with stands after stands of delicious food! A foodie&#39;s dream! You can walk around and compare prices, and see what each place has to offer. A lot are quite similar, though, your pick. The seating is also nice as there&#39;s plenty of seating and round tables. It&#39;s busy but not insanely packed when I went<br><br>Food: I went to Tien Tien&#39;s Hainan Chicken, and it&#39;s a must! It&#39;s highly recommended on TripAdvisor. It&#39;s juicy and delicious! We shared among three people. We also bought some Tiger beer and Sprite from another vendor <br><br>Price: Everything here is fairly cheap and well priced! Hooray!<br><br>Overall: Come here for delicious food, you won&#39;t regret it!

text: Uber cheap and a definite budget option offering tasty food.<br><br>Restrictive for gluten free - I went to several vendors with my little dietary card and was told that there was nothing there I could have. *sad face*<br><br>Then I found a thai vendor at the main entrance who made me seafood and vegetable fried rice. Lovely seasoning, huge portion (not much seafood) but very tasty for $5 sing.<br><br>You can take away or sit at little tables provided and other vendors sell drinks, it is very popular with locals and is meant to one of the cheapest &#39;hawker&#39; markets in the main city. <br><br>Non gf peeps will have a ball as there are lots of tasty options available!

text: Now, for beggers and choosers alike, I dare say that this is a hawker centre worth sweating it out and braving the long queues for. There&#39;s endless variety and plenty of clean dining space - if you don&#39;t mind sharing a table with complete strangers.<br><br>I really liked the Pisang Goreng from Lim Kee Banana Fritters and the Hainanese Curry Rice from the stall of the same name. It&#39;s all glory, sauce splatters and comfort food - what is not to love? <br><br>Personally, I find the famous Tian Tian Chicken Rice to be ballpark average - there are certainly better Chicken Rices out there, but if you&#39;ve got a hawker centre craving for our national dish, it will still certainly do the job! <br><br>I find the atmosphere during the lunchtime rush hour infectious - everything is brightly lit and bustling, with so much happening around you! Punters who come by every day may not be a big fan of the crowd, but lining up for your favourite stalls is always worth it in the end!

For all the chatter about this place, let&#39;s get one thing straight - this place is really touristy, no matter how you cut it. Â There&#39;s definitely a higher mix of locals-to-tourists in this particular food/hawker center than say the food center at the nearby/unknown-to-tourists housing complex just a few blocks down. Â And frankly I don&#39;t think the stalls here are that superior than what you find in a local joint. Â (Unless you really think waiting 30min to an hour for a plate of chicken rice that was featured in an American food show really makes it worth your while - personally I didn&#39;t think so)<br><br>I also think my lady got serious food poisoning from eating here ... but I digress.<br><br>This place kind of reminds me of a slightly better version of Lau Pa Sat (which at the time of this writing is closed for renovation). Â I wasn&#39;t particularly impressed or blown away by all the items I got here at various (popular and quiet) stalls. Â Stuff like wan ton mee, laksa, chicken rice (yes even the &#34;popular&#34; one), fishball soup, tofu, etc - they were fine but not mind-blowing. Â One can argue that you can get the same relative items at lesser-known places (even at the Old Airport Road hawker center for God&#39;s sake) for much cheaper, and it would taste better too.<br><br>That said, this isn&#39;t a horrible food court by any means, it&#39;s just not the be-all-end all. Â If you&#39;re a patient or dedicated tourist, do a little more homework on the other good food centers around the island, you&#39;ll be glad you did.
Probably the best of the hawker food centers in Singapore. Perfect balance of cleanliness and authenticity.

Thanks to yelpers, I came here for dinner. <br><br>I am no expert on hawker centers, so I cannot say how it compares to its peers. Had a couple dishes here at two different stalls (chicken rice and a noodle dish). Both were excellent. Big Tiger Beer bottle was $6. Can&#39;t really complain. <br><br>And I am not a fan of A/C, so didn&#39;t mind that Maxwell Food Centre lacks them. About 5 minute walk from Chinatown MRT station if you aren&#39;t familiar with the area. Definitely a better value than the Pagoda St. area restaurants (which have a major tourist trap vibe).

text: My office has been down the street for 6 years. No surprise my weight is up! This remains my favorite hawker centre in Singapore. Excellent range of stalls. Known for Tian Tain chicken rice, which is good, but try others too.

Great hawker center close to Chinatown in singapore. They have some veritable legends of SP hawker cuisine and it gets very crowded during lunch time. But overall a great selection of food, you will definitely not be wanting for options.

Is there anything more Singaporean than a hawker center? At least to me to hawker centers are vital to what Singapore is about - food is an important part of the culture and the hawker center offer a lot of different opportunities to sample a great variety of food at decent prices.<br><br>Maxwell is one of my favorite ones in Singapore. There are several reasons for that. First of all it is in a good location. Easy to reach and often not necessary to make a trip out of visiting. The second is that it offers a fairly clean and comfortable environment (compared to for example the Chinatown complex). Third good thing is that there is a great variety of good quality meals.<br><br>What I am perhaps not as big a fan of is the crowds, come here at weekends or peak lunch hour the lines can be way too long for me. I usually try to visit for an early lunch (or late breakfast) or late lunch. The issue with the late lunch is that several popular places may then run out of food. <br><br>What should you try here then? Well I will not pretend to be that much of an expert but in general the long lines are good bets. I have tried several different ones and the most I have been happy with. Tian Tian is perhaps the most famous one but I was not that impressed but I still think everyone should try it once to form their own opinion.<br><br>I do love coming here for food and the atmosphere and every local as well as tourist should visit now and then.

text: Probably my favorite hawker center in Singapore. I was meeting up with someone here and they were telling me the usual ground rules of &#34;go to the place with the longest lines, cash only, and skip Tian Tian chicken rice.&#34; We ended up eating a feast here with chicken rice, fish soup, nasi lemak, BBQ duck, dumplings, oyster cake, and finished it all off with soyabean curd for dessert. Everything tasted amazing and the fact it was all ~$2-3 each probably made me love it even more. I&#39;m glad I went with the recommendation of skipping Tian Tian as Ah Tai tasted 2x better for me. Sorry Anthony Bourdain and Gordon Ramsay, I&#39;m going to have to go with the locals on this one.

So many reviews from foreigners! I&#39;ll write this one especially for foreign visitors, because I think some of you might not be aware of other options.<br><br>Maxwell is good for offering a lot of foods that are now hard to find at normal food courts. For example, where can you find pisang goreng anywhere near the centre these days? A lot of hawker centres are using the same suppliers and offering the same taste, and a lot of food court chains (e.g. Kopitiam) are doing the same with an extra dollar or two for A/C and (sometimes) more premium ingredients. For preserving a lot of options that don&#39;t exist elsewhere, and for offering some cheap options in an area that somewhat lacks them, I&#39;m giving it 3*. Maybe I should give it 4 as the other big food centres like Lavender are all closing up and being turned into condos...<br><br>It&#39;s, however, very crowded, and quite expensive for what it is. And there ARE cheap, good options nearby. For example, I once walked into a random hawker on Keong Saik Road - Foong Kee Coffee Shop, according to Google Maps - and had well caramelised char siew, which is also hard to find these days amongst the soggy oversalted variety, for only a few percent above normal prices. And there was no queue. And the place was airy and comfortable. And you can also grab a beer for $5 (the same Tiger the hipster cafes and bars nearby sell for $15).<br><br>If you&#39;re hitting up Maxwell (or Lau Pa Sat) just for chicken rice, just look around Yelp or ask locals for recommendations in whichever area you&#39;re in. Every neighbourhood has a hawker who makes decent chicken rice &#34;properly&#34; and it will be more &#34;authentic&#34; as well as tastier and a lot faster than queuing. If you&#39;re looking for specific foods, they&#39;re available elsewhere. If you want the atmosphere, go to level 6 at Plaza Singapura instead, where you&#39;ll find an &#34;authentic&#34; A/C food court filled with actual Singaporeans filling up after their shopping (and yes, the queue at Riverside is totally worth it, and very fast). If you want &#34;loads of choice, cheap, loud and authentic&#34; go to Tekka Market&#39;s hawkers (there&#39;s even an espresso hawker).

text: I&#39;ve seen Maxwell Food Centre on travel channel, food network etc. and I vowed that I would make my way there. I finally made it to Singapore and what a treat! This place is the ultimate food court. It&#39;s very easy to get to, you can take the MRT and get off at Chinatown. It&#39;s about a 7 minute walk or less from the station. It&#39;s divey and has no AC so wear something thin. This food courts consists of rows and rows of vendors, ranging from traditional Singaporean cuisine to fresh fruits and desserts. We tried tian tian chicken, Chinese donuts, beef chow fun and seafood fried rice (from Xiao Chao).<br>All of the food was great but my absolute favorite was the tian tian chicken. I always wondered what all the fuss was about for plain chicken and rice but this dish is something else! The chicken was incredibly tender, almost like butter and it was served warm with cucumbers over white rice. The flavoring was a very mild garlic soy sauce which was lightly drizzled over the chicken and sank into the rice. It was heaven! My dad, who hates chicken, liked it! If you ever go to Maxwell, you must try this dish. The food was also dirt cheap. The tian tian chicken was $3.50 and most food there is $5 or less. The beef chow fun and seafood fried from Xiao Chao were also packed with flavor and unbelievably yummy ($4 to $5 each). I went early in the day so the heat wasn&#39;t an issue but I recommend finding a table near the openings so you can catch the breeze while eating some delicious food.

text: Food lovers - It is guaranteed you will go crazy here! The perfect spot to get local food in Singapore at a very very reasonable price. This food center has 3 or 4 aisles of just little eat out places and juice bars. Every person&#39;s plate looks so appetizing and you&#39;d want to fill your stomach for the next 10 days by eating all the different kinds of foods.<br><br>We had the famous chicken rice from Tian Tian and got a plate of Wonton Wee from a different food stall. Tried a number of drink cold drinks. No matter what your choice of food is, you will not be disappointed.<br><br>They have tables and chairs in the aisle, so you walk by to get your food and get seated anywhere and eat.<br><br>It is a mecca for food lovers. Don&#39;t miss it when you are in Singapore.

tons of local cuisine. Usually a line during peak hours. Hot and humid since this place doesn&#39;t have airconditioning. Toilet has a fee to use.<br>A must try if you are a first time visitor like me

text: The Maxwell Food Centre is conveniently located near Chinatown. If you&#39;re a tourist in Singapore, you must visit a food court and taste the local food. Singapore is a melting pot of different cultures and cuisines and a Singapore food court is a very good representation of the variety in cultures there. <br><br>For the ones who are not familiar with food courts, a food court is a place where you have multiple food stalls. You can buy your food from any of the food stalls, take your food from the food stall and have a seat at any of the tables and seats in the food court. After you&#39;ve done eating, the staff will clean up after you. <br><br>If it&#39;s your first time visiting a Singapore food court, make sure that you bring a lot of tissues or napkins and wet wipes. You might want to wipe off the table or your hands or your mouth. And napkins are not provided in the food court. <br><br>It can get very busy in this food court, so if you&#39;re going to eat there, it&#39;s better to bring a companion so that he or she can occupy a table or seats while you&#39;re getting food. Otherwise, if you&#39;re by yourself, it&#39;s also okay to sit at a free seat at a table with other people and ask them to occupy a seat for you while you&#39;re getting your food. <br><br>My recommendations to try are the Haianese chicken with rice and a lemon kumquat fruit tea with a salted plum. If you&#39;re a true daredevil, try to eat the salted plum after you&#39;ve finished the lemon kumquat fruit tea.

text: So being the good foodie tourist that I am, I had plans to have myself some chicken rice from Tian Tian, and then write a review of how right Bourdain was, how it&#39;s the best I&#39;ve tasted etc etc<br>Well instead I rocked up at opening time (8am), and Tian Tian wasn&#39;t opening till 10 (quite a few places weren&#39;t open yet which was a little disappointing). <br><br>Cue the backup plan - dumplings! (Now I could&#39;ve lined up for porridge, but as much as I like a weird array of foods I didn&#39;t grow up eating - this is not one of them. Â I don&#39;t like grits either but that&#39;s for another time)<br><br>I went to a stand a few doors up (see photo) &amp; grabbed some Har Gow &amp; a steamed BBQ pork bun. The Har Gow was average at best, but the pork bun was delicious.<br><br>Next stop - a freshly squeezed (or should I say juiced?) pear juice from across the way. Delightingly refreshing! <br><br>After a bit more people watching and a wander I came across Pan Cake &amp; a red bean paste dumpling. And oh how divine it was! <br><br>All up I spent maybe $7? And I&#39;m happy Tian Tian wasn&#39;t open yet, as I ended up trying a few different places instead. <br><br>For cheap, decent food that&#39;s quick &amp; easy, you can&#39;t go wrong. Well except the prawn dumplings I had, maybe steer clear of those!

text: We decided after a few different try-outs that this was our favorite food court.<br>Yes, it does get steamy and sweaty on warm lunch times but hey this is Singapore and I hate A/C with a passion anyway.<br>Yes, it does get very busy at times, with 15mn queues and sending a friend to save seats (or putting Â a pack of Kleenex down apparently!)<br>But the food is good and we&#39;ve tried quite a few stalls. The Tian tian chicken rice is amazing, the dumplings and the gyoza are great, the curries are fabulous and the fresh juices just the freshness you need on a hot day (I would kill for a lime juice now!)<br>You can easily eat and drink for around 5-6$ so really, what are you waiting for!

text: Clean, cheap and cheerful - just follow the queues of people and I don&#39;t think you can ever go wrong. My parents were impressed at the quality of the food, the selection and the overall cleanliness of the centre. We didn&#39;t get a chance to visit the Tiong Baru one but compared to Hong Lim and Lau Pa Sat - this is the one we will happily return for some local fare. Just follow the queues of people and order whatever they do - you won&#39;t be disappointed

text: This Hawker center was very close to our hotel.. and we discovered it on the last day.. good thing as we would have not gone anywhere else to eat had we have found it on our first day.. it&#39;s always busy, we had the chicken and rice from tian tian, it was incredibly cheap and ridiculously good.. the curry puffs were amazing the lychee drink however tasted very watered down.. I would suggest a different store

It&#39;s hard for me to find a food court in Singapore that I don&#39;t like. There are so many amazing food stalls at this place. Even when it&#39;s really busy you can still find a place to sit. Don&#39;t go if you are very hungry or you will be overwhelmed by the choices. Aren&#39;t sure what to try? Go to the stalls with the longest lines. You can&#39;t lose!

text: This Hawker center is where my first meal in Singapore happened. Hainanese chicken, milo dinosaur, and some rollies. The locals were so friendly, the food was cheap, they managed the cleanliness very well, wide variety, and short queues. I&#39;ve tried their bbq, fruit smoothies, fried bananas, noodles, satay, and so much more. If you&#39;re nearby, I highly recommend stopping briefly for at least a snack. It&#39;s a must stop for every Singapore trip in the future. <br>Oh, and the only conclusion that I have to make is that i&#39;d like to believe that some of the older men were staring at my food, and not me ;)

text: Holy Hawker Center! I was in love from the moment I stepped in. Now, don&#39;t come here thinking you&#39;re getting the luxury life. You must visit here with an open mind and heart.<br><br>This is a food stall haven and I&#39;m so happy to have been able to visit Maxwell Centre since viewing it Anthony Bourdain&#39;s travel to Singapore. <br><br>Foods stall after food stall, we decided on some prawn dumplings, chicken and scallion dumplings, fresh papaya fruit smoothie/juice and our dabble at the famous chicken and rice dish that is a must have specialty when visiting Singapore. <br><br>This is definitely a great Hawker Centre, unfortunately, we weren&#39;t able to visit any others. Therefore, I have nothing to compare it to. We were staying at Marina Bay Sands, so it was very close, and China town was basically across the street so we killed two birds with one stone. <br><br>Thumbs up!

text: I think I have been told by local friends that I have officially become a Singaporean after choosing to stand in line for a good one hour at Zhen Zhen Porridge (Singaporeans will stand in line for any food they crave!). There is a big metal cauldron with an automatic stirrer that goes on and on so that the porridge is constantly kept in a well blended and smooth texture. Porridge options include sliced fish, fish belly, chicken, century egg. The porridge is the smoothest and creamiest I&#39;ve had with hardly a trace of individual rice grains. The other star item is yusheng (raw fish salad), dressed with shaved lettuce, cilantro, ginger, sesame seed, sesame oil dressing, sliced fresh red chillies, and lime.<br><br>We return to Maxwell on another day at 2pm for hainanese chicken rice and there is a line of customers at Tian Tian despite the off peak hour. We decide to do a little &#34;chicken rice showdown&#34; among ourselves between Tian Tian and Ah Tai. Just before this, we hear that Ah Tai, another chicken rice stall that is located next to Tian Tian, is operated by a previous chef of Tian Tian. There was a fallout which led him to open the stall next door, and even going so far as to having a signboard with the same blue color theme. We order half a chicken from each Tian Tian and Ah Tai. Tian Tian&#39;s chicken is smooth and the skin retains the gelatinous layer which is very tempting to eat (admittedly, I decide to give in and sneak some chicken skin onto my spoon). It is what dreams are made of. The rice is fragrant and the glaze over the chicken has a good consistency. Ah Tai&#39;s chicken pieces look more pressed and flattened. The texture is not the smooth as the chicken from Tian Tian. The glaze and rice from Ah Tai also fall short.<br><br>The silky and milky broth at Jin Hua Sliced Fish Bee Hoon is what drives the line of people at this stall. The fish slices here are large with a solid texture. I do find it is misleading that despite the name of the stall having the word bee hoon in it, the noodles used look more like lai noodles (round, thick, and slippery noodles) rather than what I&#39;ve come to know as bee hoon (thin rice noodles). The broth is silky and the added evaporated milk into the broth adds to the consistency. The flavor is evident but overall lacks an oomph factor.
Tons of choices, cheap. This is my goto place when I visit Singapore.

text: We woke up from an overnight stay at &#39;The Club&#39; hotel and popped over to the very nearby Maxwell hawker for breakfast. It was lovely to be at Maxwell as an early bird - it was quiet except for a few elderly couples and a sprinkling of tourists, and hardworking breakfast stall-owners already done with set-up. <br><br>Some friends ordered fish porridge, some ordered carrot cake while I had my YOU TIAO and TAU HWAY. This means fried dough fritters and soya beancurd. It was excellent. The soya beancurd was warm and smooth, complimented by the crispy dough fritters.<br><br>This place is one of the most famous hawker centres in Singapore, having satisfied many office workers during lunch and families and friends during dinner. Turns out it&#39;s also great for traditional breakfasts. If you&#39;re someone who is seeking local delights with authentic yet simple flavours for breakfast, this is the place to be at.<br><br>Check out <a href="/redir?url=http%3A%2F%2Featlikeawhale.blogspot.sg&amp;s=073078668bba0d0a43c2d19980dbd9384767b13a2e1457c8da39273937aa332c" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">eatlikeawhale.blogspot.sg</a> for more pictures and reviews.

text: One of my favourite hawker haunts in the city, Maxwell Market never fails to disappoint in terms of quality and variety. Try the Ngoh Hiang from one of the stalls in the 2nd row from the main road! It is one of my favourite ngoh hiang and fried beehoon stall in Singapore although it is a tad bit pricey.<br><br>Maxwell Market is also home to a couple of famous chicken rice stalls that are well-known for good reason. It is a good place to take friends from overseas for a meal, especially after a visit to chinatown, for a taste of the local flavours. Tian Tian Chicken Rice can be found here spaninng 2 shop spaces, and has been voted to be the best chicken rice in Singapore. They are very popular so be prepared to wait in line for quite a bit.

text: Maxwell Hawker Center is a great hawker centre. They have many options to chose from and one of my favorite hawker center in Singapore for sure. It&#39;s a pretty clean hawker center and not that crowded. They serve many different cuisines here and you can eat anything. I would highly recommend Maxwell hawker centre to anyone in Singapore.

Maxwell Centre occupies almost a mythic place in Singapore&#39;s food world. Unfortunately by the time I got to the front of the line for the chicken it was all gone. I&#39;ve heard great things about it so I&#39;ll have to return.<br><br>My friend and I ended up getting some chicken curry followed by some fried rice. Both were passable, with the chicken having some interesting flavour, but nothing to rave about. Lime juice is a must, so bring lots of small change.

I was really surprised by this outdoor hawker section.<br>Many selections to choose from and reasonable prices (everything under 6). Â The portions are smaller than that of what you get in the US, but it&#39;s just my size! Â For the guys, I recommend getting at least 2 orders, or maybe an upgraded size of extra meat?<br><br>We ate at Tian Tian for the chicken rice combo. Â Got some curry roti from the Indian place, some fried dumplings from another stall and shared it family style. Â Finding a table at prime dinner time was a bit tough, you have to be like a shark in wading water and pounce as soon as you see someone finishing. Â There are fans above to keep you from sweating and a clean bathroom (was really surprised by how clean a public bathroom at an outdoor restaurant area).<br><br>You can either clean up after yourself and put your tray away at the designated areas, or they have staff walking around. Â There is a separate area for placing halal plates/dishes.<br><br>Very convenient as it&#39;s near Chinatown! Â If you don&#39;t know what to eat, sit down and share a table with the locals, they&#39;ll tell you what&#39;s good!
This place is huge, busy, and crowded! I&#39;m not sure if the traditional advice of finding the longest line applies here, but use your best judgment!!

text: The only bad thing to say about this place is that many of the stalls close too early and bring your own napkins! Â But other than those two short falls, this place is great! Â Great variety of local street food. Â Best to come with a group so you can sample all the different dishes. Â Come here for early dinner then go to Lo Pat Sat for later skewers.

This is definitely one of the best hawker centers in Singapore. Favourites include Tian Tian Chicken Rice (though in my opinion, the two other chicken rice stalls in its vicinity provide an excellent alternative if Tian Tian is closed or the queue is too long) and China Street Fritters for the Ngor Hiang.<br><br>I think it&#39;s important to judge a hawker center not only by the handful of superstar stalls but also by the quality of the stalls less patronised. I personally have never had a bad meal at Maxwell and that says something. I also find the place a lot roomier and more comfortable than Chomp Chomp &amp; cleaner than Old Airport Road. Plus its proximity to the CBD and the excellent post-feed drinking options in Chinatown/Tanjong Pagar give it extra points also.

text: Maxwell Food Centre falls victim to the whole &#34;it&#39;s so close, I can go anytime&#34; syndrome. Well, this is my first time back at Maxwell since moving a 5-min walk away from this marvelous food centre.<br><br>We gave it another shot today and I&#39;m pleased to say that Tian Tian has won my heart back for chicken rice. I have a love/hate relationship w/ this dish as sometimes it&#39;s hard to fathom why it&#39;s such a popular eat but the 30 min queue was worth the wait to share a large plate of chicken rice w/ my wife. We both ate it down QUICK.<br><br>The rice is so garlicky but delicious. The chicken is boneless and almost skinless (I think we got lucky b/c we hate skin) but damn it was delicious with their chili sauce and soya sauce. Mmmmm.<br><br>We&#39;ve got to make it more of a habit to eat here and check out some of the other great stalls.

text: Love, love, love this place!<br><br>Whether it&#39;s the affable Vegetarian Bee Hoon vendor auntie I go to in the morning to get my lunch ($3 for a very, very sizable serving!), or the auntie-uncle duo that stays open till 10.30 pm dishing out styrofoam plate after plate of ultra-delicious Rojak and Popiah (still $1 a pop!), or the ever-young gyoza &#39;ah jie&#39; that flashes her timelessly gorgeous smile as you go up to her at 3 am after a night out painting the town red, nurturing your stomach with freshly steamed/fried dumplings (done on the spot!)...<br><br>Maxwell Road Hawker Centre has been around for decades, and Singaporeans of all generations have fond memories of it... a small grouse is the disappearance of the good ol&#39; fashioned tau huey auntie and her stall (she has since been spotted selling dim sum/congee, not her fault as she&#39;s not the one running it), and the stalls that sell $2 &#39;tau huey&#39; (that&#39;s the overly sweet pudding stuff that has horrible flavours). Over-priced, and not something I agree with, really.

Maxwell is definitely a part of my Singapore visit ritual. Â I love the lamb rice from the Muslim kitchen at the back right corner, Â the fresh fruit from the centre Isle, Â and the coffee man is fabulous! Â <br>Great food. Â Great local culture. Â <br>Amazing meals for under $5... where else but there will you find that in Singapore?

text: Holy Hawker Center! I was in love from the moment I stepped in. Now, don&#39;t come here thinking you&#39;re getting the luxury life. You must visit here with an open mind and heart.<br><br>This is a food stall haven and I&#39;m so happy to have been able to visit Maxwell Centre since viewing it Anthony Bourdain&#39;s travel to Singapore. <br><br>Foods stall after food stall, we decided on some prawn dumplings, chicken and scallion dumplings, fresh papaya fruit smoothie/juice and our dabble at the famous chicken and rice dish that is a must have specialty when visiting Singapore. <br><br>This is definitely a great Hawker Centre, unfortunately, we weren&#39;t able to visit any others. Therefore, I have nothing to compare it to. We were staying at Marina Bay Sands, so it was very close, and China town was basically across the street so we killed two birds with one stone. <br><br>Thumbs up!

text: I&#39;m still not used to this ridiculously humid/tropical climate, so I was a bit uncomfortable and hot here and couldn&#39;t try all the foods I wanted since I didn&#39;t want to shower at Maxwell... but this is a foodie&#39;s paradise! Â The prior night, I went to the Old Airport Road FC with colleagues and didn&#39;t find this one to be much different, but there are indeed a good number of foreigners and tourists here. Â Still, the food stalls are heaven for someone who loves food.<br><br>Lao Ban dou hua - 2nd night in a row. Â Such a good cooling dessert.<br><br>Buns - I don&#39;t remember where the buns came from, but the stall basically only sold buns and I had pretty much one of each. Â I didn&#39;t like that the char siu bun had cooked cilantro in it (I love cilantro, but hate it when its been cooked), but it was still yummy as well as the pork-filled bun. Â Shumai was okay... not a big fan of shumai anyways.<br><br>We had some Malay food, which looked like stirfried instant maggi noodles with super extra spicy sauce, lots of green chilies, and anchovies. Â I couldn&#39;t eat much of this as it started to make me really hot.<br><br>To finish off, I had cheng teng at a dessert stall. Â I freaking love this stuff, so perhaps I&#39;m a bit biased. Â It may be weird for people who aren&#39;t familiar with it, but its basically a &#34;health&#34; drink. Â YUM.<br><br>I&#39;d suggest going with a local and trying a bit of everything here - can&#39;t really go wrong. Â Bring your own napkins and/or wet wipes though... seems like Singapore isn&#39;t about wiping your face and your hands unless you pay for it :P

text: I have found food stall heaven. Â It&#39;s Maxwell and I wish I lived closer to Singapore for this place alone. Â I tried everything I wanted because everything is ultra inexpensive. Â Like $3 noodles, $3 soup, $3 stir-fry. You get the idea. <br><br>I have to give a special shout out to this bun place called Creative Designs. It is a strange name but their baked goods are ultra-delish. Â I had a banana nutella filled bun and my husband has a pizza bun. I give a more favorable recommendation to the sweet over the savory, but I wish I could eat one every day.

An affordable hawker center in the expensive Chinatown area. Because of the area, the stalls are primarily Chinese and there aren&#39;t many choices for Indian or Halal. Beer is also incredibly expensive and only at a few stands. Some of the stalls are also open very late. Try the famous chicken rice and the fried potato balls.

text: Uber cheap and a definite budget option offering tasty food.<br><br>Restrictive for gluten free - I went to several vendors with my little dietary card and was told that there was nothing there I could have. *sad face*<br><br>Then I found a thai vendor at the main entrance who made me seafood and vegetable fried rice. Lovely seasoning, huge portion (not much seafood) but very tasty for $5 sing.<br><br>You can take away or sit at little tables provided and other vendors sell drinks, it is very popular with locals and is meant to one of the cheapest &#39;hawker&#39; markets in the main city. <br><br>Non gf peeps will have a ball as there are lots of tasty options available!

Maxwell Centre occupies almost a mythic place in Singapore&#39;s food world. Unfortunately by the time I got to the front of the line for the chicken it was all gone. I&#39;ve heard great things about it so I&#39;ll have to return.<br><br>My friend and I ended up getting some chicken curry followed by some fried rice. Both were passable, with the chicken having some interesting flavour, but nothing to rave about. Lime juice is a must, so bring lots of small change.

text: Boy was this place awesome, I went back a 2nd time and added more photos.<br><br>Place is fantastic in every way, shape, and form. I followed the long lines this time and went for the porridge with chicken and century old egg from Zhen Zhen. Best porridge I have ever had in my entire life. Having tried some top places in Hong Kong and Cambodia, this place was hands down better than all. Waited in line about 50 minutes to order my food.<br><br>Glad we had some regulars eat with us that lived in Singapore. Â We all loved the Hainanese chicken rice. Tian Tian is incredible, you can even see Anthony Bourdain&#39;s picture in the front of the place. :-)<br><br>The only thing I didn&#39;t like about this place was the heat! If it were enclosed they could put in some A/C but it is open on all sides and made it a bit uncomfortable.<br><br>Glad to have found this place on Yelp, would have gone back Kovan Hougang Food Centre which I have frequented many times on my travels to Asia. Kovan isn&#39;t bad, will probably never be as good as Maxwell Food Centre.
clubbers hangout after a rough night. The porridge is thick and flavorful and is a great way to hydrate.
Excellent hawker center. Tian Tian hainan chicken is worth the short wait. <br><br>great air circulation versus the other hawker centers.

Great food options for cheap prices. Â Gets crazy busy at certain times. Â <br><br>Lots of locals and tourists. Â Pretty easy to figure out places that are must try by looking at lines. Â No AC though so might get warm and crowded here.
Very close to where I stay where when in Singapore. This kind of food centres should remain as part of Singapore&#39;s eating heaven. Lots of choices to choose from

text: Jin Huat Fish Head Bee Hoon is worth my 15mins of wait. Creamy white fish broth with fresh fish slices (no fishy nonsense). Mmmmm.... I can personally whack 2 servings but others will judge.... :P

We stopped by Maxwell after going through Chinatown (about a five minute walk away). We got there right before 12 PM, and the place was starting to fill up. As with anywhere in Singapore, if you are unsure of where to eat, just jump in a line and you&#39;ll probably be assured of a good meal. Don&#39;t be shy to sit down at a table that is already occupied by others. There are also a fewer tables on the outside of the food center that weren&#39;t too busy (you&#39;ll see these tables while waiting in the Tian Tian chicken line).

text: I am sure some of you have your favourite stalls there: Tian Tian Chicken Rice, Zhen Zhen Porridge , Lao Ban Beancurd , Hoe Kee Porridge and Dim Sum, Jin Hua Fish Head Bee Hoon, Hum Jin Pang, and the newly opened Rolina Curry Puffs and Special Shanghai Tim-Sum .<br><br>Tian Tian Chicken Rice<br>Probably one of Singapore&#39;s most famous chicken rice stall, Tian Tian&#39;s winning formula to me has to be its rice. Even Anthony Bourdain said that the chicken rice is so fragrant and delicious that it can be eaten on its own. Probably one of the best chicken rice in Singapore, it&#39;s warm, fluffy, fragrant and tasty. So good I can just eat it with the chilli sauce. And you can always hop to Ah Tai Chicken Rice (their ex-Master chef) 2 stalls away for a comparison. <br><br>Zhen Zhen Porridge<br>If you liked your porridge thick and dense, cooked with broken grains instead of whole rice, you would find Zhen Zhen&#39;s porridge pleasurable. Every spoonful of porridge I eaten was full of ingredients, such as chicken meat (or fish slices) and century egg, and other peripherals of spring onion, shallots and chopped preserved vegetables. That made the porridge un-plain and exciting to eat. BUT, be prepared to wait for a very, very, very long time. And they close really early.

text: This place is great. If you want an excellent selection of food to choose from and can handle heat and humidity (that&#39;s just how Singapore is), then I highly recommend the Maxwell Food Center. It was a highlight of our trip to Singapore. It&#39;s like going to the fair- there are rows and rows of places serving all types of food- Chinese, Vietnamese, Korean, Thai, Japanese, etc. And the drinks!!!! That was seriously a highlight- having FRESH soursop and sugarcane juices, and it was so cheap! I think it costs only about $1.25 or so each for fresh juice!!! Another favorite was the cockles my sister ordered. They were so sweet and tasty- oh so delicious! My brother who normally doesn&#39;t care for them ate away with the rest of us. Just writing about Maxwell food court makes my mouth water...<br><br>Oh, I need to mention one downside. First time we went was late lunch time so we had no issues. But the second time we went was right during dinner time. The problem was finding seating. This is like fast food. You order and are on your own to find seats. And this can be (and was) extremely challenging during peak meal times.<br><br>But I would still definitely go back and brave the seating situation.

text: This place is absolutely awesome! Â While sightseeing in Chinatown, my family and I stumbled upon this place and so decided to eat here for lunch. At the time that we were there, it wasn&#39;t crowded, so we got our food pretty quickly. Â The food court consists of a bunch of booths in several aisles. Â Quite a few vendors were selling the food. We basically ordered from the pictures and they cook it for us right there. Â Then we bring it back to our table and dig in! Â First time I ate there, I had tom yum soup and shared a mango salad. The tom yum hit the spot and the mango salad was delicious! Â The mango was raw enough that it wasn&#39;t soggy and it was well seasoned with chili to add a spicy kick. Â <br><br>Since our meal was good AND cheap, we decided to come back for Â dinner. This time, more stalls were opened, so we had more options. Â We ordered ourselves some fruit drinks as well. We had sugar cane and soursop drinks. Â They were so good! Â The sugarcane drink was freshly squeezed. They squeeze the cane right in front of us. The soursop drink was something that we haven&#39;t had before. Â To our delight, it was extremely refreshing in the humid weather. Â It was a little sour and sweet, with some meat in it. Â We liked it so much that we ordered another 2. Â <br><br>I decided to walk around some more to check out the other stalls, and stopped at one that sells cockles. Â That took me back to my trip to Thailand. Â I ordered a large order and the guy cooked it right there for us. Â I will have to say that was, by far, the best cockle I&#39;ve ever had. They were so fresh, juicy, and sweet. Â We didn&#39;t have to season it with anything. The large order was devoured in no time by the four of us. Â Needless to say, we came back here again.<br><br>All in all, I really enjoyed eating here. This was one of the highlights of our short visit to Singapore. I highly recommend that you eat here. Â Just be sure to come at their off hours because it gets VERY crowded that it&#39;s hard to find seats during their rush hours. Â Enjoy!

text: Wow!!! 3 rows of hawkers food in this little strip. So many choices to choose from. The best place to get hainanese chicken is at the stall called tian tian #10! Don&#39;t get confused with the other stalls with the same blue signage. There is always a line, but worth the wait! I also tried the fried sweet potato stall, relish and cheap. There are many juice bars and they are all very inexpensive and delicious. There is so much good food and super cheap. You won&#39;t be disappointed.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/2-Sk4dcfssu5rKr7nXQoEg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/maxwell-food-centre-singapore-3?reviewid=AJojDkP5fy5_fWfpEhAviA&select=2-Sk4dcfssu5rKr7nXQoEg', 'altText': 'Photo of Maxwell Food Centre - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/4eC31YAXK4DqRRpPxEckaA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/maxwell-food-centre-singapore-3?reviewid=AJojDkP5fy5_fWfpEhAviA&select=4eC31YAXK4DqRRpPxEckaA', 'altText': 'Photo of Maxwell Food Centre - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: A great hawker with many local delights. The three longest queues I&#39;ve seen are for Zhen Zhen Porridge, this fried fish noodle soup just opposite Zhen Zhen and Tian Tian Chicken rice. Most of the traffic in the earlier parts of the day comprise of tourist and I notice the chicken rice is a real winner with Japanese tourists. Come lunch time, 12 -2pm, Maxwell can get pretty crowded and you will see the occasional tissue paper reservation all around tables. Visit after 2pm if you want to order your food and find a seat conveniently! And for breakfast, the Rickshaw Noodles Store is a must try!

There are several different Hawker Food Centres in Singapore, some seem more local based, while other seem more tourist based, and they change over time. This one is still a local one, the food is great at all the different stalls I went to, and I was not &#34;hawked&#34; by any of the vendors, they let me go where I chose. Just remember this place is outside and hot as blazes, but hey, that&#39;s what the cold Tiger beer is for! And cheap? A full set of Chicken Rice and a giant Tiger beer was only S$10.00. Now THAT&#39;S a great deal!

This place is one of the food havens of Singapore where you can find one of the best foods in almost every local Singapore flavours category. Just in case you are coming here for Tian Tian Chicken rice because of Anthony Bourdain, there&#39;s been some changes. The chicken that taste so good was and is cooked by a person called Ah Tai who opened a stall 2 stalls down now. Tian Tian&#39;s rice is still great but its chicken has dropped standards because of the departure of Ah Tai. Do give it a shot on both stalls!

An affordable hawker center in the expensive Chinatown area. Because of the area, the stalls are primarily Chinese and there aren&#39;t many choices for Indian or Halal. Beer is also incredibly expensive and only at a few stands. Some of the stalls are also open very late. Try the famous chicken rice and the fried potato balls.

text: The Maxwell Food Center is an institution in hawker center history. Some of the best food in here is the Hainanese chicken rice, which frequently sells out early, so go for lunch if you are in the area. Beer is cheap, the service is fast and curt, so be ready with your order when you get to the front of the queue. Great starting point for a night on Club Street which is right up the hill.

text: No offence, Singaporeans, buuuuut... is Tian Tian really the &#34;best chicken rice&#34; you guys can come up with? The compliments I hear for this stall range from &#34;best in Singapore&#34; to &#34;best in the world&#34;. It was an inexpensive meal (even with a half-chicken) but one that also definitely elicited a whole-hearted &#34;meh&#34; from me.

text: One of my favorite hawker centre in Singapore. I usually go here for Tian Tian chicken rice, the fish bee hoon and peanut soup (closes around 1pm so don&#39;t be late). Try to avoid rush hour, queues will be long and it&#39;ll be hard to find a table.

One of Hawker centers that has the most stalls available so there&#39;s lots of options for everyone. Only came here for the Tian Tian Hainanese Chicken as per the recommendations. Anthony Bourdain was came by this Hawker center which was pretty neat to know. I found it absolutely hilarious to see so many knockoffs trying to either fool visitors or pretend to be as good as Tian Tian Chickens. Â They were trying so hard that they all used the same blue background white characters and basically the only thing different was the name (rest were all the same) Hainanese Chicken. Don&#39;t be fooled! There&#39;s only one good one and it&#39;s called Tian Tian Hainanese Chicken. This other place called &#34;Ah Tai&#34; was embarrassing, all the utensils/bowls are communal and janitors usually return everything back to the respective stalls but this one employee that day was so stingy that one of our folks took their spoons to eat and he literally chased him down and took it back...Pretty embarrassing considering he already started consuming with the spoon. Just let the man use it and the janitors will take it and return it back to you. Not like they had any business that they would run out of spoons anytime soon.

text: Great place with all the different food stalls. Â Hard to decide what to eat if you aren&#39;t there for the chicken rice and if you are you&#39;ll probably hit a few of the other stalls. Â Got great dried fruits and some weird but tasty desrts

One of the best in town. Great chicken rice stall a little down the row from the one with the huge queue that Bourdain and Ramsey have frequented. Super salad stall. Also try porridge, duck rice, fried dough and banana fritter stalls.

text: Fantastic place to have lunch as there are so many varieties and cuisines to choose from. It&#39;s also a good place to have one&#39;s breakfast but remember, most of the stalls close mid-afternoon.

My favorite popiah stall is in this center. The fresh rolls are not soggy like other places and the filling isn&#39;t heavily sweetened. Order it with some spicy sauce. I like to wash the popiah down with some fresh juice (either watermelon or pineapple juice). Cheap, good, relatively clean, and fast local food.

We only visited one hawker center in Singapore and happened to choose this one. Not a bad choice as there are plenty of food options - a bit repetitive but the most popular one is Tian Tian and the Porridge station (forgot the name). We managed to try a few things here - fresh sugar cane juice, tian tian chicken, and a country style duck station. Theres seating all over although its super packed as you can imagine during lunch and may have to share tables. Not a bad choice if you only have time to visit one hawker center.

If Old Airport Road food centre is my favourite hawker centre, Maxwell comes a very close second. I like many things here. Too many to name.<br><br>The porridge, chicken rice, Thai food especially, even the Indian Muslim food in the corner and teh tarik. It&#39;s always fun to bring tourists here to try the chicken rice (say what you will about Tian Tian, it&#39;s a good introduction I think), and to try their hand at frying fritters at the China Street Fritters stall.<br><br>Sugarcane juice with lemon, some herbal soup... the location is also the best in the area: Hong Lim is a little too far for me and Amoy a bit too tucked away in the CBD, so I do come here very often although the other two above could probably give it a run for its money.

text: Maxwell food centre is a hawker centre located opposite Chinatown. It has a dizzying array of food stalls, many of which are renown all across Singapore for being one of the best in their area. Famous stalls include Zhen Zhen porridge stall, and the nondescript Hainanese curry rice stall, located in the middle of the hawker centre. Maxwell has stalls which open all hours of the day - making it a convenient place for food, at any time - be it after a night out or for a quick snack before heading to the office. It&#39;s also the home of the famous Lao Ban beancurd, the stall which single-handedly kick started the current bean curd craze taking Singapore by storm. All in, Maxwell food centre is an excellent place for a cheap meal, and you&#39;ll never leave the place feeling disappointed.

Really a great hawker center. It&#39;s all about Tian Tian chicken and rice here though. Everything else is pretty good, but Tian Tian is next level my dudes. On the real, it&#39;s pretty much as next level as you can get when you&#39;re talking about poached chicken and white rice. Everything is delish, eat it all. Now.

text: This is one of the first hawker centers I choose to take overseas guests when they visit Singapore, particularly during mornings or lunch times. Chicken rice from Tian Tian was the first time I had lined up for food in my life, after 30 minutes of my expectations building it was worth every minute. The chicken rice from Tian Tian isn&#39;t the only gem in this hawker center. Curry rice, teow chew porridge to name a couple are always must visit stalls here<br>. <br>My friends and visiting colleagues have had many a great experience here, ordering 5 or 6 different dishes and working through each of them. On the fringe of Chinatown, it gives you that real Singaporean experience.<br>This hawker center can be difficult to find a seat at certain times of the day. It is one of the dirtier hawker centers around as far as general table cleanliness goes, but hey that only adds to the experience.

text: In terms of food, this is probably the best hawker center in Singapore. Chose from an immense array of different cuisines. From Chinese to Malay to Indian to Thai to Western. And it seems like almost every stall here is very good. <br><br>Try the popiah which is in the center aisle of the food center. Very generous and tasty. Also the fish porridge, also in the center aisle is always very popular. They also have a special tofu there which is really good. <br><br>My main gripe about this place is the cleanliness. Its really not the cleanest hawker center in Singapore and if you leave your plates alone for more than a few minutes, baby cockroaches start to come to your table. Yes cockroaches. In Singapore. Its pretty disgusting. They need to do something about this asap.

Definitely one of the best hawker centres in SIngapore! Maxwell is lined up with row after row of local delicacies, and they&#39;re some of the most tasty food in Singapore.<br><br>If you only have room or time for one thing, make it the Thai food stall, which makes one of my favourite phad thai on the island. The chicken rice is also great, although somehow people have a love/hate relationship with it.<br><br>Some of the stalls open late, so if you&#39;re hitting the night spots in the area you can always drop by for some chow.

text: One of the best Food Centers in Singapore, every stall i hit was better than the next. Just good ole mom n&#39; pop Asian cooking, the Tian Tian chicken made to perfection every time I eat here. Porridge and Hong Kong noodles are a must try, along with the oyster cakes.The prices are unbeatable, so you know i can put down about 3-4 dishes. Just a awesome foodie experience, give it a try!

text: Maxwell Road Hawker Centre is clean and cheap, with interesting, delicious food. Â Love the Tian Tian chicken rice and Zhen Zhen porridge (congee) Â . Don&#39;t forget a nice cold Tiger Beer with your meal.

I have traveled a lot and NEVER seen this many places to eat in one condensed area. Â It seemed like there were at least 200 10&#39; by 10&#39; small outlets and many had great displays. Â It is very much a place for locals as it is across from a Chinese temple that is packed all the time. Â My favourite here are the fruit stands that sell smoothies. Â I also bought a few stuffed pastry Â nibblets from different places. Â I would buy small things from many places to try as many as I could. Â There was also a really good espresso place near the entrance across from the temple that I would recommend highly. Â You will love this place if you love adventure...

text: Our hotel is nearby and within walking distance to two of the biggest food courts that I have ever seen. Â Back at home where we live, no food court that is organize like these food courts. Â One is Chinatown Complex and the other is Maxwell Centre. Â My opinion is depending on the type of food you like or your favorite, they are all good. Â You could have a three course dinner at any of the food courts as mentioned above. Â We were there in October, 2015 to early November, 2015. Â It&#39;s a good thing there&#39;s air conditioning because the weather is humid and warm. Â <br>On our last night, we had steamed fish head at the Chinatown Complex. Â At Maxwell, we had steamed white chicken and rice. Â We heard they are both famous in Singapore. Â <br>We were not disappointed. Â We also have breakfast at Maxwell with coffee, toasts, and porridges. Â <br>Give yourself some time because either one of these food courts is make you spend some time walking around and just looking for what they have.

text: If you are a tourist in the country, you have to come here to get a taste of the local food and everyday life of a Singaporean. <br><br>Like our fellow member Handoyo S &amp; Joanne G said, Tian Tian Chicken Rice is the highlight in this wet hawker food centre. One of the best chicken rice in Singapore. <br><br>One thing to take note:<br>When ordering the chicken, try to ask for drumstick, or the back part of the chicken. Some people do not say anything when ordering, and sometimes the stall cook will just give you the toughest part of the chicken: breast. To some unknowing first timers, they may get disappointed because of this.<br><br>Sweet potato fritters are also nice. Can&#39;t remember the exact stall unit number. But it&#39;s along the middle lane (there are 3 lanes of rows of stalls).
I recommend this place for group of 4. That&#39;s awesome experience!

text: Was checking what was recommended around Redhill / Alexandra Â when I can across this place on hungry go where. <br>Seeing how they had rather high ratings, I decided to give it a try. <br><br>Hidden in an old coffee shop along Lengkok Bahru, I have to admit that, first impression, I was in for a night of disappointment... And I was right. <br><br>We decided to go for their special, Chicken Chop with Cheese Sauce and a basic for all Western establishments, a steak. <br><br>If I could describe the food? It tasted like some kid had the idea of opening a western food joint with food that his family praised him for at home. <br><br>The chicken chops signature cheese sauce (I know.. What was I thinking) was decent enough and the steak was well.... I&#39;ve had better. <br><br>Seeing how they&#39;re located at this old coffee shop, you&#39;d think that the price would be lower as the westerns in say.. Clementi or Holland V, but they&#39;re not. <br>You&#39;re better off taking that money to an Astons, who would serve you a better steak any day. <br><br>Lesson learnt from this experience? Don&#39;t trust everything you read online. Sure I know it couldn&#39;t have been perfect but I didn&#39;t quite expect it to be so far off the mark.

text: The simple things are often the best things, and the best things become part of special moments when you happen upon simple things unexpectedly. Â This is how the very best and fondly-remembered food epiphanies unfold. Â <br><br>Consider the humble samosa, de rigeur at tea times and coffee breaks; I know I&#39;ve carelessly stuffed more than a few of these into my indifferent maw at more courses, workshops or seminars than I care to remember. Â Then consider Balmoral Bakery&#39;s version of this quotidian pastry, this workhorse of a tea time treat. Â Also wrapped in a paper thin popiah skin and deep-fried, the wonder begins when that first bite trespasses this gossamer barrier and your tastebuds are ambushed by what&#39;s inside. Â There is the sharp aromatic tang of curry, the starchy slightly sweet embrace of potato, made perfect by the sweet spice of sweated red onions and shallots. Â Oh yes, and Balmoral&#39;s samosa has savory pieces of chicken in this already wonderful medley. Â Truly diabolical, methinks. Â I bit into this thing expecting the pedestrian experience of a plain samosa and end up with a curry puff wrapped in a popiah skin! Â  It had all the elements of an epiphany of the finest kind, it involved a simple mouthful of something truly wonderful that I was not anticipating, that neither my brain nor the jaded papules of my tongue were expecting and I was left just a little breathless after that special first bite. Â <br><br>Just so very wonderfully cool to live, explore and eat in Singapore!

In an era with overly pimped pastries and &#39;salted egg yolk&#39; flavours tiding, it is comforting to have a bakery like Balmoral.<br><br>Old school is the way to go, and not go wrong. Bakeries like this can last many years without resorting to gimmicks to cater to trendssss.<br><br>I love the samosas here, they contain generous chunks of chicken instead of the seedy minced to the death mix that you have no idea what you are eating.<br><br>The custard puff was piped nicely and wasn&#39;t too sweet.<br><br>Custard puffs and bite sized cakes will steal your heart with very affordable prices. <br><br>This is one box of goodies that you would gladly bring back to the office for value and your tummy&#39;s sake to share the calories!

text: An old-school bakery with a variety of traditional and some almost extinct cakes/pastries. One friend raved about the cream puff. Another friend enjoyed the chicken pie but found that there was more potatoes than meat. My own favorite was the banana cake- fresh, fragrant and not too sweet. Overall a nice place that brings back childhood memories with a few must try items whereas it seems like the rest can be hit or miss.

Balmoral Bakery is one of the old school bakeries that we look upon to as every visit here bring us good flashbacks to our younger times when having such simple stuff on earth makes our day. In the current environment that we are in, it is less often that we will come across such down to earth design of the cakes.<br><br>With many bakeries keeping up with the modern equipment and modern look in their shop, this facade of the Balmoral bakery remains humble with red bricks by the side of the walls. Walking into the shop is like a walking back into the past with the time machine.<br><br>Made up of Multi layers crispy &#34;biscuits&#34; with the top as chocolate and icing. In its buttery fragrance and the flaky thin layers, one tends to get addicted over it.<br><br>The nostalgic feeling when you saw the blueberry puree topped the cake with a cream layer in between. To be frank, I was never a fan of blueberry cake when I was young as many of my birthday cakes were all covered with similar blueberries. However, it brought back a lot of good memories with cake having a old school taste!<br><br>The traditional flavour that I love most is perhaps this Swiss roll that topped with peanut chunks and sugar. I always find this special somehow as compared to the usual Swiss Rolls cradling the creams.<br><br>There are quite a few flavours of Swiss Roll to choose from like Pandan, Vanilla and Chocolate. These little Swiss Rolls were being shrink wrapped and placed in the chiller to maintain the moist. We had the most basic flavour of all.<br><br>Besides selling cakes, they have pastries like Beef and chicken pie. I will be back again for other items.

This is unlike your commercial bakery found all over Singapore. They serve the traditional puffs and cakes that are now too rare or way too processed. Walking in, you will immediately realize that they have very different choices from most bakery and yet it smells wonderful. The aroma makes you want to get something. <br><br>A few specialties I have tried there are their char siew song, chicken pie and curry chicken puff. Their char siew song is my favorite. They make everything, including their char siew in-house. It is very crispy on the outside and delicious barbecued char siew on the inside. The combination is just perfect. The curry chicken puff is also very tasty with spicy chicken, eggs and potato filling. Their prices are also very affordable at $1.20 - $1.80 a piece.<br><br>It is always lovely to find a local place that keeps some of the traditional flavors. Definitely worth a visit!

text: This is the bakery that I always go to when I am in a particularly nostalgic mood. Everything is super old school- the kind of bakery that still pipes their cakes with sugary pastel-coloured creams and cartoon figurines, even in an era where fondant reigns. Strangely though, there is something very comforting about the mixture of butter cream and sponge cake and perhaps that is the reason why I keep coming back.<br><br>It is possible to custom design your cakes. Everything looks kind of vintage and cool- I have seen cakes modeled after cars and having every bit of the &#39;glossiness&#39; through the boss&#39; ingenious use of jelly icing, football poles on sports-themed cakes made out of chocolate wafers etc. Prices are also pretty reasonable for the kind of handiwork you get. To me the best part of the cakes is that they always look so home made, not the kind of rive gauche cakes that you wouldnt even bear to cut up.

text: Being their customer for more than a decade proves how good this old school Hainanese Singaporean bakery is. Their cakes and pastries are good, especially their Samosas and chicken pie

Balmoral Bakery is most probably one of Singapore&#39;s longest standing and most authentic pie-oneers, readying their piecrusts and baking for generations before us. 40 years is definitely a long, long time in a country that does not have much of a baking history, and their pies are testament to how they have managed to perfect their craft.<br><br>Coming in at an affordable $1.30, their chicken pies look exactly the same as they did back in 1965, as it&#39;s still the same person behind and the exact same baking equipment. Their quality chicken chunks, and &#39;al dente&#39; peas that burst with delicious gravy are sure to leave you hungering for more.

text: Having patronized this store for over 10 years, it was no difficult feat coming back for the cream horns that have played a significant part in my childhood. The cream horn ($1.20) is small-more or the size of one&#39;s palm-and stuffed to the brim with cream. To date, this remains their signature product, and it cannot not be found in other bakeries. The bread is crispy, albeit sometimes a little burnt, and each bite causes a mini explosion of cream into one&#39;s mouth and a shower of bread crumbs onto the floor. The shop claims to be one of the few carrying a new tasty treat called Napolean($1.20), which cannot be yet found in any other shops. Other sweet treats worth trying would be the eggtarts($1) and creampuffs ($1.10). Opening hours: Mon to Sun 9am-8pm.

text: Most people review Nassim Hill for it&#39;s brunch, to be fair: I have also been several times for brunch and never felt the need to write about it, it is decent but nothing out of the ordinary.<br><br>When my girlfriends and I discovered they also do Ladies night, free flow prosecco with a minimum spend of 35$ per head, we decided to come on a Wednesday night. I categorized the night as follows:<br><br>THE GOOD:<br>- Burrata, arugula, tomatoes and watermelon - tasted fresh and yum, almost ordered a second one.<br>- The Big dipper (crab, artichoke and spinach dip): good dip but not enough bread, extra charge for more bread.<br>- Poutine: tasty fries, however they should not call it Poutine as it does not taste like it, more like loaded fries.<br>- Prosecco: two types available and the staff is generous with the top-ups (when asked)<br><br>THE SO-SO:<br>- Grilled Chicken Quesadilla <br>- Steak and eggs<br>- Sweet potato fries<br>- The service: I guess your typical spotty service, had to ask for top ups of the drinks and remind them of our request for extra bread.<br><br>THE BAD:<br>- Roasted bone marrow: typically one my favorite things to eat but had literally no flavor, looked impressive though.<br><br>Overall I find this one of the better Ladies Night deals and there were quite a few dishes I gladly eat again so 3.5 stars rounded up to 4.

Nice play for brunch. We had the skillet eggs (their take on the Shakshouka) and Eggs Benedict. Slightly pricey even by Singapore standards but the food was tasty. Finished off with a pear crumble with ice cream which was delicious!!

text: First time here. The food came quickly but the service staff needs a lot more training. They don&#39;t look happy as well. <br><br>The waffles were good. I had the bacon cheddar waffles. Very fluffy and tasty. The Belgian waffles were good too. Eggs Ben ok, nothing to shout about. <br><br>Nice place to have brunch as long as you&#39;re having waffles. Will come for lunch or dinner one day to try the rest of the menu.

text: I have been back several times since my review and the food is still good.<br><br>It can get crowded and they do take reservations. Call early as they will close the reservation list once it reaches its limit. Then it will be walk in only. <br><br>The menu has been refreshed but the many favorites remained. <br><br>The skillet eggs is pretty spicy but it is so good. I am quite taken with the spicy huevos Benedict. It comes sprinkled with chili padi. Wow! <br><br>The coffee is from LIberty Coffee which is one of my favorites, plus it is a double shot. I don&#39;t know much about coffee or where Liberty coffee is from, but it is smooth and is not too acidic. I don&#39;t need to add sugar to my flat white. So yay!<br><br>The burger is also a good and safe choice. I am not that into its pasta or poutine though. Get the sweet potato fries and waffle. It is one of the better ones around. For a light bite, the chicken quesadilla is pretty delish. <br><br>I just saw the dinner menu and the rosemary lamb chop description looks tempting. So I guess I need to go back again for dinner some day.

text: I&#39;m torn between giving 4 and 5 stars, so I&#39;m going to be generous and give a 5. I don&#39;t think the place is perfect, but nothing really offended me.<br><br>I came here for brunch on a Saturday with a friend. The online reservation was fully booked, but they said we could walk in. Walking in before 11am was OK. We were seated immediately. Soon after, the place really started to fill up. <br><br>I had the bacon and cheese waffles, and my friend had the blueberry pancakes. The blueberry pancakes were extremely fluffy, and tasted just right. My bacon waffles tasted more of bacon and cheese than waffles. Definitely delicious. We ordered a cup of tea each, and that wasn&#39;t memorable. They give you a teapot of hot water, which is good for about three teacups. The water kept warm for a long time, which was surprising.<br><br>I thought the food was well done, although it would have been a better deal if it was a dollar or two cheaper. I used my DBS credit card and got 10% off so that was pretty sweet. This is the first brunch place I&#39;ve been to in Singapore, and I wouldn&#39;t mind coming back again. But I would like to check other places out.

text: Although this place seems to be a brunch place, I came for dinner. I started with the truffle fries, they were really good, finished the bucket in minutes. <br><br>We ordered the Chilli Crab Pasta, Asian Salad and Sausage with Mashed Potato. <br><br>The salad was great, the serving was bountiful, it looked appetizing as well. The Chilli Crab Pasta was great too, it was on the reviews, we weren&#39;t disappointed. However, the sausages and mashed potatoes were a bit disappointing. The potatoes were a bit to oily and didn&#39;t really have enough taste to make me want to order it again. The sausages were average.<br><br>Overall, this place was great! The ambiance is soothing and calming. Although it has a bar, it didn&#39;t really make a big difference. There were a lot of locals eating there also for dinner, I guess that shows that people really come back for the food and ambiance.
Don&#39;t know who marked this as good for kids! They don&#39;t have a kids menu! And that&#39;s just the start....

Sunday brunch here was an Eggs Benedict. It took a while to come, so be prepared to wait.<br><br>So my Eggs B wasn&#39;t awesome, but the bread they served before you eat what you ordered is amazing, so it made up for the lacklustre eggs. <br><br>My friend had a decent coffee (or so he said). This place is a wee bit inaccessible without a car, because it&#39;s quite far from the nearest MRT station (Orchard), so come here with a friend who drives, or even better, don&#39;t come at all. Food was pricy and I didn&#39;t feel satisfied with my brunch.

text: T menu is different and lovely . All sooo so yummy .. <br>Cant decide on a favorite<br><br>Look at t drink list too <br>Yummy Yuzu breeze

Never returning to this place. There are so many cafes in Singapore, so to be competitive I think the very least is to have kickass food or service. Customer service really sets the tone of your restaurant. I&#39;m sure I had special sauce in my food today. <br><br>The staff are smiley until a hiccup happens. This is what I mean - today I ordered a cake and coffee set before ordering a snack. This is all within like 10 minutes apart. when the savory snack arrived, I moved the cake to the side to eat the snack first. Halfway through it, I realized the cake was missing! We completely did not see the waitress clear it, but we only had 3 bites and it was such a waste to clear. We informed her it was a mistake and she said she assumed we didn&#39;t want it since we put it to the side (Just ask next time!). She was apologetic and said she would get it back. <br><br>You wouldn&#39;t believe what she did next. She brought half a slice of the cake. A half slice! We were weirded out. I mean, what is she going to do with the other half? I thought that was completely cheap. We were like huh? And she told us it&#39;s because we ate almost half of the cake (not true) but whatever, the cake was ok tasting but not worth this rubbish! <br><br>If they can be so cheap, you won&#39;t want to know what lame ingredients they may be using. <br><br>So yeah, no smiles from all the staff after we complained it wasn&#39;t cool to be cheap about the cake. It&#39;s such a small matter but they&#39;ve lost some pigs as customers.

text: As my kids just said to me: &#34;Why aren&#39;t we coming here more often?! This is great!&#34;<br><br>We dropped in for breakfast after I dragged my kids to get their injections. Consider it an amazing bribe. Our order was delivered quickly and service was fantastic. The food was well prepared, beautifully presented and delicious. The food &amp; ambiance is unpretentious and comforting. My flat white was full flavoured without relying on fancy coffee art to tell me it was well crafted. (I am not against coffee art if the coffee is good.)<br><br>Will we be back more often? Definitely.

text: Decided to come here with a few others on a Saturday around 6.45pm. Parking was pretty easy but the layout of the building was like a maze and after 5 minutes, my friend and I figured out how to reach the front of this cafe and towards the end, we realized there was another shortcut (next to the lift) and you could walk in from the back door.<br><br>Ordered these few dishes<br>1) Tonkatsu (entree) - portion was pretty small and it was only an average dish with a high price tag.<br>2) Full sized chili crab (pasta) - didn&#39;t have much crab meats in the dish and doesn&#39;t look photo worthy like the pictures on the website my friend gave me.<br>3) Two faced pizza - half salami and half blue cheese with arugula. This was pretty good. Pizza come in thin crusts which made it crunchy. Even though the ingredients were rather normal, somehow the mixed ingredients added flavor to the two different types of pizza.<br>4) popcorn chicken bites - came free as an option if you made a reservation through hungrygowhere. Came in smaller pieces but was pretty good after a few bites. Not as crunchy as I thought it may be and I couldn&#39;t taste much of the sriracha sauce.<br>5) pear cheddar crumble (dessert) - was not too bad but would probably prefer the crumbles to be more flaky and crunchy.<br><br>Price here was pretty steep and the food wasn&#39;t too impressive either. Definitely a good place to chill if you are into alcoholic beverages.
