text: Friends suggested lunch here to enjoy the good ambience and good food. I am impressed with the interior design of the cafe which gives out this relaxing vibe once you&#39;re inside. <br><br>Many reviews suggested a Hot Reuben so I&#39;m not gonna ignore that.<br><br>Turned out that the sandwich was massive (for me at least) and my friend actually betted that I couldn&#39;t finish it by myself. So to prove him wrong (I&#39;m a fighter), I ate slowly to savour and also to not overkill myself in the start of the meal. The sandwich was rich in flavour and I can&#39;t break it down to the individual tastes but it all came together very nicely. <br><br>I opted for the set and they had cauliflower soup then. It was smooth and good and flavourful! Nice! <br><br>The ambience was very chillaxing and a beautiful way to start the morning. The interior is clean and bright, plus it sure doesn&#39;t hurt to have the whole place smell of fresh bread to hit you (nicely) in the face as you walk in.<br><br>Will bring hubby here to share the beautiful experience.

text: Good food, fresh ingredients! I&#39;m a fan of the Shakshouka. The hot reuben was a bit disappointing though. Taste of the pastrami was a bit bland, underwhelming. And once again, Singapore, why so kiam siap! (Look at the photo. Just look at it.) There should be twice as much pastrami in there. And more sauerkraut. C&#39;mon. You can&#39;t even see the pastrami when the dish arrives!

Sitting next to the post office on Nassim Hill is not the best spot for a restaurant, parking not great luckily I can walk from my office for lunch. Â They have a decent selection of sandwiches and lunch fares service is ok. Â Some of the options are tastier/more flavorful than others. Not my favorite place but good for change up from typical Tanglin food.

text: what impressed me most is their spaciousness, the stained glass art and their artisan bread.<br><br>service however, can be spotty. some tables get water automatically but others have to ask for it.<br><br>their coffee for me is over priced at $6 and of below par standard.<br><br>a lack of free wifi and sufficiently current reading materials also make it less worth hanging around.<br><br>sausages and scrambled eggs were nice.<br><br>charcuterie is nothing to shout about.<br><br>french toast almond brioche had a nice taste and bite but could be accompanied with some extras like fruits to make it less plain in presentation.<br><br>the place starts filling up quickly after 10am on a sunday morning.

A go-to brunch place for a couple of reasons.<br><br>- The Chili Crab Spaghetti is insanely, insanely delicious. Spicy with lots of chilli padi and the most perfect chilli crab sauce, fit for pasta. I happily finished the $25 bowl.<br><br>- The egg dishes are fairly well done and consistent. The chocolate banana waffle stack is quite a load if you like eating dessert for brunch. I&#39;m personally not a fan of their dry french toast. <br><br>- The free bread baskets have excellent bread. Eat them carbs people.<br><br>- Nassim Hill is generally frequented by the older aunty/uncle or family crowd, as opposed to young kids with SLRs and too much make up. I don&#39;t know but somehow that makes me feel more at peace eating a meal there. The tables are also fairly spaced out so you don&#39;t have to listen to annoying, vapid mealtime conversations. <br><br>- Prices are decent <br><br>The one thing I don&#39;t like is the service. It&#39;s a bit of a blank-stare-who-ordered-this-item kind of place and they serve water when you&#39;re about to die from a parched throat. Otherwise, this is a safe weekend bet.

text: Popped by around the area during lunchtime on a Tuesday and the staff seemed overwhelmed by the crowd. The pair of us managed to get a seat without reservation luckily. Long story short, our coffee orders got mixed up with the table behind and the Cheddar Cheese with Bacon Waffle arrived at the table looking haphazardly put together. Staff forgot the condiments for the waffle so my partner chewed through half a dry waffle before I realised that the next table had butter and honey to go with their waffles. The skillet eggs I had was really good though and I liked that it was spicier than others I&#39;ve tried so far. The flat whites which we finally had after much confusion and sorting out, were really decent too. It was just unfortunate that the staff was unable to cope with the swarming lunch crowd on our visit.

text: one of my newest favorites - so good I returned a second time in a matter of three days (sometimes you have to give in be kind to yourself). both times, i was surprised at such fantastic execution of brunch classics - it&#39;s good, simple cooking done well; big portions I want for a meal that marries the best of the morning and the start of the afternoon; a beautiful space with beautiful people and the option of champagne.<br><br>everything we had was better-than-average and well on its way to excellent, so let&#39;s start with that. a plate of three american-type pancakes came with a scoop of blueberry ice-cream, berry compote, crumble sprinkles, and REAL maple syrup. <br><br>the hot reuben is a house specialty - and deservedly so. it&#39;s a hearty wholegrain beer bread with enough structural integrity to hold the melting morass of cheese, sauerkraut and corned beef in, served alongside a fresh green salad. quite completely delicious, and properly rave-worthy.<br><br>on my second visit, I had the grilled cajun chicken on wholegrain; not nearly as fantastic as the hot reuben, but this was a very generous portion of marinated chicken stuffed between actually-crunchy leaves and another bit of good bread.<br><br>both the poached and scrambled eggs were decently done too - but you must finish with the waffles - dark-brown belgians with crunchy exteriors but still creamy enough inside, dusted with icing sugar and served with more of that delicious syrup. the sausage alongside was tasty enough - it&#39;s a hearty breakfast or a could-I-have-more-please dessert.<br><br>this is as sparkling a review I can write while being objective, and really - just give it a go, it&#39;s pretty darn brilliant.

text: One of our favorite weekend places for brekkie/brunch. Been here a couple of times and really enjoy the food and relaxed atmosphere here, the service staff are friendly too. Never had a problem with food taking a long time to arrive. <br><br>So far we&#39;ve tried the whole meal waffles, pancakes, fish and chips, egg breakfast sets and they were all yummy and of good portions. <br><br>The coffees here are good too and double shots, only thing missing is they don&#39;t have the option of soy milk available. <br><br>The gingerbread cookie they serve with the coffee and tea are delicious and we usually buy a whole bag to take home :)

text: Recommended by ex-pats living in Shangri-La Apartments... Â everything here is fantastic.. steaks, wine, Mac &amp; Cheese..
Tasty breads and great coffee. If you happen to be in the neighborhood, this is a good place to get a hearty breakfast!

For full reviews and photos, visit my blog!<br><br>If you want a quiet brunch in town, Nassim Hill Bakery, Â does a good job of satisfying an egg craving. The outpost at the hidden part of Tanglin Post Office is nowhere to be seen from the main road. <br><br>The place wasn&#39;t too packed on a Saturday afternoon. I don&#39;t think 1pm is too late for brunch. I hope it stays this way, though i&#39;ve let out on this secret. Bistro and Bakery by day, Nassim Hill Bakery does a wholesome breakfast food for egg crazy people like me. At night, she transforms into a bar serving unique cocktails and the aromatic Grimbergen draught beers (A Belgian abbey beer first to debut in Asia and exclusive to Nassim Hill and 1128). A dinner menu is also available.<br><br>All breakfast sets comes with a basket of bread, all freshly baked by Freshly Baked, one of my favorite bakeries! Head Baker Audrey takes charge of the bakery section and supplied Nassim Hill Bakery with the same breads that is ever so perfect and familiar. The bread basket includes the fluffy white ciabatta, the yeasty and malty Grimbergen Ambree bread, fluffy Walnut raisin bread and cereal rye bread.<br><br>The Hearty Scrambled Eggs ($20) was creamy and runny and it was served with Swiss cheese, French Rosette de Lyon salami or prosciutto with our signature Grimbergen AmbrÃ©e beer bread.<br><br>Lovely Eggs Benedict ($20) on the airy white ciabatta pillows. Perfectly poached eggs with chunky succulent and sweet smoked ham, creamy hollandaise sauce with the right amount of acidity, what more can i ask for in a Benny? I reluctantly swapped a half of my benny with S&#39;s Hot Reuben, which i ordered for him because i wanted to try. Haha. <br><br>I did not regret exchanging our dishes at all. Seriously, this is the star attraction at Nassim Hill. The Hot Reuben ($18) is a massive sandwich of sliced corned beef with melted emmental cheese, saurkraut, onions and Russian dressing on their signature Grimbergen AmbrÃ©e beer bread. This sandwich is absolutely appetizing and no one flavor overpowered the other. The malty aroma in the bread could be tasted in every bite. This is definitely my must-order from now on. <br><br>Their coffees ain&#39;t quite impressive and neither were their iced teas. The mocha was way too sweet, even for the boy with the sweet tooth. Chocolate syrup=meh but i love the ginger snapps that came with it. Yums. <br><br>Adding to my list of yummy brunches in town!

text: Came here for brunch on a Sunday. My friend and I started out the day right with a beer each. I had an amber and my friend had a blonde. The beers were poured into frosted glasses, and were very refreshing. I could keep drinking and drinking my amber if not for the fact that my food came very soon after.<br><br>So I ordered a reuben sandwich. The bread was nice and soft with a slight sweetness to it. The pastrami was tender. There was nice onions in the sandwich too. But I wasn&#39;t impressed, and in fact was rather frustrated at why I was still underwhelmed. After a whole day of thinking and discussing with fellow foodies, it finally dawned on me that (and this is kinda embarrassing for me to admit this) the sandwich was just not greasy enough! Maybe I&#39;m used to something with more spice, something with more cheese, something with more warmth. Something this healthier version didn&#39;t quite meet.

text: Nassim Hill Bakery Bistro Bar has one of the most interesting concepts - bakery with brunch items in the dawn, bistro in the noon, and transformed to a charming bar by dusk with DJs spinning at the side. <br><br>If this bar within a post office concept seems familiar to you, it is also done up by Imaginings who is also behind KPO, WALA WALA, Balaclava and 1128. Beer drinkers can rejoice because you can tap your own draught beers at the end of the counter. (I unfortunately, don&#39;t drink beer.) <br><br>Considering I am not quite a carb-person, I fell in love with the Grimbergen Ambree bread ($8), a Grimbergen (Belgian abbey beers) infused bread created by Head Baker Audrey from Freshly Baked at Killiney Road. (No wonder the bread and cakes taste so familiar. The KPO probably approached her since they are &#39;neighbours&#39;.) The bread is very wholesome, full-bodied and hearty, with a slightly rustic feel to it. Extremely satisfying with the marmalade jam.

text: We made our way to north Singapore on one of the weekends in 2020 (Nothing to do, can&#39;t travel out, so have to explore every part of the city!). It is very close to the Lower Pierce reservoir park, so its a nice place to hang out after/before visiting the park. They have pretty decent coffee, and nice cold pressed juice. We went late afternoon, post lunch, so didn&#39;t order any food. But the food menu looked interesting and we would definitely give it another try if we were in the area again.
Nice Starbucks, free WiFi and not outrageously expensive.<br><br>There is no milk or cream at the counters like we have in North America. Â Be sure to ask the casher/server for some.

Should you consider to buy a muffin or cake or something at this place, reconsider. The hygienic standards don&#39;t seem to be the highest here. We just witnessed a staff member whose hair fell on 8 or 10 muffins while packing something else. The muffins were obviously not thrown away. Apart from that, a staff member was carrying a baby behind the counter. <br><br>I will definitely not go there again.

text: The only Starbucks at the Marina Bay Financial Center. Located at the Marina Link Mall (underground) which is accessible to the Downtown MRT station and Raffles Place MRT station. <br><br>Had to ask two persons how to get there from the office towers. One needs to enter through the entrance at Tower One and take the escalator down and keep walking. One should see the store ahead. <br><br>My first tall no whip hot chocolate from Starbucks since I stepped foot on this sunny island last month. It was not good. Was I expecting it to be amazing? Not really :(<br><br>Staffs were friendly. Lots of seatings. <br><br>Was waiting for someone to show up and he did not. Never feel so sad leaving a Starbucks. This a first but it was not Starbucks&#39; fault and no one else either.<br><br>Update: 7/20/2017<br><br>My 2nd time to this same exact Starbucks. I guessed it was a &#34;cruel&#34; twist of fate I was sent to the Raffles Medical Center @ Marina Bay Financial Center Tower 3 by my doctor at Raffles Hospital. The previous time I left this Starbucks feeling so awful, though by a twist of event my friend turned up looking for me but I already left. It was quite a story. Anyhow this is not a place for me to write my own life story, lol!<br><br>FOOD/DRINK<br>Drink was great, I no longer want to compare the hot chocolate I always have in Atlanta. <br><br>AMBIENCE <br>Lots of seating area. I like it. <br><br>STAFF(S)<br>Friendly and seemed nice like any other Starbucks barista I encountered here in Singapore. I have no complaints.
Prices are a lot higher than expected but good food options and lots of great drinks.

text: I live in the area, and am always interested in trying new places. I love the location of this restaurant, so peaceful and the layout of the place is very comfortable and welcoming. The menu is the perfect size, not too many dishes to choose from so that you&#39;re overwhelmed, but just enough to have some good variety. I went for lunch with my wife, and we split the poutine to start and then I had the poached salmon as a meal. Both dishes were tasty, though I wish the salmon had been a bit larger or maybe some more garnish. I didn&#39;t feel as though I got enough food for the money. I will definitely go to this restaurant again to try out some other dishes, maybe it was just the salmon that wasn&#39;t enough for me. <br><br>I have one other suggestion, as a person who grew up on the Canadian border, poutine was regular in my childhood diet. Nearly every restaurant in the area where I grew up served it, so I am very familiar with the Quebec taste and cuisine. My suggestion is: use Cheese curd. I&#39;m not sure what kind of cheese was being used, but it was not plentiful, there should have been more and larger pieces. Also, more gravy!<br><br>This place has a lot going for it, a lot of potential. Just needs to make some minor adjustments to get me to move it up past 3 stars.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/c8p77YT56jEcY9qAvsQSBw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/starbucks-orchard?reviewid=UBW_KtMwktCVfSYBPjaAGw&select=c8p77YT56jEcY9qAvsQSBw', 'altText': 'Photo of Starbucks - Orchard, Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: The baristas here are always so nice. I have been by a few times during my visit to singapore and they always very politely answer all my dumb American questions like if they have pumpkin spice lattes or if my mobile app will work here. Starbucks has consistent drinks and merchandise, but the service is variable and I like that this store is consistently friendly.<br><br>I take that part about the consistent drinks back. Starbucks in Asia have some interesting drinks unavailable in the US. I&#39;ve had matcha tea with red bean in Indonesia and yogurt citrus drinks in Singapore. Apparently I can&#39;t get PSLs anywhere but North America, but I can settle for caramel macchiatos, and regular lattes. I also like collecting the city Starbucks mugs and picked up some singapore espresso shot mugs here (I&#39;ve never seen these little cups anywhere else). <br><br>This store has a little seating area upstairs from the cashier. It&#39;s cute and comfortable, but can get crowded in the early afternoon. I&#39;m also soooooo happy that they finally got free wifi. I was getting tired of walking across the street to the cuppage st. location.

text: I was in town to run some errands yesterday and decided to drop by Gather to grab a quick takeaway lunch. The pastrami sandwich is delicious - lightly toasted ciabatta, beef pastrami with sweet chili relish, rocket, and Emmental cheese. the sandwich was going for $14 and I could nitpick, I wished there was more meat in the sandwich. <br><br>I also bought their seasonal cold brew - Generra and Wicked. Both equally delicious and addictive ($9 each). Generra is mocha infused with orange zest while Wicked is infused with mint. I know the coffee elitist will be rolling their eyes while reading about Generra and Wicked, but hey, why limit yourself to only filter coffee or the usuals. It&#39;s OK to try a variety of coffee beverages right? <br><br>If you&#39;re in City Hall area and looking for a quick takeaway and not wanting the hassle to go into the mall, check out Gather. It&#39;s located at Raffles Hotel Arcade and directly opposite across the road from Brotzeit (at Raffles City). I recommend this place!

text: Had their Toblerone coffee mocha today for the very first time. Def loving it so soo much! It&#39;s a great choice if you are not really in the mood for some strong coffee. You&#39;d be able to taste both the dark chocolate and the coffee right from the first sip to the last drop. They don&#39;t use any kind of syrup at all in all kind of their chocolate mocha drinks (not like Starbucks). I can testify on that cos I saw the whole process when my barista was making my drink. Here you&#39;ll be spoiled by choice for your chocolate options. You could pick any of these: Cadbury, Toblerone, van Houten, Milka, Lindt, Godiva. You could literally have different chocolate coffee mocha mix everyday.<br><br>My old times favorite are definitely Hawaiian latte, cold brew and matcha latte. Even though there are 2 other coffee shops in the same building, YCC would get my vote by a lot. The barista here definitely knows what they are doing. The coffee always tastes consistently very good all day every day.

HEAVEN!!<br><br>Laksa- first time trying it and it was pretty good. Full of flavor to soothe the soul.<br><br>Mee Tai Bak Soup- my favorite of the 3. Perfectly flavored and hearty. I enjoyed every bite of this bowl. <br><br>Kopi- the best coffee I&#39;ve ever had!!! I would love a cup of this RIGHT NOW!<br><br>This is a great go to if u want good food at a fast pace. Actually, getting food anywhere in Singapore is pretty quick.

text: A pleasant and cosy halal cafe which sells decent bakes and drinks. Haven&#39;t tried their mains but their cakes are pretty delicious-love their crumbly carrot walnut cake topped with cream cheese and walnuts. <br><br>I&#39;ll skip the tea lattes, which are single tea bags soaked in warm milk. They are average but lacking the distinct flavour at the price and would be better if they could cold brew their teas beforehand.

text: Tucked between boutiques along the citylink connector, this little Rive Gauche outlet (comprising one refrigerated case and two small tables) is easy to miss. <br><br>Their signature Guanaja ($7/slice) is a cake that one can never get enough of. The light sponge, punctuated by layers of mousse is sandwiched between a shiny layer of rich dark chocolate ganache on top, and a crispy hazelnut base made of cornflake crumbs below. The flavor is well-balanced; though rich, the cake remains pleasantly light in terms of texture, which leaves one craving more down to the last bite. <br><br>Due to the low human traffic here, they have many promotions worth capitalizing on: <br>1. Tea set ($6): one slice of cake and tea/coffee. Top up 50 cents for a latte. <br>2. Daily promo: All slices of cakes for $5 (not too sure if this is still available)<br><br>In conclusion, though Rive Gauche can be found in many places, this branch has a quiet charm that&#39;ll definitely bring me back!

text: Nice ambience.<br><br>Nutty brownie with ice cream. Separately, the brownie is average, the ice cream disappoints, but together they are delightful. <br><br>Salted caramel milkshake is the best I ever tasted. Very well balanced. Hint of chocolate, does not overpower the salted caramel flavour. Slightly expensive for milkshake.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/oAGj3ksHp5hhhSKXKfaEXQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/max-brenner-chocolate-bar-singapore-2?reviewid=Vb_jCqXFQQrvQA2cMhGkyA&select=oAGj3ksHp5hhhSKXKfaEXQ', 'altText': 'Photo of Max Brenner Chocolate Bar - Singapore, Singapore. Big chunks of ice that were in my milkshake, cradled by the large uneaten portion of the hard chocolate topping.', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Big chunks of ice that were in my milkshake, cradled by the large uneaten portion of the hard chocolate topping.'}]
text: Maybe I just have unreasonable expectations, but this seemed overpriced, overprocessed, and mediocre.<br><br>I asked what their most popular milkshake was and they recommended the 80&#39;s chocolate shake. It came with a scoop of not very good vanilla ice cream on top (instead of mixed in) with what looked/tasked like Smucker&#39;s hard shell chocolate topping on top - not something I would normally eat.<br><br>Then the milkshake hurt my teeth because there were big chucks of ice in it. Who puts ice in a milkshake? Especially an $11 milkshake? I feel like this is a case of paying more to get a worse product. I wish I had gone to Ben &amp; Jerry&#39;s or Cold Stone.

Chocolate lovers would like this place just because everything here is chocolate. My friend and I tried the Italian cream and spicy hot chocolates respectively. The Italian cream was really thick, which is great at first but gets too sweet and jelat later on. The spicy hot chocolate was actually pretty spicy, but I only tasted a bit of it so I don&#39;t know whether the spiciness wears off. My friend seemed to like it pretty well. <br><br>It&#39;s a good place to have a long afternoon chat since it&#39;s very quiet, but it can get pricey and the chocolate drink was too sweet for my taste.

My friend and I ordered The Italian and Mexican Hot Dark Chocolate drinks. <br><br>The Italian drink was a bit too thick to drink and didn&#39;t taste unique.<br><br>If you like to spice up your hot chocolate, I&#39;d recommend the Mexican drink. I could taste the spice from the cinnamon and nutmeg. However, the spice tapered after a couple of sips. <br><br>Though it was good, it wasn&#39;t worth $7.50 for the drinks, especially since the drinks got cold really quickly.

text: I think almost every chocolate lover in town must have heard of Max Brenner&#39;s Chocolate Bar. It has some of the best chocolate in town. The concept of the stall is really pretty. Â <br><br>We ordered banana crepe with caramel and chocolate dip. When it comes, the crepe looks super crispy. When we opened the crepe, there is chocolate inside it together with banana. My suggestion will be, the crepe is already pretty sweet. Therefore, the dip is not required. It tasted really nice. For some reason, I can&#39;t help linking it back to roti prata stuffed with banana and chocolate inside.<br>Their chocolate is really sweet. But it does giving me an urge to go back for more. Will definitely be a frequent customer if their prices are cheaper?

text: Theatre and tons of chocolate. Great for kids, and kids at heart. <br><br>Despite being loved by the ladies, the chocolate pizza was a tad too sweet for me. On the contrary, the molten lava cake, was done just the way I like it - not too sweet, gooey, and served with a scoop of ice-cream. The chocolate crepe with berries was the dish of the evening. <br><br>A great end to an otherwise average foodie evening out.

Chocolate Dip!', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Chocolate Dip!'}]
text: Not worth the money.. ordered Chocolate Dip, worth $16 and got a cup of melted chocolate with slices of strawberries. No plating, nothing added to the plate, no pictures the menu. Disappointed!

Love chocolate? Then Max Brenner is a must-try. There is enough chocolate on the menu to make an Oompa-Loompa giddy!<br><br>Try the traditional hot chocolate for starters. It really fills you with warmth that seeps to all corners of your soul.<br><br>The chocolate souffle is to die for, though it&#39;s a bit too rich. Then again, I&#39;m not so huge a fan of chocolate so others may find it just right.<br><br>My favourite is the Fantastic Popsicle Chocolate Fondue. You&#39;re given a vanilla ice cream and three small bowls of chocolate stuff to dip, such as hazelnut and tiny chocolate balls. If you&#39;re going to order only one thing, make it this!<br><br>The service is not fantastic, but the staff aren&#39;t rude or anything, just a little inattentive but it&#39;s not a big problem. Also, I&#39;m not really sure how they wash the metal straws! :O

If you call yourself a chocolate lover, then you should really head down to Max Brenner Chocolate Bar to try some of their chocolate and chocolate-inspired delights.<br><br>I was recommended to order the hot chocolate, or rather the hug mug. Although Singapore isn&#39;t that cold to truly enjoy a piping hot chocolate to warm you body, I really loved how rich the chocolate in your drink tasted. <br><br>It is also a good place for desserts, but of course, you got to pay a little more for their quality cocoa.

This is a difficult place to find because it is located in the basement level. Â It&#39;s actually next door to the McDonald&#39;s behind Shiraz on Orchard.<br><br>Like all Killiney&#39;s, this place located off Orchard was a regular place for me to go to get coffee. Â  Very good cheap breakfasts eats here. Â For $S4.50 (about $US4), you can purchase a coffee, soft boiled egg, and French Toast. Â They offer a take out as well. Â The French Toast is similar to French Toast back at home (toast battered in egg) but unique in the kind of bread used and served with kaya, a coconut flavored jam that&#39;s pretty good.<br><br>I do not know how they do it, but their coffee, served with sweet condensed milk is always perfect. Â I seldom drink coffee with milk or sugar, but when I come here, I have it the way they serve it and it&#39;s always the best.

text: Good food, but there is this one aunty that just absolutely hate people. I dont know how you stay open that long with that lady running the cashier. There is so many kopitiam in singapore, I wont be coming back. <br><br>To be working in hospitality industry, first you need hospitality.

If they want more business they have got to get their act together. Â If customer is waiting grab it first then do what u got to do to fix what they need. Â Don&#39;t leave then standing and waiting. Â Staff attitude definitely needs an overhaul.

text: Lao Huo Tang is a great place to go for a good hearty serving of chinese herbal soup. Served from large metal cauldrons and set in a pretty traditional coffee shop with traditional chinese letterings decorating the walls, Lao Huo Tang takes you back a few decades as you enjoy their herby offerings.<br><br>My favourite soups from Lao Huo Tang are the Old cucumber pork rib soup and their Watercress pork rib soup. While I could do with a few more slices of old cucumber in the soup, the old cucumber pork rib soup is awesome and very tasty. Same goes for the watercress pork rib soup. They also give a pretty hearty amount of pork ribs, which is always a good thing. I like the fact that they do not use MSG or artificial flavourings in their soups, hence all the flavours that come through are from the ingredients and herbs used, making it a healthy and hearty meal.

text: This was a really chill place to hang out, and I may come back the next time I&#39;m looking for a quiet comfy (air conditioned!!) place to read and write in the Raffles Place area. A haven among the usual order-and-go coffee joints in the CBD.<br><br>I came here ~10am and stayed until lunchtime, nursing an iced latte with vanilla. The baristas were really friendly and made me feel welcome. The latte was pretty good, though I regret ordering this vanilla thing to try in substitute of fresh milk - it sounded interesting, but really overwhelmed the flavors of the coffee. Another gripe is that the iced coffee is pricey and small at $6.50 for a 12oz cup. Joe and Dough just one floor above has a more generous portion. Though I didn&#39;t get to try it, Joe and the Juice also has sandwiches, juices, superfoods drinks that reminded me of New York. <br><br>I&#39;ll be back because of the comfy loungey space, with cushions for the long wooden bench lining one wall of the cafe, and padded seats throughout! Music is a little loud if you&#39;re planning to have a Serious Conversation but funky and I liked it.

text: I didn&#39;t think much of it when I stepped in here, namely because it was a random place on my trek around Singapore to grab something to drink, this time a juice as opposed to a coffee or a beer. However, the disappointing thing was that they didn&#39;t have any tea. However that didn&#39;t faze my brother namely because the place specialised in juices, which he loves, especially pineapple and apricot juice. I ended up grabbing a coffee, and I have to admit that it wasn&#39;t all that fantastic, but then again I have come to expect that from a lot of these chain stores.

text: Coffee Bean&#39;s are generally quite consistent in their service and food standard across the board, but what makes this outlet a little more unusual is that it&#39;s the only one in Singapore that serves up Kosher food, probably because there&#39;s a synagogue nearby. The menu remains the same though, so no worries about that.

text: One more hipster cafe to add to the list!<br><br>This place is newly opened and operated by the same folks at next door Rubato. It&#39;s al fresco and looks like a lovely place for meetings or to work from during the day. One drawback is it&#39;s in ulu Greenwood Ave... the Downtown MRT line can&#39;t open soon enough.<br><br>I had a flat white and it was fine. I tried my husband&#39;s hot chocolate and despite the pretty latte art, it was baaaaaad. It wasn&#39;t sweet, had this weird metallic aftertaste, and was chalky. <br><br>The extra star is for ambiance. They have have a dog friendly patio, which is pretty rare in Singers. The tables near the entrance have great natural lighting, and if you go towards the back they have those trendy-ass lightbulbs that are dim on purpose and makes the space look cosy and shit.<br><br>Bring your Kinfolk magazine that you&#39;re not really reading (after all, it&#39;s the one accessory that gets you those extra likes on Instagram) order the flat white, compile that paragraph of hashtags, and you&#39;d fit right in at Claude&#39;s!

Jia Cheng is a shop inside the Coffeeshop that sells Lor Mee and Fried Hokkien Mee. <br><br>And I&#39;m pretty convinced that&#39;s enough tho there are many stalls in Singapore that sell Lor Mei, 80% of them are more like a by product of the other noodle types they are selling. <br><br>I like their thick sauce that flavourful and coats the noodle nicely. I&#39;m not crazy about their ngoh hiang slices, they are &#34;ok lah&#34;. BUT!! I LOVE this deep fried bits of I-dunno-what that STAYS crunchy even having been in the sauce during your meal!!! Amazing!!!<br><br>I usually like my lor Mee with extra vinegar and extra spice! It really adds to the kick of the meal!!!<br><br>My favorite place for my Lor Mee fix in Toa Payoh!!!

text: Located at the second floor of the shopping centre was this open concept cafe. What attracted me to the cafe was the pretty display of sliced cakes and tarts on the shelf. Although it was pretty early in the morning, there was already customers enjoying breakfast in the cafe. While the dine in area was located in the open, the kitchen area was hidden near the lifts.<br><br>LOBSTER MAC &amp; CHEESE ($25.50)<br>WITH SHAVED FENNEL &amp; FRESH DILL, BAKED IN CAST IRON PAN<br>Although I wished for more cheese on top of the dish, it was pretty delicious and the sauce was evenly spreaded.<br>The pepper and salt container that served with the dish was in a quite unique 2-in-1 container.<br><br>MOCHACCINO ($5/ regular)<br>The drink was rich and thick. Quite a peak me up.<br><br>Pear Tart ($6.50)<br>The crust cut easily with a fork. The pear slices were soft and moist. It did not taste too sweet.<br><br>Overall the food was great. Service was great too. Staffs often came over to check on me. I was seated at the sofa seat which was quite comfortable.

text: Unresponsive staff, slow service, l had to ask for sugar, it did not come with the coffee. Had to ask for salt for the eggs as well. The coffee cups are tiny and only half full. Not recommended!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/znxzPL89kzJnUvla_x-SqQ/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/the-famous-ice-cream-rolls-shop-singapore?reviewid=WXXcmo683ziUu1i-fiDpjg&select=znxzPL89kzJnUvla_x-SqQ', 'altText': 'Photo of The Famous Ice-Cream Rolls Shop - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: These days the trends is fried ice-cream with lots of shops selling popping out. One of them is The Famous Ice-Cream Rolls Shop which is located at Thomson V. The outlet is small with a couple tables indoor and another couple of tables outdoor for dining in. Besides fried ice cream it also sells milkshakes, waffles, teas and cupcakes.<br><br>The fried ice cream is priced from $4.20 onwards. Add 80 cents for mixed of 2 flavours. Choices of flavour includes Nutella, Milo, Ovomaltine, Oreo, and . It is served with Hershey Chocolate sauce and rainbow rice. There is also Fruit Delights version ($4.90) which has flavours such as strawberry, lychee and mango. Top up 50 cents each for toppings such as wafer sticks, M&amp;M, and milo powder. <br><br>I order a Kinder Bueno version which costs $4.20. The flavour is not strong and could taste the kinder bueno in it. The ice cream melts rather fast too.

Everyone told us that kaya toast is a must try in Singapore. Ya Kun is the biggest chain and can be found all over. This location is a 3 minute walk from where we were staying and it was the perfect breakfast option for us.<br><br>The two of us shared a set menu F with peanut toast and Tea-C. I was amazed by how perfect the eggs are cooked and how flavorful it was with just a touch of soy sauce and white pepper.<br><br>When the toast came out, it looked deceptively boring. But one bite into it and I was hooked. How come toast in the US never taste this good? Anyway, for less than $5, get yourself some kaya toast.

text: Amidst the industrial estate in Tai Seng, you find a stretch of F&amp;B choices. Round 8, being a healthy option amongst the rest, stands out immediately!<br><br>Priding themselves in cold pressed juices, DIY foods, wraps, salads, and yogurt parfaits. They also provide delivery services for those working hard at their office desk job and want something healthy!<br><br>Their prices are reasonable too, the wraps/salads are priced around $6-8 and their cold pressed juices are $5.50 each or at $5 for a top up with a wrap/salad.<br><br>1. Thai Rib eye $9.90<br>So once you know what you want to get, you have to choose between tortilla wraps (original, spinach or tomato &amp; basil), then choose a protein, (beef, chicken, fish, turkey bacon, seafood or mushroom), then choose your condiments and lastly, choose a dressing from a wide variety of homemade sauces.<br><br>I picked, tomato &amp; basil, mushrooms, couscous, pasta salad, mango salsa along with the thai mayo which was recommended for my thai rib eye.<br><br>It was a delightful combination. I enjoyed every bite. Filled with tasty goodness! I highly recommend trying the thai rib eye! Although I might want to ask for a hard boiled eye rather than a egg wrap.<br><br>2. Yogurt Parfait $4.20<br>The staff highly recommended the nutella one and so I got it. It was filled with granola on the top, and then big round grapes in the center which took up most of the cup, and then a layer of thick nutella and the yogurt at the bottom. I personally feel that for $4.20, it&#39;s priced a bit steep, but it is a yummy dessert to go with your salad!<br><br>3. Absolute Beauty $5.50<br>The main ingredients were watermelon, grape &amp; lemon. Advertised to improve heart health, improve blood flow, anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, reduce asthmatic event and prevent migraines. That&#39;s one very promising bottle of juice. At least the from the content of the drink I can indeed tell that it is cold pressed, as the fibres are not separating themselves in the bottle.<br><br>The staff were very friendly and helpful in recommending items to be added into our lunches. All in all, I love this place and the concept! Eating healthy doesn&#39;t always have to be expensive!

text: In the midst of trendy restaurants and bakeries, Cafe O offers traditional plates of Nasi Lemak, pratha and byriani. A nice local alternative to the expat-heavy scene in the Village.

text: I love that you can always experience Starbucks in every country. This is a great location. Lots of seating with WiFi in a large mall. Everything inside still looks like new. It&#39;s very well maintained and clean. There is an upper area with some booth seating. The lower area has a large table, some smaller tables and a long bench area.<br><br>The employees provided excellent service. I was able to order and get my drink in a timely manner. They were courteous and professional.<br><br>It&#39;s a great location to get some coffee or a snack and get some work done. There is a welcoming atmosphere. You will need to reconnect to WiFi every 30 minutes but you can reconnect as many times as you want.<br><br>I&#39;ve always liked Starbucks and this location shows the true commitment to what the brand is trying to accomplish across the word.

text: Excellent staff and coffee. Â Located a short walk from the Regent Hotel. Â Free wifi here and excellent air circulation.<br><br>Looks brand new here. Â Should be a permanent fixture here as they offer pretty good quality coffee.

One of the few starbucks branches that still feels very neigbourhoodly (if such word exists lol). So far, it&#39;s one of the few branches where the staff are warm and all cheery at any time of the day. This branch is designed in such a way that you feel that you can just bring your favourite book and plop down here for hours and the staff never actually try to shoo you away. Although location wise is not the most accessible, i think it just adds more charm to this branch. <br><br>P.S. to the baristas here, good job! Keep up the good work!

text: Staying at the Orchard Hotel and wanted to get outdoors and away from the hotel crowd for a fast sit down lunch. photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/LW7Mz80YaFT5gInKdd-JEA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/rocky-master-singapore?reviewid=4emNbklhJvwvy9REvM9GXg&select=LW7Mz80YaFT5gInKdd-JEA', 'altText': 'Photo of Rocky Master - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}, {'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/cd83iwQWCgSyqhn9n4RgPA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/rocky-master-singapore?reviewid=4emNbklhJvwvy9REvM9GXg&select=cd83iwQWCgSyqhn9n4RgPA', 'altText': 'Photo of Rocky Master - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: I&#39;m not really sure where to begin. I started with three stars, but realized that may be too generous.<br><br>The people were very nice. So there&#39;s that.<br><br>We stopped in because of the huge signs on their window advertising with seemingly great pride the all-day breakfast. I was really jonesing for some pancakes &amp; eggs!<br><br>There are a few breakfast sets on the menu. The first is the Chinese breakfast. No thanks. The American breakfast is listed next. That&#39;s what my husband ordered. I went for the pancakes, but since they didn&#39;t come with eggs, I ordered them on the side.<br><br>I asked for my eggs to be scrambled because I figure those couldn&#39;t be screwed up. I was afraid if I tried for &#39;over medium,&#39; I might confuse the server &amp; end up with something that may not even resemble an egg.<br><br>Let&#39;s start with the American breakfast, shall we? It looked like nothing anyone in America would ever order. Scrambled eggs, ok. But the hash browns were those tiny rectangles that come frozen in long packages. There was a grilled whole tomato, which most Americans do not eat for breakfast. There was a pile of mushrooms. Yeah, we don&#39;t usually eat those either. (Tomatoes &amp; mushrooms in an omelet, yeah. But not solo.) Then there were some anemic looking hot dogs, which I imagine were supposed to be sausages? Oh. And a couple pieces of toast that must have been left in the toaster for roughly 15 seconds, if that.<br><br>My pancakes were three deep on the plate with real Canadian maple syrup. The pancakes were perfectly round, all the same size, and all had that same shade brown as the frozen ones you buy from the grocery store. And yes, that&#39;s exactly what they were. I ate my eggs &amp; about one and a half pancakes.<br><br>If you&#39;re a smoker, there&#39;s great outdoor seating. The seating inside is limited.<br><br>I don&#39;t see myself going back anytime soon.

text: A pleasant and quiet place to rest and think, away from the bustling streets of orchard road. (it&#39;s quite quiet given that today is a public holiday)<br><br>The staff are friendly and welcoming, but the desserts and coffee are average. The coffee is somewhat close to your usual Starbucks and lacks any special flavour/standard. No fancy latte art/beans to choose from and I couldn&#39;t taste any notes. The matcha latte was like any made using matcha powder-but thankfully decently thick and not too sweet. <br><br>The macarons were a tad too sweet which overpowered the flavours that their name suggests-couldn&#39;t taste any specific earl grey or gula melaka in both of them.<br><br>Overall, the peaceful setting and reasonable prices (no gst &amp; service charge) makes this place a comfortable place to relax and chill if you lower your standards for food and coffee/are nearby. Wouldn&#39;t come down specially to have their food though.

text: A good place to get away from the hustle and bustle of Orchard Road as not many people come to Delfi. The student/laptop crowd flocks to the three surrounding Starbucks, leaving this place untouched. Comfortable couches and nice view of Orchard Road. It&#39;s pretty low key and basic. Menu items include a mix of local delights (like laksa) and Western (pizzas and pastas). Prices average about $10.<br><br>Coffee is very average here. Perhaps, the food is better. I didn&#39;t try the food when I was there. There also aren&#39;t any power outlets so if you&#39;re planning to use your laptop, be sure to charge it up first. <br><br>Overall, quite a nice place to rest and relax after a mid-afternoon shopping pilgrimage.

text: I decided to have breakfast here when I stayed at the hotel. It was served at the seating area - it functions as a breakfast area from 6:30am to 10:30am, normal cafe from then to the evening - and the bar starts functioning from 6pm to 1am. So, it is quite a good deal actually. I tried the breakfast, which was pretty okay. There&#39;s a general spread - cereal, noodles, fruits, salad, meat and cheese platter, soups, omelet station, etc.<br><br>What I Love: It&#39;s got nice decor, and the omelet station was good. Food was nice. I had grilled vegetables and the omelet. The bacon was pretty yummy too (I kinda helped myself to quite a few servings of that). The coffee station was good - you could make your own - which I don&#39;t mind - as then, I can make it my own way. The vegetables were fresh - there were quite a few options and at least there were healthy options.<br><br>What I Don&#39;t Love: The noodles looked like they were dipped and coated in oil. Ewwww. I shrugged it off. The Cafe is also pretty tiny. When you have quite a full hotel - you gotta have enough seats. So, I took my breakfast to the poolside to get privacy. There could be more options.

text: Located around the suntec city fountain is this Beanstro, we actually had to contemplate between eating at the Marina Square one or this one. But we heard that this was the bigger and quieter outlet and it was! There were tons of ceiling fans and air conditioning which made me whip out my sweater!<br><br>With so many tea-time, cake options it was hard to settle with what cake and what drink to have!<br>They also have all day breakfast! Which comes with free flow bread and soup and a cup of tea/coffee, we topped up $3.70 to get a hazelnut latte.<br><br>1. Chocolate of a Thousand Leaves $6.50<br>When this cake arrived, it looked dry and it indeed was dry, but the chocolate wasn&#39;t too bad, it was sweet and little gerlat, but with 4 people, we each managed to slowly share the cake. There is also a small portion of hazelnut bit on the bottom outside corner of the cake.<br><br>2. The Ultimate $12.50<br>Being that The Coffee Bean is halal, everything here is either chicken or turkey. I do like turkey bacon, contrary to most people. The chicken patty was tasty, flavourful and not oily. The 3 slices of &#34;bread&#34; which was more like khong guan biscuits, was crisp and went well with the butter and jam. All in all an okay breakfast set. I think it&#39;s pretty worth the money since it comes with a drink and a bread/soup set.<br><br>3. Hazelnut Latte<br>I Â was quite stunned when I saw how big this cup was. Probably 16oz? Nonetheless, it was midly warm, just the right temperature to drink this. It was sweet enough at the begining, but as I drank towards the bottom, I had to walk up to a counter to add more hot water. <br><br>The bread was okay, I did like eating it with jam and butter, but the soup was too diluted. For any mains, it comes with soup and bread.<br><br>Using the QOO10 vouchers, I think it was quite value for money, plus there&#39;s no service charge and tax, unlike some hipster cafes!! Their cheesecakes look so good! Hope to try them soon!

text: This appears to be Singapore&#39;s answer to Starbucks, not that they don&#39;t have Starbucks here, but then again there are very few places I&#39;ve been to (with the exception of Adelaide) that doesn&#39;t have a Starbucks. Anyway I stopped in here for a coffee, namely because I wanted to see what the coffee was like, and also because I have a habit of drinking more coffee than tea when I am away. Mind you, I wouldn&#39;t expect anything hugely fantastic, but it certainly does the job. The inside does feel a lot better than your average Starbucks though, and I would probably be more inclined to come here than the other.

text: Eat Until &#34;Blur&#34;<br><br>Oh, the humble hamburger. How it&#39;s evolved from a meat patty, melted cheese between a toasted sesame bun to a level that&#39;s..... gourmet worthy. <br><br>We love a good burger bar and was gutted when discovering that Mojo Burps, one of if not our favorite burger joint, had closed. <br><br>Since than, we&#39;ve given a few other places a shot without much satisfaction, UNTIL NOW!<br><br>We decided to do a takeaway because we&#39;ve seen just how saucy their burgers can get and decided we should do a takeaway to avoid messing ourselves in public. <br><br>The Wife had the Prime Beef Burger with Foie Gras while I went with a more Non-traditional, smoked salmon burger. <br><br>Prime Beef with Foie Gras ($24.95)<br>OMG. <br>First the basics. The bun was nicely toasted and thanks to the Foie Gras, the top bun was flavored with the Foie Gras oil, which soaked in every bit of flavour it had to offer. <br>The patty was a spot on. An inch thick patty, well seasoned and perfectly cooked (we had ours medium rare). The patty had a great fat to meat ratio, ensuring that it didn&#39;t taste dry or chewy. Consistency of the mince was good as well, avoiding any portion of clumpy meat or overly mushed mince. The results? An extremely juicy patty that constantly dropped juices down the side of our mouths. <br>The Foie Gras was pretty generous, with 2 thick slices, which added richness to the burger. Though not the highest quality of Foie Gras, they were still pretty good. <br>The cheese was perfectly melted while the relish used added a nice sour kick to the burger, helping to cut the richness of the burger. <br><br>Smoke Salmon Burger ($12.50)<br>I was expecting maybe 6 slices of salmon, max, with tons of avocado. <br>Turns out, it was the complete opposite!<br>The smoked salmon was folded into a one inch thick patty while the avocado was a thin layer between salmon and bun. It was a smoke salmon lovers delight! Only thing I wished was for more avocado and more sauce and you could barely taste it over the salmon. It did need that bit of sourness to help cut the powerful taste of the salmon. Also, it did feel a little strange either smoked salmon between a burger bun, might have been Â more &#34;traditional&#34; between a bagel but hey, It still tasted good but I have zero complains with the generosity. <br><br>Every order also comes as a set, which comes with a drink, salad and awesome wedges with cheese sauce. <br><br>Hands down for now, this is my favourite burger joint. It may not be the most price friendly restaurant but it&#39;s definitely worth it.

text: Best truffle mayo I&#39;ve ever had. Burger was juicy and delicious. Highly recommend the entire meal. Got the bacon burger with fries, salad, and zucchini lemon refresher. The zucchini lemon drink was to die for. Don&#39;t expect a real salad, when they say greens. They mean a couple pieces of romaine with some balsamic dressing; but honestly anything else would&#39;ve been overkill. Ate 4 hours ago and still remarkably full. Asked for my burger medium and I would say it came more medium rare, but was still delicious :)

text: This burger joint is a solid 3.<br><br>Came here for an early lunch and it was already beginning to get busy as we rolled in.<br><br>The burger was cooked to medium rare and was quite juicy, and it was a good overall bun-to-pattie ratio, which made for a good experience. I had the prime beef with streaky bacon, which looked to be the best burg on the menu, but unfortunately they snuck some sort of truffle flavour in there (can we stop with that nonsense already???) and there wasn&#39;t a good burger sauce to give it a better taste (anything would have helped - BBQ, Tomato, Mustard).<br><br>So whilst they have the cooking down, they need to work on the construction of the burger somewhat.<br><br>The handful of wedges was a bit meagre and the wait for the food was on the extreme-side. However as there is only 2 guys, that&#39;s probably part of the experience, and with it being Singapore, service is never on the awesome-side.

text: Came here with two church mates as one of them wanted to try out burgers for dinner around 7.00 pm on a Saturday. Located walkable distance from Tanjong Pagar MRT and next to famous ramen chains. <br><br>After exploring the menu, I decided to order Prime Beef with Streaky Bacon. Yes, I am a fan of bacons. And Gruyere cheese sounds unfamiliar. For the beverage, I asked one of the staffs whether the ice lemon tea was homemade and when she answered it was, I ordered that.<br><br>Price wise here was a bit steep. For the meal, you can either get the wedges for the price listed on the menu or add-on for other side dishes. I decided to try truffle fries with the burger.<br><br>For the home made ice lemon tea, it is highly recommended. But unfortunately they placed too much ice cubes inside the glass that lost its taste after 20 or so minutes. Could probably ask them for less ice. <br><br>For the truffle fries, it was good if consumed before 10 minutes. Unfortunately I left them out in the air for long and they turned soggy even though the truffle fries were of thin cuts. <br><br>For the beef patty, I ordered it medium rare as that is what I normally choose for burgers. Sadly it was not as juicy as other Yelpers had mentioned. The bacon was chewy to my liking and the buns were nicely baked. <br><br>Store wise, it is not so spacious and could only contain maximum 15 customers. So to avoid the crowds, you might need to come earlier. Portion was reasonable and it did satisfy my hunger.

text: I&#39;ve been introduced to this place a couple and came a couple of times already because I&#39;m drawn to their pulled pork burger. They have nice dessert, but the basic burger is already food for my soul! <br><br>I&#39;ve tried a couple of places around this area, but this place still wins hands down. Sure you have to wait a bit, the guys are really trying their best (and they&#39;re not slow, mind you) to serve. Friendly staff, and patient (even though my colleague and I took so long to decide on our drink choice).<br><br>Hope people would give service staff a break with their negativity because a smile to them makes their day too!

text: I&#39;ve always walked past this place but have never gone in as the place looked small and cramped. This time, my hungry friends had traipsed down the entire Tanjong Pagar Road on a Friday, and with every establishment full (I kid you not), we ended up here as this was the only place with seats, which isn&#39;t always a good sign. <br><br>We were however pleasantly surprised at the burgers! The beef patties were suitably thick and juicy! Flavorful!! The burgers/patties aren&#39;t large, so if you are looking for something substantial, these aren&#39;t. nonetheless, these burgers were still satisfying! The portobello one seemed nice (my friend&#39;s order) and I would go back to try this one. The truffle fries were good too, although I found the smell to be a little overpowering. Haha! <br><br>One side note, the salad was a little oily, which was strange. <br><br>We sat outside, so thankfully it didn&#39;t feel cramped. <br><br>Will go back!!

text: Searched out the menu and was very tempting. Came down and arrived at an almost empty shop ( the ramen stalls round the corner were flooding with people ). One guy came to show us a table, was chill when we wanted another. Was hard to understand his accent when we asked the bestseller. But the taste of the burgers swept us away. <br><br>Ordered a steak burger and a puller pork burger. Steak burger had superb truffle infused mayonnaise and steak patty (well done) was moist and didn&#39;t have the raw taste. Pulled pork reminded me of kong bah (black sauce braised pork). The tenderness draws me in for a bite after another. The lettuce inside was boiled, goes well with the pork instead of conventional salad kinda raw lettuce.<br><br>Love the crispy potato wedges. <br><br>Overall it was a very satisfying meal!(:

text: Two Blur Guys definitely has the best burger I&#39;ve tried so far in Singapore. Â Back in NYC, this burger would fit right in.<br><br>It&#39;s a small, cozy burger shop, with limited seating and a warm and welcoming staff. Â There is one primary waitress and one burger chef. Â We noticed that our burgers were made with extreme care, and after we ate, the burger chef was very focused on making sure we enjoyed our burgers. Â The burgers come with a small scoop of potato salad and a side salad of greens with a delicious balsamic glaze.<br><br>We wrapped up the meal with the apple pie, and it was tasty, but I can&#39;t help wishing it was served hot with a scoop of apple pie on the side :)<br><br>PARTING THOUGHT: We&#39;ll continue on our Singapore burger quest, but so far, we&#39;re quite happy to have found a winner!

text: The best burger in Singapore... where is the six star rating? When I asked for a medium rare burger, I finally got what I had never gotten in this city-state, a medium rare burger. The finishing was perfect, from the bread to the meat to the greens served with it. The fries were amazing too, and the mayo with the fries and the burger was to die for. I&#39;m not one to like mayo very much, but this one, this one is something different. Had a pecan pie for dessert which is quite nice, and the beer selection is quite affordable and varied. I honestly wish I could write more, but I don&#39;t want to waste any of your time while you read this review instead of going and having the best burger here. You&#39;ll thank me for it!

text: The burgers here are very good - the beef patties are thick and juicy and the bun is also very good. I had my burger medium well and it came out perfectly cooked, while my wife&#39;s was medium and slightly more pink in the middle. Love it when a restaurant knows how to cook their meats.<br><br>The venue is very small and non-descript. I&#39;ve walked past this place MANY times without as much noticing it. It looks like a bakery from the outside b/c they display their pies and desserts prominently. There&#39;s not much seating so get there during an off hour or do take away. They really need to put a BIG picture of their juicy hamburger on the storefront to attract more folks.<br><br>We also shared the lemon curd tart which was awesome, worth trying.<br><br>I only give them 4 stars b/c they do not serve fries and their version of ketchup is a translucent gelatinous pink sweet goo that I couldn&#39;t get into. Next time I&#39;ll bring fries and ketchup from McDonald&#39;s to complement their satisfying burger!

text: For someone who generally stays away from burgers, I really dig the ones here. <br><br>I ordered the Prime Beef Burger which came with a side of leafy greens and a tiny mountain of potato salad. The beef patty was thick, juicy and well-seasoned. Definitely not fast food material. <br><br>I saw the cook meticulously grill the beef patty as she toasted the buns, take out the buns and slap on the patty and a slice of gruyÃ¨re, stick the whole thing back into the oven and finally, keep a watchful eye for the buns to turn a nice golden brown and the cheese to melt just right.<br><br>The burger here is surely a product of love, love that goes all the way down to my tummy tum tums.

With just four tables in a tiny space, Two Blur Guys isn&#39;t trying very hard perhaps in this newly competitive Duxton/Tanjong Pagar area (Soooo many good things to eat around here), but maybe it doesn&#39;t have to. <br><br>I come to Duxton a lot and frequently walk over to the Orchid Hotel to eat at Teppei or Tonkotsu King. So I was pleasantly surprised to see this tiny space along the Tanjong Pagar stretch.<br><br>I wish they did more marketing, or maybe it&#39;s good that they didn&#39;t, because when I started to hear friends excitedly discuss the burgers and desserts here I was intrigued enough to go check it out. There&#39;s a small selection of interesting (mostly Aussie) beers and wines, and the cakes and tarts like the Lamington are good.<br><br>Alas I have been too full from ramen usually to ever eat a full meal here, but I&#39;m going to check out the burgers next time especially now that I&#39;ve found out that Singapore&#39;s elusive food extraordinaire Jimmy Chok is involved here in some way or other.

text: If they actually bother to serve you, the burgers are amazingly good. Â I&#39;ve sampled a fair number of burgers in my time, and these ranked in the top tier. Â The potatoes as side dish are OK but nothing special. Â French fries would be nice.<br><br>I went here twice. Â The first time my companion and I received immediate and attentive service. 2 Blur Guys is a relatively new burger shop set up in Orchid Hotel. Its concept is simple - a stripped down quick meal place which serves quality food at reasonable prices. The menu is simple - there&#39;s a list of less than 10 burgers to choose from, and each burger comes with a side of potato salad and greens. Portions aren&#39;t massive, but they&#39;re pretty filling. 2 Blur Guys also serves desserts such as brownies and ice cream. The restaurant is nothing fancy, but it serves as a functional place to grab dinner at with friends.

text: If I could sum up my experience at this CBTL in few words, it would be that some coffeehouses are more equal than others. Even though TCBTL have outlets all over Singapore, and I have been to many, this has got to be my favourite. Owing to its location (and I say this from a selfish consumer POV)- I especially like this place because it is hardly ever bustling, except maybe on a weekend afternoon. If you prefer to spend an afternoon people watching- then you are better off at the Holland Village outlet.<br> <br>Even the food seems better at this outlet. Placebo or not, I like to think I get more salmon slices in my salad, more cherries in my blackforest (yum!) and it never hurts to always have cute baristas in sight. Even though I sometimes find the furniture a little too closely spaced, it is usually never so crowded that you will have to sit directly beside someone/be privy to someone&#39;s gossip session. For those who are looking to do some work/reading, be mindful that the lighting within the restaurant is not that good (don&#39;t bother unless you are working on a laptop), but there is an outdoor space that receives plenty of sunlight though it might get quite warm in the middle of the day. Also, they never seem to be understaffed! Fast service, gentle comfort, whats there not to like?

text: After a heavy feast at Newton Circus Hawker Centre and whilst heading home, my friend was craving for ice cream so we decided to stop by braddell. Sadly though at 930pm, 30 mins till closing, they ran out of waffles.<br><br>We tasted a few of their ice creams before deciding in earl grey lavender and banana nut milk. At $5.80 for 2 scoops, I felt it was reasonable. The scoops were big.<br><br>The earl grey lavender was subtly sweet and when I closed my eyes, I imagined I was eating a cup of tea ice cream! It was superb and when I wanted to take home a pint of it, they were out of it. So I ended up taking home a pint of thai milk tea, which is also delicious!<br><br>The banana nut milk had real banana fruit and nuts in there. It was nice to bite into abit of fruit and nut, whilst savouring the milky and creamy ice cream.<br><br>You can help yourself to iced water. The shop itself is always crowded, as there is a neighbourhood playground right in front of the shop. You can always get your ice cream in a cup or cone, and sit on the park benches out side.<br><br>I will definitely be back to try their waffles at some point, but for now.. I will make my own waffles at home and enjoy it with my pint of thai milk tea ice cream :)

text: I&#39;ve heard lots of scary stories about the crowdedness of this little ice cream-waffles shop. Took a gamble and popped by on a Sunday evening to check what the commotion is l about. Yes, packed with people but we managed to get a table of four easily without waiting, thankfully. Premium ice creams cost $0.90 more per than the usual scoop of $3.30. Rather redundant, since 80% of the choices were premium flavours and might as well sell them at the premium price.<br><br>Waffles with Thai Milk &amp; Earl Grey Lavender ice cream $11.80. <br>Waffles were good--crispy, eggy and sweet. The ice creams that I&#39;ve tried, Black Sesame, Rich Dark Choc with Ferrero, Cookies and Cream, including those ordered (Thai Milk, Earl Grey Lavender, Peanut Butter Jelly) were silky, luscious and dense. <br><br>Peanut Butter Jelly $4.20 <br>What distorted the happy ice cream moments was not the food, not the agony of waiting, but the grim lackluster service. Not referring to every staff but the two frontline ice cream servers cum...erm &#34;taste-testers&#34; who were quite dutifully taste-testing the flavours yet Â displayed an air of cold nonchalance towards customers. At least, put on a smile, yeah?
Great ice cream! Good service, love coming here with the family. We really like the earl grey ice cream with some nice crispy waffles!

I know people talk about the waffles here but I was just too full from lunch and had to &#34;settle&#34; for the sea salt gula melaka. A very yummy scoop, I think it was about 3 bucks and not a premium flavour.<br><br>My friend had the strawberry sorbet - refreshing but not unusual. Good texture, no clunky ice crystals here; and the cookies and cream. I didn&#39;t try the latter but she declared it very good and cookies and cream is one of her favourites so I think she has tried a lot of it. lol either that or it&#39;s ALWAYS good (know what I mean?)<br><br>Tiny tables and not much space. It&#39;s a bit too neighbourhoody..ie some grumpy auntie and uncle waiting around for table. <br><br>Coffee took too long to come but it was better than I expected, a decent latte at $4.50. No skinny milk here so go fat or go home. <br><br>Music is a bit old but the art work around is interesting. The nice thing is it&#39;s very near where I am on Sat mornings but don&#39;t come here unless you&#39;re just 1 or 2. Even then a lot of people standing squashed in waiting for a table doesn&#39;t give you that chill vibe..guess you have to look to the ice cream for that. Having said that, we considerately got our 2 lattes &#34;to go&#34; and sat outside on a bench drinking them. Not popular seats as noone bothered us so at least we had a relaxing chat in the shade.<br><br>I might have to update once I finally get to try those talked-about waffles ;)

text: sigh.....why did alexis c. have to FTR this place?<br><br>sigh.....why did cheryl n. have to re-emphasize and validate their existence?<br><br>sigh.....why did i end up at hup chong hakka yong dou foo innocently thinking i wanted to eat healthy?<br><br>sigh.....why did i use yelp to search for everything nearby and found you?<br><br>sigh.....why did i go buy baos from teochew homemade pau and ended up within steps of you?<br><br>sigh.....why did i then use the monocle to good effect, though it could potentially make an untrained user sea sick, and discovered you were just around the corner?<br><br>sigh.....why did you open exactly at the time i chanced upon your door step?<br><br>sigh.....why did you have a sweet enticing photo of an ice cream waffle sitting there seductively as i enter?<br><br>sigh.....why are all your staff so lovely and full of life?<br><br>sigh.....why are you also an art gallery where one can purchase limited edition art pieces?<br><br>sigh.....why is your piped music, music to my ears?<br><br>sigh.....why is the environment so relaxing that you just want to chill here a little longer even though my car park coupon has expired?<br><br>sigh.....why don&#39;t you have free wifi?????<br><br>sigh.....why don&#39;t you just install free wifi for me and get that elusive fifth star?

text: High standard of waffles and ice cream! Had the salted gula melaka flavored ice cream but it felt a bit strong to go with waffles as I prefer vanilla for a cleaner taste. Skipped coffee as it was too late at night so can&#39;t review on the standard of their coffee.<br><br>The crowd was crazy! And the cafe is a tiny one with around 10 tables cramped together. The tables beside you can definitely hear your conversations and vice versa. So this is not a cafe where you chill out and chat with your friends. For those who can&#39;t get a seat, you can try to see of the playground seats outside the cafe are available. More spacious for sure. <br><br>4 stars for the waffles and ice cream but it&#39;s a nightmare for people who are claustrophobic!

text: Is it just me, or has there been a sudden explosion of independent ice-creameries here in little Singapore? As an ice cream lover, I&#39;ve honestly not understood all the hype. Give me a tub of Haagen Dazs any day I&#39;d always say after being disappointed with our latest adventure of the beaten path. Not this time!<br><br>We discovered Creamier&#39;s sinful creations one night when we had dessert at a new food bar on Ann Siang Hill called Lola which serves Creamier instead of the usual fare. The quality was so surprising, we&#39;ve been dying for a chance to check this place out.<br><br>Tucked away in a sleepy corner of the Toa Payoh housing estate, Creamier stands out amidst its slightly dated surroundings. The humble decor and staff are a welcome respite from the recent proliferation of money no object outlets which have burst onto the Singapore scene of late, each trying to outdo the other with bigger budgets and gimmicks. You&#39;ll find none of that here. Just honestly good ice cream and reasonable UnSingaporean prices.<br><br>We ordered a waffle with ice cream, but the price was only $7.50 and this being Singapore, I was concerned that we&#39;d only be getting a tiny portion so I asked for an extra scoop of ice cream to go along with it. Little did I know that the waffle already came with two HUGE scoops and that the extra scoop would too much. Gotta love a place that feeds you well.<br><br>Super sized portions are usually the domain of cheap eateries which attempt to make up for the lack of quality with more &#39;value&#39;. But at Creamier, you&#39;ll find probably the BEST fresh ice cream in town, with some honestly good flavors. We tried the Richest Dark Chocolate Ferrero, Peanut Butter and Sea Salt Gula Melaka (local caramel-like palm sugar) and all exceeded our expectations. Everyone needs to try this place quick before it isn&#39;t a secret any more...

Creamier has a limited seating place,so big groups do take note. the waffles are freshly baked upon order. It has a good height to it but not the best nor the worst.<br><br>Service is quick and efficient. They have an iced water dispenser in the shop too.<br><br>I would recommend a milk/cream based ice cream and a sorbet for sharing. A good mix

text: I think it was a few weeks ago when everyone crazy shared about Creamier on FB! I was excited to see what kind of cafe it is set in a hdb neighbourhood. The place is cozy and clean, packed with people at around 4+. I sat outdoor sharing a table w a young couple &amp; kid. It&#39;s a pretty quiet neighbourhood. <br><br>I had the white and purple icecreams with waffle (earl grey &amp; berry something, can&#39;t rmb the full names). With cappuccino. Waffles were warm and crispy, taste really good with a 1 cream and 1 fruity icecream combination! Icecream melted pretty fast though.. :/<br><br>Funny thing was how easily the fork might just fell through the gaps on the wooden tables, making the experience slightly awkward, as I had to always make sure i rest it properly on a plank and not on a gap.

text: Pop by after dinner on a weekday and a queue has already form outside the shop. This ought to be good by local standard. <br>Many flavors of ice cream to choose but not seeing it made in person made doubt if they are imports. Proceeded for a sample of the flavor. At this time, I notice my sample was much less than the person ahead. I wasn&#39;t appreciative of this inconsistency. <br>I ordered the waffle with 2 scoops of ice creams. Â Wafer was nice, thick yet crispy on the outside. Ice creams were good, not that sweet which I preferred. The ice cream on the hot waffle will melt before your very eyes and I have to hurry up. Overall good dessert, place is very tight, but everywhere else too. Not a comfortable place to laze and chat. As we walk out, the queue was even longer than I started. So, can&#39;t be wrong here.

I was very surprised and happy to find this place by my office. Â The ice cream is served in a small scoop (by US standards) but it&#39;s very rich and dense. Â I tried the pistachio, which was very good. Â The flavor could have been a little deeper, but overall, it was solid. Â Will look forward to trying other flavors soon as well as the waffle!

text: Tucked in the depths of the Toa Payoh HDB is this little gem. Â I had a scoop of the sea salt gula melaka and fell in love immediately - kind of like salted caramel but the great thing about it is that it is not too too sweet, can be rare in Singapore. Â Nice home-made taste and I saw various people having waffles, next time when I have more space in my stomach. Â There were other interesting flavors like the earl grey lavender Â so if you want ice cream with a bit more thought in it, this place is for you. Â The small eatery seems to double as a small showroom of art pieces hung around the walls, I was staring at one while downing my scoop of gula melaka.

Super crowded (as usual). We went at 3pm and managed to find a sweet spot! <br><br>Love the vibe of the place! A hipster joint right smack in the middle of the good ole&#39; heartland :) <br><br>We had the hoky pokey ice-cream (vanilla and honey comb) with waffles and a mocha (strong). <br><br>Price-wise, it&#39;s definitely on par with other cafes at more prominent locations. I&#39;ve notice the trend of new cafe/creameries moving to the heartlands because of the lower rent. YAY for convenience but sadly I don&#39;t see any decline in prices despite this.

text: I was recommended to this place by a friend. We got lost on our first visit, cause we didn&#39;t really have much time as &#39;nature called.&#39; But anyway, just a tip, if you&#39;re driving, turn into the parking lot of block 128 and immediately turn right after wards. Just follow the road and the shop is just tucked away at the corner.<br><br>I have tried many ice cream shops all over the world and I have to say that Creamier is up there on my list. You can just feel that the ice cream was very finely made. It was very smooth and, true to its name, very creamy. I think it is slightly too sweet but it was not overwhelming. The flavors were also quite creative. I had the salted gula Melaka and earl grey lavender. Both were just absolutely wonderful.<br><br>I had the ice cream with waffle and it was well made too. It was too crispy for me tbh, but I can understand that most people will like it. I&#39;m just one of those oddballs who prefer his waffles without any crispiness to it. If you&#39;re like me, let the ice cream sog down the waffles first, let it absorb those delicious goodies before devouring it.<br><br>I can&#39;t wait to go back to Singapore and try the other flavors from Creamier.

I think the other ratings are not five stars because it seems that Singaporeans, and I am probably overgeneralizing, tend to give yelp ratings almost a star below what Americans would, unless it is Japanese or Italian food, not because this isn&#39;t a great place with affordable, high quality food and nice staff who seem to pay attention to details. If this was in Seattle, the mean would be 4.7. I am also glad they don&#39;t have wifi, as the internet tends to distract from enjoying ice cream.<br><br>I had waffles with the tahitian vanilla and sea salt (gula melaka) ice creams and a long black coffee. The ice cream is excellent, as in I wanted to close my eyes and savor it melting in my mouth, over and over. It tastes like they use high quality ingredients. The plating was solid. The location is also charming for its embeddedness in real life and lack of pretension, overlooking a playground in a block of HDBs.<br><br>The only blip was that instead of a beeper or plastic sign with a number, they hand out paper coffee cups with a number on the side so they know where to bring each order, which I think is clever but kind of odd, because if the writing at the bottom inside the cup explaining what it was had been a little more faded, I might have filled it with water and drank from it, and it wasn&#39;t particularly clean.

text: sigh.....why did alexis c. have to FTR this place?<br><br>sigh.....why did cheryl n. have to re-emphasize and validate their existence?<br><br>sigh.....why did i end up at hup chong hakka yong dou foo innocently thinking i wanted to eat healthy?<br><br>sigh.....why did i use yelp to search for everything nearby and found you?<br><br>sigh.....why did i go buy baos from teochew homemade pau and ended up within steps of you?<br><br>sigh.....why did i then use the monocle to good effect, though it could potentially make an untrained user sea sick, and discovered you were just around the corner?<br><br>sigh.....why did you open exactly at the time i chanced upon your door step?<br><br>sigh.....why did you have a sweet enticing photo of an ice cream waffle sitting there seductively as i enter?<br><br>sigh.....why are all your staff so lovely and full of life?<br><br>sigh.....why are you also an art gallery where one can purchase limited edition art pieces?<br><br>sigh.....why is your piped music, music to my ears?<br><br>sigh.....why is the environment so relaxing that you just want to chill here a little longer even though my car park coupon has expired?<br><br>sigh.....why don&#39;t you have free wifi?????<br><br>sigh.....why don&#39;t you just install free wifi for me and get that elusive fifth star?

Creamier goes up there in my ice cream list in Singapore, among the likes of Salted Caramel, Ice cream Gallery, Alfero. Artisan ice cream rocks especially if it&#39;s at such affordable prices. A single scoop is only $2.90 for the standard and $4.90 for the premium. Each scoop is an intense burst of flavor and the servers are extremely generous with their ice cream. Suck that Udders, you and your stupid weighing machine. :P<br><br>I was rejoicing at the gazillion black specks of the Tahitian Vanilla. Espresso is a must order for caffeine addicts like me. Earl Grey Lavender was a tad too sweet for my liking, could not taste much of the tea. Avocado was really smooth and creamy. Chocolate peppermint is like a liquid version of After Eights. Heavenly. No you don&#39;t want to know how much ice cream i ate in 1 seating. <br><br>The lava cake uses really dark chocolate, to the point it tastes almost alcoholic. It&#39;s not that flowy but it&#39;s not a bad snack. Pair it with a sweeter ice cream. <br><br>Oh extra ice cream cups cost 50cents. Now that&#39;s a funny story.. <br><br>Love the ambiance of the sleepy mature estate. Glad that this is breathing some life into the place.
