text: Creamier joins the artisan ice cream scene but with one difference - it chose to locate at Toa Payoh amidst barber shops and laundromats. I really like the fact that it chose an old HDB estate to set up shop because it breathes life into the area.<br><br>The cafe and ice cream parlor is also very nicely decorated, having design background owners. It&#39;s cosy and filled with small tables and chairs. The smell of fresh ice cream and coffee is also alluring.<br><br>The flavors of ice creams are really wide-ranging as well. They have exotic ones all the way to the usual, but I urge you to go try them yourself! Of course the ice cream quality is also very good. in fact it ranks up there with Salted Caramel, and wins it when it comes to experimentation.

The Good Good Eating House coffee stall is fantastic. It has the quality of the best modern coffee and toast places, at lower prices, in a fairly typical local coffeeshop environment. On off peak hours, the coffeeshop is completely relaxing and one can lounge under the coffeeshop&#39;s umbrella tables well-situated under trees while sipping kopi and reading the paper. It&#39;s a great place to chill with friends in the neighbourhood.<br><br>The coffee is great. Thick, aromatic, everything you&#39;d expect of traditional coffee. The Kopi Ping is done in the style of Ya Kun, ie whizzed in a blender to create frothiness. The eggs and toast are also very comparable to Ya Kun&#39;s stuff. In particular, I would recommend the Iced Lemon Tea. It&#39;s great on the hot day and they don&#39;t skimp on the lemon. The tea is also not too thin and watered down, like the kind you unfortunately get at many coffeeshops.<br><br>Service wise, the staff are also very efficient, if rather business like and hurried. Overall, I would really recommend this place for your regular breakfast/tea/kopi needs if you live in the vicinity.

It&#39;s one of those very few places that are open on weekends and in those in between hours after lunch hour and before dinner time. <br>Excellent food and serve excellent wine. Extremely affordable wines. Food portions are great and well prepared.

I stop by this Starbucks a lot on my way to and from the gym. I&#39;m not there to buy drinks - just grab our coffee beans for our machine at home. They always offer to grind them, but we don&#39;t need that service. It&#39;s very handy for those that do, though. <br><br>Service is never extremely quick and they seem under-staffed when I stop in. The place is clean and there&#39;s quite a bit of patio seating. If you&#39;re looking for Air Con, this is not the stop for you, as it is located outside.

Unfortunately, not the best Starbucks along the Orchard Road stretch. It&#39;s so bad, I had to leave a review. <br><br>This Starbucks is located right outside the Cineleisure movie theater. Although open 24 hours, it&#39;s perpetually crowded with people and has a crammed interior, and there&#39;s no AC. It&#39;s practically a greenhouse on a hot afternoon.<br><br>One unfortunate evening, I found myself sandwiched between a group of gossipy ladies guffawing and screeching hysterically about the Fifty Shades movie, and a couple of visitors to Singapore that were lost and sitting about arguing about the next place to go.<br><br>One side of the cafe faces the road, where you experience the Doppler Effect as vehicles zoom past. The other side faces the entrance of the movie theater building, where people hang out and light up after their movie. The second hand smoke creates a perpetual haze. <br><br>They&#39;ve also gotten my order wrong twice. (nuff said)<br><br>One additional star for it being open 24 hours, if you need your caffeine fix in the wee hours of the night. Otherwise, do yourself a favor and head over to the Starbucks at Cuppage Road or Plaza Singapura mall.

Tucked away in the greenery of the Istana park, this place is like a little quiet haven unmarred by the rest of the bustling city. A cup of coffe together with the sound of the water and fountain around the cafe does wonders for the spirit.<br><br>I&#39;ve never really tried the food here, just had some finger food on one occasion. The desserts left a good impression.<br><br>The best part is exploring the cafe and checking out the art piece on display. Do go up to the second level which has a nice decor and gives a higher view of the surrounding landscape.

text: Art Palattes is a cafÃ© located within a two-storey art studio, which itself is inside the (admittedly small) er... semi-lush greenery of Istana Park. The whole atmosphere is very welcoming and unpretentious. The cafÃ© itself is surrounded by water and is very pleasant indeed. <br><br>I&#39;ve been here twice - once to see a live band performance on a weekend night - the place was teeming with people then, and I loved walking around looking at the art pieces on display. The second time was a weekday afternoon, to check out the cafÃ© (it&#39;s open-air, surrounded by water but shaded), and I was surprised to find it with quite a few customers - mostly foreigners that seemed to be regulars. <br><br>Best of all though - this place is quiet. <br><br>I got a freshly brewed iced-tea for $6.90 and relaxed in my seat, really appreciating the understated loveliness of this place. Despite it being in Orchard Road, this really feels like an out-of-the-way little pocket in nature and is definitely a little treasure I&#39;m going to return to on lazy weekday afternoons to pass away the time.

text: It was 12pm and 33 degrees Celsius outdoors when I found myself on a 2km hike with this inaccessible little cafe marked as the destination. Upon arriving with a sweat-soaked shirt and skin a shade darker, I asked myself: was it worth it? <br><br>This cafe offers the standard fare: eggs Benedict, smoked salmon Benedict, sandwiches, pasta and the usual range of desserts. I ordered the crab pasta which was the most interesting choice on the menu, along with an additional serving of smoked salmon. It was pretty alright, though the crab was a little sparse and the sauce too garlicky for my liking. Next up was the beef baguette! Not bad at all, but with an extremely forgettable taste. <br><br>To compensate for the strenuous walk, we ended with a chocolate lava cake and apple crumble! The latter had a superb crumbly top layer, which easily melts in your mouth! The apple filling was mild and not overly sweet, just the way I like it. <br><br>All in all, to answer the question posed earlier: no, it was not worth the long and arduous journey from the mrt station. Sure, the food was good and the experience was certainly enjoyable, but I&#39;m sure other cafes located within the heartlands can match up and even surpass the food found here.

text: Typical western food meaning Halibut and grilled salmon that tasted ok gets served in this climatized neutral restaurant. We waited really long for our drinks, even after asking 2 times. The food is pretty expensive, but the veggie noodles were pretty good. No recommendation considering the Thai foodstall across the street has much better food and atmosphere. We didn&#39;t pick the place and we probably will not go there again for our lunch break.

text: I only gave 1 star because there is no way to vote NO star. <br><br>Visited the restaurant for dinner, Â it was empty. The staff just hung around, not even greeting us. <br><br>When I asked for the waiter who was standing across the restaurant to come over, Â he shouted, &#34;just fill in the order form&#34;. <br><br>The menu items were very ordinary, but prices seemed high for a diner located in an Industrial Estate. <br><br>After staring at the drab, depressing looking Grey walls for 5 minutes and being unimpressed by the rather pedestrian menu, we decided to leave. <br><br>Was charged $1.50 for the 15 mins of parking...

Cafes are popping up all over Singapore faster than sexually transmitted lesions on the patrons of Orchard Towers. That&#39;s some achievement. What I like most about Backstage is that it&#39;s almost completely unpretentious.<br><br>There&#39;s a big space which is currently pretty empty. The seats are comfortable (none of this milk crate BS) and there&#39;s free wifi. Coffee is locally roasted Palheta magic and the staff are very friendly. Extra care was taken when we ordered food as my better half was following a strict diet (for religious diet). We were even warned about the egg included in one of the salad sauces, unprompted.<br><br>The food is really nothing amazing but it&#39;s competently executed nonetheless. These days when I get a poached egg in Singapore that isn&#39;t completely overcooked I celebrate a little bit. Expectations, people.

text: After running some errands in this part of neighborhood or town, both my friend and I decide to have our Coffee or Tea break here. Â This Old Chang Kee occupies a few units at the Corner of some what Old Building which has been revamped. Â Apparently this OLD CHANG KEE is the FLAGSHIP Store for the EMPIRE Of Old Chang Kee.<br><br>YES Old Chang Kee is a CHAIN. Â YES it has A LONG Local History what nots. Â Thankfully by now in 2019, ALL Old Chang Kee locations are Halal Certified. Â That is definitely good in my books.<br><br>The service was OK here. Â At least, the staffs are attentive, welcoming and answered several questions that we asked. Â There are several seating areas that can accommodate big groups inside. Â It is air-conditioned though we opt to be seated near to a full blast fan that evening.<br><br>Now what about the Items being sold. Â I have tried their Curry Puffs numerous times, but for a sit down meal or snack, this is the first time for me at this location. Â They offer items such as Laksa, Rice dishes, and some desserts too.<br><br>Thankfully we managed to get a table on Sunday January 20th 2019 at about 17:50hrs ish. Â We opt for the so call Happy Hour Specials that they offer at this location DAILY. Â My friend opt to have the Curry Puff, while I opt for the Chicken Mushroom Curry Puff. Â <br><br>I cannot recall if my friend opt for Coffee or Teh Tarik. Â The Iced Lemon drink which needed to be charged with an additional cost of SG$1.50, they put it in the &#34;old school&#34; container or canister. Â (View the pictures of the beverages). Â The Iced Lemon Drink of some sort, apparently was overly too sweet for my liking. Â I wanted to ask the staff if they could rectify my drink, but since I was too tired, I just &#34;drink aka swallow it&#34;...<br><br>Overall, the Location is indeed prime. Â It is located just opposite of Selera Restaurant along this &#34;famous&#34; road called Mackenzie Road. Â Ambience are kind of old school. Â That is good in my books, but I wish they could like clear some of the cutlery that was scattered nearby.<br><br>While I am writing this, apparently their Old Chang Kee website is experiencing some technical issue, or was it my computer/laptop is a little cranky for today.<br><br>Will return when needed and perhaps my experience may differ. Â The nearest MRT is Little India MRT Station (NE7/DT12) EXIT A, which is about 3 to 5 minutes walk away. Â Left Old Chang Kee Coffee House @ REX about 18:50hrs ish.<br><br>It is opened during the following hours :<br><br>* Â Monday - Thursday : 11:00 - 21:00<br>* Â Friday - Saturday : 10:00 - 22:00<br>* Â Sunday &amp; PH : 10:00 - 21:00<br><br>Old Chang Kee Coffee House @ REX<br>19/21/23 Mackenzie Road, <br>#01-01<br>Singapore 228678<br>Tel : 6732 1665

Earl grey and black sesame kaya toast, and caramel latte', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': 'Earl grey and black sesame kaya toast, and caramel latte'}]
text: The line was really long, but there is a lady that walks down the line with an ipad to take orders. I recommend taking a picture of the menu before getting on the line so you can decide your order as you wait instead of deciding when she reaches you.<br><br>We ordered 2 kaya toasts - the black sesame and the earl grey, as well as one of their most popular drinks, the caramel latte. The black sesame kaya toast was stronger, whereas the early grey had a lighter flavor. The caramel latte was sweet, but not overly sugary. It&#39;s a great place to pick up snacks for a coffee break in between sampling all the hawker stands, a nice modern twist on the traditional kaya toast spread.

text: The drink stall was located at the second floor of the hawker centre, next to the well known lor mee stall. Order was taken by ipad. Besides the hainanese style of coffee(S$1.90) and kaya toast (S$2.50), the stall also offered drinks such as green tea latte and toasts with spreads such as matcha coconut and key lime creme.<br><br>Ordered Black Sesame Toast (S$3) and Rum &amp; Raisin Toast (S$3) which were packed into black paper bags. The black sesame version was distinct and flavourful on its own, while the rum &amp; raisin version was overwhelmed by the butter taste. The toasts lost its crispiness when cold.

text: As an American, I&#39;ve only ever had kaya from a can by Yeo&#39;s. Â Fresh kaya was something new to me, and I&#39;m a fan! Â Kaya with butter on toast... can&#39;t say I&#39;ve had that one before. Â The toast was a little over-saturated with butter and the bread was a little on the dry side, but nevertheless a decent taste of a legitimate Singaporean breakfast.<br><br>Ordering coffee here can be a bit confusing for a visitor - there&#39;s Kopi C, Kopi O, and all kinds of other Kopi that I still haven&#39;t gotten the hang of even after going a couple times. Â I&#39;d make sure to ask questions or bring a local just in case.

Food was just okay. The sliders were not good, I would not recommend. The arrabbiata pasta with shrimp was pretty tasty. The service was great in general, but server did not check on us. Got free drinks on a Wednesday because it was &#34;Ladies Night.&#34; Not a terrible experience, but not a &#34;must try&#34; in my opinion.

text: Had to double check website that this was the place as the stock pictures didn&#39;t match. This is on the bar/club area of Clarke quay and we were so glad we stumbled onto it. A two man band named &#34;dirty martini &#34; was playing..they appear to be regulars and were awesome. The ambience was very nice, pretty diverse crowd. I ordered a seafood pizza that was good, not great. My wife had a sandwich that looked really good..as is always the case if you miss happy hour in Singapore you can be prepared to be hit over the head with the prices, but the ambiance here was nice enough that you don&#39;t feel like you&#39;re being rooked.

text: Recently a cafe has opened at Toa Payoh central. The cafe is decorated in black color with industrial look. Although it was located away from the crowded part of the town, the cafe was packed when I arrived for brunch.<br><br>Menu was a simple 4 pieces of papers, held by a clip board. Order and payment was taken at the cashier. Currently only cash and NETS were accepted here, with NETS for order above $20. There was no GST and service charge here. Remember to help yourself to the iced water next to the counter.<br><br>Baked Escargots ($8)<br>Garlic butter &amp; paramesan cheese<br>The dish smelt garlicky when served. The deshelled juicy plump escargots soaked in the rich garlicky buttery sauce. Nice and yummy, although wished there was more paramesan cheese or some toast to dip the garlicky sauce with.<br><br>Mushroom Truffle Grantin ($16)<br>Elbows with shimeji, shitake and button mushrooms in truffle cream sauce and cheese<br>The truffle smellt and taste was a bit faint in this dish. The creamy sauce was rich and fully coated the mac and mushrooms in the dish, but felt that it was a bit too salty.<br><br>Overall the food was delicious and reasonable priced. Can&#39;t wait to come back to try other dishes too.

text: A homely neighbourhood cafe that lacks lustre but is comfortable enough for a meal at the end of a tiring weekday. While the ambience and service makes the cut, the price tag may be a little costly for the quality of food served. <br><br>The flat white was a disappointment. It lost points on first sight as the usual latte art one would expect on your typical cafe coffee was not present. The coffee lacked texture and was rather flat (the only thing not expected from a /flat/ white), and overall failed to pack a punch. <br><br>The duck confit was passable with a rather big portion of duck leg. While the meat paired with mashed potatoeswas nicely seasoned, it did not go well with the fruity sauce that resembled a familiar brand of jam. <br><br>The ribs were served on a plate that was slightly too small for convenient consumption while the fries were a bit on the oily side. The sauce did not appeal to me and was said to be on the losing end when compared with that of a certain cafe on upper Thomson. <br><br>Overall, a homely cafe that I&#39;ll visit again if I&#39;m in the vicinity and craving cafe food. A plus point is that they do offer a huge selection of food (pastas, brunch, sides etc) and are always ready to welcome you! :)

text: Found this spot yesterday on the way home. Cafe serving simple but tasty food. Ordered the linguini with clams--very good and nicely spiced. You receive menu at table and then order at the register. Â Friendly atmosphere -- only Western style restaurant surrounded by hawker food stalls (delicious, too!)
Had the royal truffle chocolate cake, and iced mocha. The mocha was ok, wish that the coffee taste was stronger. But the cake was delicious, I like how rich it was.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/q6Fs4nSR_nDEWKUYGEMRnw/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/mr-teh-terik-no-title?reviewid=ZYzDWQPe8VmF9M0a-5cfbg&select=q6Fs4nSR_nDEWKUYGEMRnw', 'altText': 'Photo of Mr Teh Terik - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': None}]
text: Mr Teh Terik started out as a Malay pulled milk tea kiosk at Far East Square. It has amassed a huge following with the office crowd who will queue relentlessly for a nice creamy and sweat milk tea with a frothy head. Then it became a chain teh terik cartel. It&#39;s amazing how a little drink could conquer the whole of Singapore. <br><br>Anyway, I&#39;ll always have mine at Far East Square. It&#39;s the atmosphere really. Of perching on little wooden stools and watching the Malay encik stretch the tea to cool it down. You don&#39;t get to watch this performance very often these days because they gotta be fast when serving the drinks.<br><br>There are tons of other drinks available. Hot favorites like Milo Dinosaur, Teh Cino and all the works. They also do sell some little snacks like walnut cookies and the Kuehs. Best way to keep yourself awake after lunch is to grab a Mr Teh Terik and a perk me up for tea.

text: Absolutely the coffee place for me! There are 4 blends of beans to choose for pour overs and the wide range of food makes it easy for friends with varied preferences to dine together. The place is delightfully designed to provide good space for singles as well as groups to gather. <br>And the choice of music is superb! I could read, write or have a decent conversation without having to raise my voice. <br>I&#39;ll definitely be back again!

Mochi pancakes - 4.75 stars<br>AMAZING. Best pancakes I&#39;ve had, ever. The pancakes themselves were moist and souffle-like but the best part was the mochi in the centre! The mochi had an incredible soft texture.<br><br>Big breakfast - 3.5 stars<br>Alright. The croquettes were dry and the potato probably wasn&#39;t even mashed. The scrambled eggs were flavourful and well-done. The rest was decent.<br><br>Oat milk flat white - 4 stars<br><br>Oat milk matcha latte - 4 stars<br>Slightly sweet.<br><br>I&#39;d go back just for the pancakes.

text: old hen kitchen now has a set lunch menu which is a really good deal! coffee, starter and main ranging from $15 - 19+. <br><br>they also allow substitutions, for extra $$, depending on the coffee and/or salad you get. <br><br>for eg: if you get their infamous cold brew instead of a flat white, you top up $2<br><br>i usually get the tomato soup (with pancetta!!), salmon soba! heard great things about the burger and the rice and pork belly usually runs out, so get their early if thats ur jam!<br><br>set lunch runs weekdays 12-230pm, excluding weekends and public holidays.

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/sA-lakuftCaM3vlsQKxBsA/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/lim-teck-guan-minced-pork-singapore?reviewid=rFX3Y1IeKfS_iRBFrpEqoQ&select=sA-lakuftCaM3vlsQKxBsA', 'altText': 'Photo of Lim Teck Guan Minced Pork - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: Lim Teck Guan Minced Pork has been around since I was a little girl. My grandmother used to buy the coin bak kwa for me whenever I visit her (yes, I&#39;m spoiled) and I still go back there to get my bak kwa for Chinese New Year every year. The store has not changed much since I knew it more than 20 years ago. It is still located in the old, cramped coffee shop and the only difference is that the middle-aged man my grandmother used to buy from is now an old man with white hair. The taste has remained the same too. While other bak kwa stores have tried to innovate by adding ingredients like pineapple, etc. to their bak kwa, Lim Teck Guan has stick to what they do best: creating traditional bak kwa that taste delicious.

Healthy cafÃ© with several chains across Singapore. The food is pretty good across the board - some favorites are the grain bowls and soup with bread. Pastas are ok as well though a bit too saucy. <br><br>If you want to reward yourself and be less healthy, would recommend the carrot cake which is amazing here.

text: From its classic Carrot cake to Middle Eastern inspired Sesame Tahini Cake, Cedele&#39;s organic cakes have always impressed with their light, delicate, exceptionally moist cake layers and this is no exception for Christmas log cakes. Blessed with a touch of zen, the Green Tea Yule Log ($8.50++) is such a wonderful and joyous thing to eat because of its unrivalled intense flavours and superbly fluffy green tea sponge. One bite simply tells it all-- a genuine matcha cake that in on par or even better than some in Japan.<br><br>The bonus lies in the smooth black sesame mousse, a much better match than red beans in my opinion. Â I&#39;m thankful to have found my BEST Matcha Roll Cake in Singapore.<br><br>Yuzu Pistachio logcake ($8.50++) is also another stunning creation where the nutty pistachio cream with plenty of grinded nuts are rolled in feathery light sponge and smeared with a tart citrusy cheese frosting. Organic unrefined sugar and grapeseed oil is used<br><br>Since it is now the festive season, we decided to try the all-day Christmas set menu which features a Grilled Turkey Bacon Roulade (or any other main course) + Christmas cake (or any chilled cakes) + coffee/tea at $35++. <br>Filled with basil pesto and red pepper, the turkey was well-seasoned but too chewy for my liking. It didn&#39;t help that the bacon lacked the crisp as well. But the sides and condiments were unique and tasty. The strawberry cranberry chutney had some plump cooked-down strawberries which added some juicy bites while the orange mash turned out to be sweet Kumara (New Zealand Sweet Potatoes)!! Lovely!

text: Starving in the MRT tunnels? Â looking for something that is fast and pseudo healthy? Â Check out Cedele. Â they have a great looking salad bar and they look huge! Â i did not go for this since the pastrami was calling my name. Â while this is not the normal pastrami that i am used to the... the chabatta bread was fresh and it tasted great. Â the service was fast, but i would go early cause all of the seats were full and people were waiting to sit down.

text: One of the better &#39;chain-style&#39; sandwich/soup/salad lunch spots I feel and is my go-to for whenever I feel like one or two of the aforementioned &#39;S&#39;s&#39; food items. They do good combo deals and you can help yourself to slice up yesterday&#39;s bread to accompany your soup - good idea. Lacking somewhat on atmosphere and vibe, but efficient service, plenty of choices and reasonably priced. <br><br>Haven&#39;t had any of the sweet stuff but granted, I&#39;ve been very tempted!

I love cedele for their cakes and the fact that they tend to promote the use of healthy ingredients. I know that their cakes probably still pack a whole lot of fat and sugar, but something about the way they roll makes me feel a little less guilty indulging in their towering slices of cakes. <br><br>They do one of the better carrot cakes in town. Topped with a smooth cream cheese frosting and packed with a generous serving of walnuts, it is a light a subtly sweet delight. I would have liked it a little denser but otherwise, its great! I&#39;m a big fan of their apple nut cheese cake too. Creamy cheese filling baked with a healthy serving of apples and nuts, giving the classic cheesecake an interesting twist. The cakes are not exactly cheap but worth every penny!

text: Cedele is probably one of the best places in Singapore to get a healthy and delicious meal. The restaurant prides itself in using fresh (and some organic) ingredients and all of their meals are healthy and free of trans fat. I come here a lot for their sandwiches, salads, breakfasts and cakes. <br><br>The best sandwich I think, is their veggie burger. Its really yummy and served with a beet chutney and a side salad. Their chocolate chip pancakes with cranberries are awesome. And the best part is that its served with REAL maple syrup, something hard to come by here in restaurants since its pretty expensive. <br><br>Their cakes are pretty good in general. Some are not as good as the others. Stick to the carrot cake and the chocolate banana cake. Breads are pretty good too, although a little bit expensive. Cupcakes and cookies aren&#39;t that great.

text: If you&#39;re craving for quality carrot cake, this is gonna be your haven.<br><br>Being a cake-o-holic, I have been to numerous bakeries and cafes around the world, but Cedele&#39;s desserts are second to almost none. The filling of said western carrot cake is palatable and crunchy, giving you that extra oomph as you bite into the soft, flavourful sponge. Topped with their special cold cream cheese and you have the perfect combination there. I also like to pair my cake with a hot beverage from their selection of teas - Chamomile Flowers being my favourite. Fragrant yet mild, it will invigorate your senses naturally without snatching the taste of your food.

Brunch / breakfast place in Fusionopolis. Dishes here come with egg and bread - you can choose to customize what you want in the plate or choose one of the many delicious pre-designed options. The food here tastes simple, healthy and good. <br><br>Would definitely recommend if you are looking for brunch / all-day-breakfast in the area.

text: I love this place simply for the fact that they make their own bread! As you walk in on your right, you see massive glass doors that lead into the kitchen. They have huge mixer bowls and all sorts of fancy, commercial grade baking equipment.<br><br>They sell their bread too, you can buy half a loaf for $4-5 or a whole loaf for $8.<br><br>They have free wifi, water, and baking magazines to browse through. You order at the counter and for sandwich items, you pick them up at the collection counter when your buzzer rings. For breakfast platters and other non-sandwich items, the staff will serve the food to you. Everything on their menu is nett priced and sounds and looks delicious!<br><br>1. Smoked Chicken Sandwich $8<br>Sandwiched in a very crispy country bread, are smoked chicken slices, long beans, mustard and melted cheese. The exterior of the bread is almost biscuit like and it does take some jaw muscle to bite in. The chicken slices are breast meat sort of, with the mustard and gooey melted cheese. The chicken tasted so good! The smoked flavour wasn&#39;t very evident, mostly covered up by the mustard. The long beans provided as crunch in the sandwich as well as the &#34;green&#34; for the sandwich.

text: A hidden gem (can I still say this? It&#39;s getting less and less hidden by the week!) in the currently low traffic Galaxis. Prices are very reasonable, and the coffee, breads, pancakes and dessert are fantastic. The sandwiches are decent but not outstanding.<br><br>The flat white in particular is executed skillfully, with a roast that isn&#39;t too acidic, topped off with smooth, creamy microfoam.<br><br>The wife enjoyed the sweet pepper vegetarian sandwich while my toddler who&#39;s been having a bad week cheerily gobbled down the classic scrambled eggs on toast (rye bread).<br><br>The butterscotch &amp; berries pancakes were soft and fluffy (get this!), and we couldn&#39;t get enough of the banana coconut bread pudding with gula melaka caramel and vanilla ice cream (get this too!)<br><br>Give the cookies a miss though - they were dry (we prefer soft and gooey) and were a tad too sweet.

text: The coffee here is pretty legendary. Its gentle flavor with a hint of nuttiness swaddles your tongue in warm dulcet tones, leaving you wanting more. Its the kind of coffee you&#39;d want to being home to meet your parents, and they wouldn&#39;t even ask all the normal embarrassing questions because its personality is just that charming. And then you&#39;d get married, it&#39;d be a simple wedding, with just a few guests, and you&#39;d wake up every morning wondering what you did to deserve such a good coffee. And then you&#39;ll have kids, and it&#39;d be the cutest little cappuccino ever, and your life will be perfect. And then one day, you&#39;ll wake up in horror to find that you&#39;ve drunk your little cappucino, brown stains still around your mouth as they drag you away to jail, kicking and screaming about how it was just one sip.<br><br>Oh and the bread pudding is pretty great too. More like that girl whos kind of cute with the funky hair that youd hang out with a few times but overall not too bad either.

Wow this place is NOT good. Ive been using Yelp since 2010 especially when I moved to a new continent to help eliminate trial and error. It&#39;s not often that I get disappointed by highly rated yelp and this is one of them rare instances.<br><br>We ordered the butterscotch &amp; berries pancake and a Norwegian. The pancake was average and the Norwegian was a disappointment. For me salad (came w the Norwegian) isn&#39;t just a garnish, it&#39;s food. The cucumber was seeded (ok) and hard (not ok), the hollandaise sauce that came w the poached egg was not impressive (watery). The Hokkaido bread was quite ok. The smoked salmon was v average. The grilled asparagus on the other hand was really good. Unfortunately that&#39;s forms only 5-10% of the dish.<br><br>The service was pretty good and people are Super friendly. Alight I&#39;ll bump them up to 3.

text: The pancakes were an absolute delight! I don&#39;t typically enjoy pancakes because they tend to be too sweet for my liking, but I tried the maple syrup with bacon (forgot the name) and it was not too sweet and not too salty! The bacon was also one of best I&#39;ve tried. <br><br>The sandwich was pretty normal, but the pork belly sandwich was interesting - it&#39;s like a Chinese and western fusion. <br><br>Pretty cool place, everyone working there seemed to be students, and I heard it&#39;s a relatively new place so many things were amateur eg paper plates and amateur waiters (we were asked to sit with a bunch of strangers on the same table before we hesitated and they gave us a table of our own). Not too expensive and the portion was alright.

5-stars for the price for value at Bread Yard. You can construct your own Egg&#39;s Benny for under $10 ($6 for poached eggs with Hollandaise sauce + $2-3 for either back bacon or smoked salmon). I would say the bacon is a better bet than the salmon--the latter was a bit salty the last time I had it. Sandwiches are also passable, while the mashed potatoes with gravy were delicious! Home-brewed iced team should be skipped.<br><br>Seating is often easy to come by, but the space is small. Bread Yard is tucked away inside one north, but it&#39;s a comfy place on a Sunday morning or afternoon. Take a walk around to catch a glimpse of the architectural work of the late Zaha Hadid!

text: I really wanted to like this place, but sadness. My coffee was burnt and undrinkable. My croissantwich was dry and room temperature. The staff seems pleasant though.

text: well steeped and hence rather steep?<br><br>as you all know by now, my go to caffeine has to be a cuppa coffee but this bespoke tea bar, like others rising, has definitely gotten my attention.<br>but don&#39;t worry, you flat whites, magics, cortados and blacks won&#39;t be so easily replaced:)<br><br>but the folks here are giving you a really tough fight!<br>professional tea brewing machines that looks good and delivers a punch!<br>definitely very well steeped and hence might be a little steep for most.<br><br>also available are refreshing tea cocktails, like what bartenders will concoct, sans alcohol for days where you would like to give your liver a break.<br>well crafted and steeped but obviously less steep!<br><br>i do like their location.<br>easy access from bugis mrt station, to pogo ex raid gym and convenient, plentiful shopfront parking is also available.<br>i do like their chillax interior dÃ©cor, bright and airy, filled with friendly and knowledgeable staff.<br>of course all these are irrelevant in times of takeout covid19:(<br>but yes, they do island wide delivery so you can still have some well steeped at slightly more steep.

The only thing about this place is that it&#39;s a bit out of the way (but still quite accessible by MRT) and there&#39;s a bit of walking.<br><br>It looks like this place was recently renovated as the seating is pretty clean and modern looking (marble tables?) and the bathrooms rival those of malls. Not to mention there&#39;s an escalator to access the second floor rather than just stairs.<br><br>First floor is a market for flowers, goods, produce, meats and etc.<br><br>Second floor is the magical food court! On the day I visited there was also a guy singing covers of famous English and Chinese songs which just made the dining experience all that much better.<br><br>As I was still stuffed from my early lunch at Maxwell, I only got to try two things here:<br><br>Lor Mee: I got the recommended order and added on fried shark nuggets. I mean it&#39;s fried shark meat? It was kinda just like eating fish...I couldn&#39;t really tell the difference. The gravy that accompanies the noodles is pretty good though. I think you definitely need to come hungry in order to finish a whole bowl by yourself as the gravy is pretty heavy.<br><br>MJ drink: wow who knew grass jelly and soy milk went so well together?! Why was this combination not in my life till now! And it&#39;s soo cheap too! I would get this all the time if I lived near here! I&#39;m so glad I managed to get here about half an hour before they close shop for the day.<br><br>I really really wanted to try the prawn mee by the escalators (looked like it was good as there was a line) but my stomach said there was no more space so next time for sure!

But I must say this Â place is a hit or miss for me. It&#39;s either super tender or dry and overly chewy pieces. <br><br>Since the portion sizes are small <br>I ordered the double meat portion steam/baked and bean sprouts. Total price 8 dollars.<br><br>Regarding lines, expect to waiting anywhere between 5 to 30 mins

text: Tiong Bahru Food Market...<br><br>Friday November 16th 2018. Â Time about 09:45hrs ish.<br><br>Definitely rich with Singapore History since 1951... Â Way back that time, it is known as Seng Poh Road Market... Â Found out about this Market since I follow religiously thru CNN or Travel Channel which featured the Late Anthony Bourdain.<br><br>Fast forward in 2018, I went here in order to run some errands. Â This area is more concentrated with the Chinese population, and majority of the stalls or vendors are run by the Chinese.<br><br>Managed to get a Sugar Cane Beverage with Ice ($1.70) from Wang Wang Sugar Cane stall #02-27. Â Decent and Doable Sugar Cane Beverage. Â At least I get to have a beverage and a place for me to seat for awhile while trying to enjoy my snacks which I have purchased prior.<br><br>Thankfully while I was there, this Market was indeed kept cleaned. Â It takes me about 10 to 15 minutes leisurely walk from the Tiong Bahru MRT Station. Â If you commute by the Public Transport i.e. the Bus, it will take about 3 to 5 minutes.<br><br>I know for a fact, there is ONLY 1 Malay stall or Food Vendor at Tiong Bahru Food Market. Â I do not mind returning and perhaps try what this Malay Stall has to offer.<br><br>In the middle aka &#34;Courtyard&#34;, at Level 1, there is a mini playground for the kids.<br><br>At Level 1, the outer perimeter of this Market, some vendor sell clothes or accessories, while the inner side aka inside consists of the normal market you can find across town, for fruits, flowers, vegetables, meats, poultry what nots.<br><br>You can find parking on the 3rd Level. Â As usual, in the mornings when I was here, this Market is indeed busy with other patrons alike, either for grocery shopping or having their Breakfast, thru Lunch.<br><br>Another Market for me to explore despite the lack of Halal vendors in this part of neighborhood. Â I know my bestie likes to have her coffee just across the road.<br><br>All in all, a doable Market. Â I will return and perhaps my review might differ. Â Furthermore, I am indeed impressed with the recent discovery of this Market with all the Social Media, its getting known for.

text: Although I think you have to catch this place on the right day when the weather is not so stifling, but after living in Singapore for a year now, my husband and I think this might be our personal most favorite hawker center to have visited (and we tend to visit a lot!). Â <br><br>Why does it get high marks from the Nings? Â Cleanliness, community feel and flow of space. Â <br><br>The place is super clean and seems cleaner than any other hawker center we have been too. Â It is off the beaten path a bit from touristy spots and has that community feel to it (although easily reached via subway and then a 5-10 minute walk). Â The center area of the hawker center is open and thus a bit more breezy, if you are lucky to have a day that is breezy. Â <br><br>When we were here a few weeks ago, we enjoyed many dishes, but the Laksa at stall #50 was my personal favorite. Â We both commented that this would be the hawker center we would bring future visitors too, for the cleanliness and flow make it a nicer experience for the uninitiated to absorb.

text: Having never been to a Hawker Center, Tiong Bahru was a great fist experience! If you&#39;ve read anything about hawker centers, they are monitored by the Singaporean government and ensure things such as cleanliness and food safety. This was evident all throughout the market. Everything was clean and safe to eat. The smells here are amazing! There is so much food, and so many people who come here for a good and very affordable meal. <br><br>There are a ton of food options- you could easily have all your meals here. Breakfast, lunch, dinner, dessert, there is something for everyone. I knew I wanted to try fried kuay teow and had a place in mind. It had a long line but that is the sign of a good place. We also ordered coffee from one stall, and a noodle dish from another stall. The food was fantastic! It was so flavorful, great use of spices. If you come to Singapore, Tiong Bahru is a must visit.

text: Following a renovation a few years back, this is easily the cleanest hawker centre in Singapore. Not as large as Â some others (like Maxwell, Chinatown Complex), but still includes some countrywide famous stalls, for shui kueh, Hainan chicken rice, roast meats, pig organ soup, hokkien mee, kway teow, etc..

text: First Yelp review in Singapore!! Had to check out this hawker center for breakfast right after checking in. Agreed with some of the other reviews, although it was 930 there were a lot of stalls that were not yet open for business. The one that I was disappointed most for was the Tiong Bahru Hainanese chicken and rice place...oh well, next time! <br><br>The famous lor me (a thick gravy with fat noodles, fish and egg) place was open though, and it was quite tasty (you can tell it&#39;s the right one bc it will have a line). It seemed like a more traditional place, so was worried that we would have trouble ordering - but it was so easy! I really liked how it was &#34;build your own&#34;, meaning once you got the dish you could add as much garlic, spicy peppers, green onions and vinegar as you wanted! I highly recommend all the accompaniments, the garlic and vinegar together were delicious.<br><br>We also tried the sugarcane juice (less sweet than I have tried at other tropical locations) and soyabean milk (slightly sweetened- was good!) at other stalls. <br><br>There are honestly a million things to try, and I didn&#39;t even recognize half of the dishes. I truly recommend this place, I think anyone can find at least one thing that they like and it&#39;s a fun experience.

Delicious hawker center!! The center was big and there were lots of food options on the second floor (the lower floor is where you can buy groceries and other home goods). I loved how it was super clean! <br>The chwee kueh and the fried carrot cake were by far my favorite! The chwee kueh is basically white kueh (semi sticky rice cake) with a generous layer of sauce that included some finely cut marinated veggies (å¬è), garlic, and other ingredients. It is a little bit oily but the sauce mixture is super flavorful. I tried the fried carrot cake because I&#39;ve seen it on some YouTube videos. I got the black fried carrot cake and it was very delicious: the carrot cakes were lathered with some egg, onions, and a sweet soy sauce. I also got the classic kaya toast, sugarcane water, kopi, and fish noodles, all of which were great and had traditional flavors. There are lots of seating but can be busy on the weekends! The time I went, there were also singers who performed live. For someone who has been to Singapore multiple times, I think this hawker center really satisfies my local food cravings and would totally recommend this place!

text: Tiong Bahru Food Market...<br><br>Friday November 16th 2018. Â Time about 09:45hrs ish.<br><br>Definitely rich with Singapore History since 1951... Â Way back that time, it is known as Seng Poh Road Market... Â Found out about this Market since I follow religiously thru CNN or Travel Channel which featured the Late Anthony Bourdain.<br><br>Fast forward in 2018, I went here in order to run some errands. Â This area is more concentrated with the Chinese population, and majority of the stalls or vendors are run by the Chinese.<br><br>Managed to get a Sugar Cane Beverage with Ice ($1.70) from Wang Wang Sugar Cane stall #02-27. Â Decent and Doable Sugar Cane Beverage. Â At least I get to have a beverage and a place for me to seat for awhile while trying to enjoy my snacks which I have purchased prior.<br><br>Thankfully while I was there, this Market was indeed kept cleaned. Â It takes me about 10 to 15 minutes leisurely walk from the Tiong Bahru MRT Station. Â If you commute by the Public Transport i.e. the Bus, it will take about 3 to 5 minutes.<br><br>I know for a fact, there is ONLY 1 Malay stall or Food Vendor at Tiong Bahru Food Market. Â I do not mind returning and perhaps try what this Malay Stall has to offer.<br><br>In the middle aka &#34;Courtyard&#34;, at Level 1, there is a mini playground for the kids.<br><br>At Level 1, the outer perimeter of this Market, some vendor sell clothes or accessories, while the inner side aka inside consists of the normal market you can find across town, for fruits, flowers, vegetables, meats, poultry what nots.<br><br>You can find parking on the 3rd Level. Â As usual, in the mornings when I was here, this Market is indeed busy with other patrons alike, either for grocery shopping or having their Breakfast, thru Lunch.<br><br>Another Market for me to explore despite the lack of Halal vendors in this part of neighborhood. Â I know my bestie likes to have her coffee just across the road.<br><br>All in all, a doable Market. Â I will return and perhaps my review might differ. Â Furthermore, I am indeed impressed with the recent discovery of this Market with all the Social Media, its getting known for.

text: I&#39;d eat here everyday if I could. <br><br>The chwee kueh and char kuey teow are easily within the top three anywhere in Singapore (or the entire region). <br><br>This is truly the modern day Singapore hawker center experience. Clean, simple, fresh, unpretentious, cheap and delicious! Locals will love it. Westerners will find the setting slightly uncomfortable (no A/C, no wait service, and not many amenities), but with an open mind and stomach one will walk away happy.

It is the Tiong Bahru Food Market so come with a appetite to try the various options available! Along the same row where the infamous Chwee Kuey is, you&#39;ll see a family with an old uncle dishing out awesome Char Kway Teow. It&#39;s not the best that I&#39;ve had but it&#39;s not bad as a dish to throw into the mix of having your calories smile from all the junk food. Back to Chwee Kuey, it&#39;s famous and the consistency of the Kuey is good but it&#39;s a tad too oily for me. The chili does have some kick so beware of the generous dollop. Other food to consider: Tiong Bahru Hainanese Chicken Rice &amp; Pork Innard Soup.

So far the best hawker centre ever with great food and hospitable vendors. I&#39;m just so glad that some of my favourite stall are not pushed aside after the renovation. <br><br>If you&#39;re coming here, I&#39;d recommend you to try out the following <br><br>- Beef noodle. It&#39;s quite obvious there as it is the only one, just walk towards the ban chang kueh stall deep inside the hawker centre<br><br>- Ban chang kueh beside beef noodle. It&#39;s really good and they are still doing it old-fashioned style which I personally prefer over Mr Bean&#39;s<br><br>- Nonya cake shop, located beside the kway chap stall. Near to beef noodle shop, try to spot the bright white neon sign. <br><br>- Tiong Bahru Pau. You would spot this easily as they&#39;re the only store to occupy two stalls at the left of the escalator. Queue early in the morning as they&#39;re usually sold out by 11 am. <br><br>- Prawn Noodle. It&#39;s located somewhat near the toilet, you&#39;d definitely spot it since it has a long queue<br><br>- Oyster Omelette beside the famous pork rice. The stall is manned by a very nice and chatty uncle. Although I couldn&#39;t really speak chinese, he still tries to relate to me, something I don&#39;t really experience in Singapore anymore. The food itself is really good too! Large, fresh oyster was used and the sambal was very fragrant. <br><br>- Char Kway Teow. This is the legendary stall, located to on the left when you come up from the escalator. Try to spot the orange store sign and long queue and voila you arrive at the correct stall. While it is very oily (by very I really do mean it), it has that wok hei that no food court has managed to replicate. It is truly a definitive mark of an experienced cook. <br><br>I&#39;m pretty sure there are many others stall that are just as good but I may not spot it yet. The above are just a snippet of my suggestion if you&#39;re crunched for time yet want to experience Tiong Bahru Market.

text: I came to the market for a Sunday lunch to try local food as suggested by some lovely locals. A wide range of local foods, good quality and very low prices. No service charge. No GST. Great place to visit. I definitely will come back here when I have a chance.

text: Definitely one of the better wet markets in SG. They have a good selection of vendors. Also, a few stalls for Australian and New Zealand meat too which was a pleasant surprise. <br><br>Tip: as with most wet markets, earlier you go the better the selection

For my 1st meal in Singapore my friend took me to Tiong Bahru Food Market &amp; Hawker Centre for some chicken rice. Â I got the small size which was a ton of food and very inexpensive. Â We split some bean sprouts which were tasty. Â It was on the crowded side but we had no trouble getting a seat. Â There are tons of options here and the surrounding area was very cute.

Excellent food court place in Singapore. I used to have breakfast at this place for $1.50 for the egg parata and $1 for the coffee.<br><br>If you are a tourist and are looking for a cheap place to eat, do yourself a favour and stay away from the trendy areas and eat at this place with the locals. Your wallet and taste buds will thank you.

My favourite market in singapore ! Good place to grab breakfast or lunch - lots of variety of hawker fare. And it always seem to be something new to try every time I am here. Good place to shop for fresh produce too !

I usually don&#39;t get to go out exploring during lunch so I never knew that there so much good food near my workplace! Luckily I&#39;ve been able to have a more flexible schedule this month, hence the opporturnity to explore the Tiong Bahru hipster area thoroughly <br><br>This is probably the most un-hipster place in the area but I LOVE IT because it has so many good stalls for cheap. You could come here everyday for a week and not get sick of it because there&#39;s just so much variety (tried and tested)<br><br>Heads up that most of the stalls are closed on monday (something to do with the slaughterhouses not being open).<br><br>So my favourites so far are the<br><br>- Zhong Yu Yuan Wei Wanton noodle for the ARMPIT CHARSIEW!<br>- Tau Kwa Pop store for the TAU KWA POP!<br>- Lee Hong Kee Roast for the ROASTED MEAT AND RICE! (chili was exceptionally awesome)<br>- Hu Ji Fishball Noodles for the FISHBALL NOODLES! (this stall only, there were 3-4 fishball noodle stalls in the area)<br>-Hwa Yuan Porridge for the FRIED PORK INTESTINES PORRIDGE!<br><br>Large, spacious, well-ventilated even in this awful haze and sheltered from the sun and rain. And you could have an entire meal for less than a main at any other place in the area. 5 stars for sure!
One of my favorite hawker centers in Singapore, especially for breakfast. Â Nice and open, airy atmosphere, and the peanut pancake lady has been open every time I have been there.

My first hawker experience and still one of my favorites. Â It&#39;s basically shaped like a giant triangle which makes it very easy to circle around and decide how you best want to spend your $3. Plenty of shade and breeze make it possible to dine comfortably.<br><br>It&#39;s cool that there&#39;s a wet market downstairs. Â It&#39;s not cool that it&#39;s a bit of a walk from the MRT.

text: Having come to the old Tiong Bahru Food Market &amp; Hawker Centre in the 90s, hand-in-hand with my mum, it does sadden me to see that it has gone and been replaced with a two-storey building (beautiful and modern and all), but I guess it did re-package the place and became more attractive to visitors, and juxtaposed with the new array of boutiques and cafÃ©s in the area, it still does stand out as the centrepiece of Tiong Bahru.<br><br>That aside, the prawn mee (the one that used to be rather mediocre until it was on a cooking show on Channel 8 and &#39;improved&#39;) is an always must-have, the Lor Mee with shark nuggets with the snaking queues (oh la la!) is the reason why I&#39;m always taking a 45-minute journey there (inclusive of walking), and the soy bean milk and bean curd vendor is the very same one from when TV was still black and white (though their prices have compounded, you know). <br><br>Adore this place, though not as much as Maxwell Food Centre or Old Airport Rd Hawker, but I do strongly recommend it for some of Singapore&#39;s best hawker fare!

photos: [{'src': 'https://s3-media0.fl.yelpcdn.com/bphoto/RCCb1UEp7Be6_GOt4oGHYg/300s.jpg', 'link': '/biz_photos/tiong-bahru-food-market-and-hawker-centre-singapore?reviewid=OhfvicVN9NcCCib-KvzzIw&select=RCCb1UEp7Be6_GOt4oGHYg', 'altText': 'Photo of Tiong Bahru Food Market & Hawker Centre - Singapore, Singapore', 'width': 300, 'height': 300, 'caption': ''}]
text: The rooftop EPS Parking (electronic parking) was the next best thing that happened to this place after it was rebuilt. <br><br>Ventilation is no longer a problem, though I missed crowding with everyone else at tables that circled a big tree in the open air at the old smokey and hot Tiong Bahru market, where everyone was having the same wet fried sotong hokkien mee or small styrofoam plate of black fried carrot cake on a banana leaf.<br><br>Gone is the old school 1960s backdrop but the food remain varied, cheap, and delicious. In one fell swoop, you can have the best chwee kueh in Singapore (Jian bo #02-05), great charcoal grilled rojak (right next to Jian bo), silky porridge (Hwa Yuen at #02-74), the famous Tiong Bahru lor mee (#02-80), value-for-money Hainanese curry rice with ridiculously crispy pork chop, fish cakes/balls in every shape and size imaginable, and one of the few bakeries (Sin Tong Nam #02-76) in Singapore that sells gai zai beng. New tenants like Joo Chiat beef (noodles) king and Deli &amp; Grill which serve refreshingly good western food have now also made it to my list. <br><br>Part of my weekend routine. Can&#39;t do without it!<br><br>And the wet market below the hawker centre is a major plus, get your grocery shopping for the week done at the same time (good fresh seafood stalls, my favourite place to buy a mountain of prawns).

text: A great place to find a smattering of Singapore&#39;s best, it is most well-known for its chwee kway and assortment of noodles. I really liked their wanton noodles and I heard the pig organ&#39;s soup is nice as well. Look out for the queues for each stall - it is a sign of their quality. That is very Singaporean, but a tried and tested method (most times).<br><br>Situated among the precious old estate of Tiong Bahru, the parking here is a nightmare on weekends but it is surprisingly not as crowded as some other food centres. The open air 2nd storey is also well-ventilated. Once done with the place, it is also good to take a stroll around the estate to admire the quaint houses in white.

My favourite market in singapore ! Good place to grab breakfast or lunch - lots of variety of hawker fare. And it always seem to be something new to try every time I am here. Good place to shop for fresh produce too !

I suppose you can&#39;t help but be biased towards the hawker centre that you spend most of your time at... and although when you come here often enough you will get bored of the food on offer, it&#39;s a great place to visit because there are so many good stalls, and there&#39;s also a stall turnover so you have new places to discover.<br><br>*deep breath*<br><br>Beef noodles. Char kway teow. Chee Kueh. Western food. Ayam Penyet. Tiong Bahru Pau. Roasted meats. Wonton mee with special char siew. Soya bean. Bak kut teh. Curry rice. Herbal soups. Fish porridge. Mee pok. Thai food. You can get all that at a very good level here.<br><br>*phew*<br><br>It&#39;s also quite airy and while can still be a bit warm, definitely isn&#39;t as bad as a lot of the older hawker centres around.<br><br>Lunch is definitely the time to go as more stalls are open, and also be warned that there isn&#39;t much variety in the way of vegetarian options.

Kovan rojak starts at $3, add $2 for jellyfish and $1 for century egg. So we went for the full set which was buried in punchy gravy and heaps of peanuts. Nearly everything was good,the century egg was surprisingly bouncy. However, the gravy needs more Assam/tamarind paste and lime juices to shine. This soggy Tau Pok and You Tiao (dough fritters) may appeal to those who likes them chewy but we prefer crunchy, well-toasted ones<br><br>Hence, its twin, the Tau Kwah Poh ($4) hit the right note. The dried cuttlefish, dough fritters and beancurd puff were grilled upon order and stayed crisp till the last bits. The mango, cucumber and pineapple lent a refreshing note when dipped into the chilli sauce and rojak shrimp paste. Thanks to the Kovan Rojak, there was ample leftover gravy to go with the tau kwa poh.

text: Cheap and good street food; not easy to get to via MRT. <br>The char kway teow stand is great; cheap and tasty.
One of my favorite hawker centers in Singapore, especially for breakfast. Â Nice and open, airy atmosphere, and the peanut pancake lady has been open every time I have been there.

A nice big hawker center in the heart of the trendy Tiong Bahru district. Big selection of stalls, though most are Chinese or seafood, not many Halal options. The shark nugget soup is a must try. I don&#39;t know what exactly was in the syrupy stuff, but super good. The pork rice is also very good. Prices are of course super low too.

Tiong Bahru Food Market is a fantastic place because it is so striking against the many cafes and edgey shopping spots around the area. I love it that I can get some popular local favourites here then go for drinks and dessert at a nearby cafe.<br><br>My picks at this place: Lor Mee with fried shark meat (try it if you aren&#39;t a fan of the usual braise variety, this is a good one!) and oyster omelette. I&#39;ve heard a lot of raves for the roasted meat stall so I might need to do a return. (It was a non-peak timing when I went so there weren&#39;t any queues and I didn&#39;t know where to start.) The kway chap stall is quite a good try if you&#39;re doing a run of local favourites here.

Modernised hawker centre missing a bit of soul<br><br>Don&#39;t get me wrong - I love Tiong Bahru! But for those who remember the really good hawkers who used to inhabit the old hawker centre, the new 3-storey building is a bit of a hit-and-miss. Sure, there&#39;s the great Jian Bo Shui Kueh (#02-05), Lor Mee (#02-80) and Yeap Seng Pau Tim (#02-71), alongside the Tiong Bahru Roast Meats and one really good fishball noodle stall, but other than that, good luck finding really outstanding dishes amongst the other 50+ stalls. Follow the long queues for the really good plates of food, and skip those that are there just to fill the tummy.<br><br>The market below has also lost a bit of its original intent, being more yuppified now and serving lots of expatriates with inflated prices. Beside a few vegetable stalls and the lovely old folks running three egg stalls, I barely venture there for groceries. Used to buy high quality clams at $5/kg, and these days you&#39;re lucky to get substandard &#34;Aussie&#34; clams for $10/kg. The fruit stalls especially sell their wares at about 20% markup at NTUC or elsewhere. Tekka or Chinatown markets are much more true to their market origins.

I have an itchy mouth, and it has become a habit to find a snack to go with any main course that I am having. In hawker terms, this usually means finding a dessert, some bubble tea, or even some you tiao as a kind of sinful wash-down. This fishball store offered a great alternative as an accompaniment to my lor mee. <br><br>It is, of course, famous for its fishballs. I told the uncle to serve me up a mix of his best dishes, which he did with some hearty recommendations. My friends and I tucked into a serving of fishballs, crispy &#34;tau ki&#34; skin and some ngoh hiong, or teochew spring rolls. I was not too impressed with the fishballs, as the skin was rather saggy. Ditto with the ngoh hiong. I felt that Old Chang Kee could do better! The crispy skin, however, was a rarity - I wish I had ordered more! Dipped into lime chilli sauce, it is really a shiok and sinful pairing.

Great hawker center. It is arranged in a big triangle on the second floor with open air and trees in the middle so it doesn&#39;t overheat at night like some of the other centers. The head chef of a $300/seat Japanese restaurant in Sydney, Tetsuya&#39;s, listed this as one of his favorite places to eat in Singapore.

text: another hawker center with tons of eating options.. we came with a couple other people and pretty much ordered everything <br><br>bbq pork.. duck rice.. roasted chicken rice.. fish ball soup... noodles with shark meat.. noodle soups.. oyster omelette.. bak kut teh with noodles.. laksa.. char kway teow.. and a bunch of fruity desserts.. <br><br>you gotta come here if you like cheap delicious food..

Solid selection of stuff. I&#39;ve had better chicken rice than what I tried here- the chicken was quite dry, although the sauce was good. I also tried the chwee kueh (is that how you spell it?). It&#39;s honestly hard for me to describe what it is. I know it&#39;s made out of rice flour, and the texture is sort of gelatinous, and it&#39;s topped with pickled veggies? Honestly, It&#39;s completely different than anything I&#39;ve ever tried before. If you&#39;ve had banh cuon in Hanoi, it&#39;s fairly similar, although I think I prefer the way the Singaporeans do it.
